									"blurb" : "It was a good weekend for the White Sox in Boston, completed by Sunday's victory at Fenway Park before 36,998. White Sox starter Reynaldo Lopez allowed two runs (one earned) on six hits over 6 1/3 innings, outdueling Rick Porcello, who allowed three runs (two earned) in six innings. Chicago jumped out to an early lead on a Jose Abreu RBI double and added some insurance with a Daniel Palka two-run double. The Red Sox struggled to bring home runners in scoring position.",
									"body" : "<p>BOSTON -- It was a good weekend for the White Sox in Boston, completed by Sunday's 5-2 victory over the Red Sox at Fenway Park before 36,998. But it was a better 10 days overall for Rick Renteria's 22-41 squad.</p><p>The White Sox took a home series last weekend from Milwaukee, the National League Central leaders, and then split four games in Minnesota. They won the series from the Red Sox, outplaying a team sitting 22 games over .500 on Sunday afternoon and held Boston to six runs in total while scoring eight. The team's 6-4 record comes on the heels of being swept in Cleveland, followed by a players-only meeting.</p><p>\"Well, yeah, we had our meeting, but it was private between the guys,\" said White Sox reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-275E1DD943030C5B5FB9D\">Joakim Soria</span>, who saved all four victories on this road trip, including a scoreless ninth Sunday. \"Whatever is working we are going to keep doing it. The chemistry of the team is a little bit better.</p><p>\"Guys just are enjoying the game. They are coming to the field expecting to win. It's pretty good lately. You have great chemistry on the team and it reflects on the field.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9FA7F2E5B8A9875EE0B94\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139791683\">Video: CWS@BOS: Abreu rips a wall-ball RBI double in the 1st</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-212DE831C266CB42802BC\">Dylan Covey</span> pitched six scoreless innings Friday, topping former White Sox ace <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E09A5C6B0D7BB2C4551B6\">Chris Sale</span> in a 1-0 final, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3055644DABCB711618A81\">Carlos Rodon</span> followed with a solid 2018 debut in Saturday's setback after rehabbing his way back from arthroscopic shoulder surgery in September. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D9DAA42490BC0B227599\">Reynaldo Lopez</span> completed that starting pitching trifecta, allowing one earned run on six hits over 6 1/3 innings Sunday, while striking out six and walking three.</p><p>Over his two starts on the road this week, Lopez yielded seven hits in 13 1/3 innings. White Sox pitching as a whole held the Red Sox to 1-for-26 with runners in scoring position, and 1-for-11 on Sunday.</p><p>\"We are playing good. We are doing the little things, and the hitters are doing their job,\" said Lopez through interpreter Billy Russo. \"The pitching staff is doing their job, too. When you as a team can do the little things and can work as a team with all the parts integrated to the things that you need to do, you will have good results, and I think that's what we've been doing the last couple of weeks.\"</p><p>\"Our pitching did awesome, and every game was close and low scoring,\" White Sox right fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-760E83788F63C48DDF7AD\">Daniel Palka</span> said. \"In that Game 1, we were like, 'Our pitching is going to be there, so play good defense and get enough runs and we've got a chance.'\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E6D877BB9EC2A8D9D039C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140010583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson draws a bases-loaded walk</a></span></p><p>In both the third and sixth innings, the White Sox scored runs without getting a hit off of Boston starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ACEB6A8D4FD80CC07ECA7\">Rick Porcello</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91AD363841ED76C7060A7\">Tim Anderson</span> walked with the bases loaded to force home a run in the third. In the sixth, Anderson walked, was bunted to second by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-68CA80F95ED6B4A6A77A8\">Charlie Tilson</span> and scored from second on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-55F7368BE04958F4173A0\">Trayce Thompson</span>'s ground out. First baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-64CD4F91E838690A6C98F\">Mitch Moreland</span> flipped to Porcello covering on the Thompson play, but when Porcello slipped and collided with first-base umpire Quinn Wolcott, Anderson was able to beat the throw home.</p><p>\"I kind of figured it was way away from first, and I knew he had a long run,\" Anderson said. \"I saw him go down. I was busting it. And I was able to get in and score.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-460084A221436934CEBBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140337783\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson scores from second on a groundout</a></span></p><p>\"When he's on the bases, he can do some pretty special things,\" White Sox manager Rick Renteria said. \"He was able to take advantage of speed and the situation and scored the run. Great heads-up play by him.\"</p><p>Palka completed the scoring in the ninth, connecting on a 0-2 pitch from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F3A93356640B35066AB0\">Matt Barnes</span> for a two-run double, giving him 22 RBIs on the season.</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Fielding gem:</b> Anderson and first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F352FC9E205DF80BBB9A1\">Matt Davidson</span> combined to take a hit away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CC4A8F62FBB98029F49BA\">Xander Bogaerts</span> to end the fifth and, in the process, took a run away from the Red Sox to maintain the lead. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C784204BF18430ED5BB4\">Sandy Leon</span> on third and two outs, Bogaerts hit a grounder in the hole gloved by Anderson, who threw across his body to a stretching Davidson to nab a sliding Bogaerts.</p><p>\"I just remember getting an out and getting excited,\" Anderson said. \"It was a good play in a key situation. Was able to get out of the inning and scratch out a win.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-56D431904961877F1F5BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140276183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson delivers jump throw to end the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>That was close:</b> The Red Sox sent 13 men to the plate combined over the sixth and seventh innings and scored a grand total of one unearned run. Lopez induced a routine pop fly to Anderson from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F1B435C49B4E098FEC386\">Blake Swihart</span> to strand the bases loaded in the sixth, and after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-549ED10CFB146448E9CBD\">Yoan Moncada</span> fielding error allowed a run to score in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FC81372023C05244CC0BE\">Brock Holt</span>'s fly out to center against <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A01CA209CC332D81E0489\">Jace Fry</span> stranded the bases loaded once again.</p><p>\"Today I was able to control the situation and slow the game down and be able to be effective in that situation,\" said Lopez of the sixth.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-412467956BE5CDFFAF4B2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140416583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Lopez escapes a bases-loaded jam in the 6th</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Lopez has held opponents to seven hits in the last 45 at-bats. He is limiting opponents to a .215 average this season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The Sunday awad for hard-hitting goes to Palka, with exit velocities of 113.7, 112.8, 116.4 and 107.1 mph in four of his five at-bats, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-23730D7C7D9AA9F7C5E85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>. Palka picked up two doubles in those four at-bats.</p><p>His first three connections made Palka just the third player this season to have a game with three 112+ mph batted balls in one game, joining Davidson on Opening Day and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F7330F5A16C0560ED6CA4\">Nelson Cruz</span>.</p><p>Four 107+ mph batted balls in one game ties him with Cruz (April 28) for the most hit by any player this season. The only players to previously do this before 2018 since Statcast\u2122 began tracking data in 2015 were <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E673EA12C41DA76D45188\">Tommy Joseph</span> (May 24, 2016), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2836C14E0570C3E685693\">Wilson Ramos</span> (Aug. 1, 2016) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-234DA65DCF4B07EE7FAB9\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> (May 7, 2015).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5DAE442BC99D96A8B96BF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140873483\">Video: CWS@BOS: Palka lines a 2-out, 2-run double in the 9th</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It just goes along with what we wanted to start out in the month of June. We knew we had a bunch of good teams coming up, and we had a game plan to refresh ourselves and start out new.\" -- <i>Palka</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />The White Sox challenged a ninth-inning grounder hit by Moncada, which ricocheted off of Barnes, but was ruled an out at first after Barnes recovered. The call was overturned by video replay, giving Moncada two hits for the day.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C91ACC313F379CD2B52B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140823183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Moncada reaches first safely after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The White Sox open a seven-game homestand and a four-game set against the Indians with a first pitch of 7:10 p.m. CT Monday at Guaranteed Rate Field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3AF0395C10670B84922A4\">Lucas Giolito</span> gets the call for the White Sox, with his 39 walks ranking among the Major League leaders. The White Sox have scored one run or less in seven of Giolito's 12 starts, including zero runs five times. Cleveland will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1991AA23E3C62AA661FAC\">Carlos Carrasco</span>.</p>",

									"body" : "<p>BOSTON -- It was a good weekend for the White Sox in Boston, completed by Sunday's 5-2 victory over the Red Sox at Fenway Park before 36,998. But it was a better 10 days overall for Rick Renteria's 22-41 squad.</p><p>The White Sox took a home series last weekend from Milwaukee, the National League Central leaders, and then split four games in Minnesota. They won the series from the Red Sox, outplaying a team sitting 22 games over .500 on Sunday afternoon and held Boston to six runs in total while scoring eight. The team's 6-4 record comes on the heels of being swept in Cleveland, followed by a players-only meeting.</p><p>\"Well, yeah, we had our meeting, but it was private between the guys,\" said White Sox reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-275E1DD943030C5B5FB9D\">Joakim Soria</span>, who saved all four victories on this road trip, including a scoreless ninth Sunday. \"Whatever is working we are going to keep doing it. The chemistry of the team is a little bit better.</p><p>\"Guys just are enjoying the game. They are coming to the field expecting to win. It's pretty good lately. You have great chemistry on the team and it reflects on the field.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9FA7F2E5B8A9875EE0B94\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139791683\">Video: CWS@BOS: Abreu rips a wall-ball RBI double in the 1st</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-212DE831C266CB42802BC\">Dylan Covey</span> pitched six scoreless innings Friday, topping former White Sox ace <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E09A5C6B0D7BB2C4551B6\">Chris Sale</span> in a 1-0 final, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3055644DABCB711618A81\">Carlos Rodon</span> followed with a solid 2018 debut in Saturday's setback after rehabbing his way back from arthroscopic shoulder surgery in September. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D9DAA42490BC0B227599\">Reynaldo Lopez</span> completed that starting pitching trifecta, allowing one earned run on six hits over 6 1/3 innings Sunday, while striking out six and walking three.</p><p>Over his two starts on the road this week, Lopez yielded seven hits in 13 1/3 innings. White Sox pitching as a whole held the Red Sox to 1-for-26 with runners in scoring position, and 1-for-11 on Sunday.</p><p>\"We are playing good. We are doing the little things, and the hitters are doing their job,\" said Lopez through interpreter Billy Russo. \"The pitching staff is doing their job, too. When you as a team can do the little things and can work as a team with all the parts integrated to the things that you need to do, you will have good results, and I think that's what we've been doing the last couple of weeks.\"</p><p>\"Our pitching did awesome, and every game was close and low scoring,\" White Sox right fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-760E83788F63C48DDF7AD\">Daniel Palka</span> said. \"In that Game 1, we were like, 'Our pitching is going to be there, so play good defense and get enough runs and we've got a chance.'\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E6D877BB9EC2A8D9D039C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140010583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson draws a bases-loaded walk</a></span></p><p>In both the third and sixth innings, the White Sox scored runs without getting a hit off of Boston starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ACEB6A8D4FD80CC07ECA7\">Rick Porcello</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91AD363841ED76C7060A7\">Tim Anderson</span> walked with the bases loaded to force home a run in the third. In the sixth, Anderson walked, was bunted to second by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-68CA80F95ED6B4A6A77A8\">Charlie Tilson</span> and scored from second on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-55F7368BE04958F4173A0\">Trayce Thompson</span>'s ground out. First baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-64CD4F91E838690A6C98F\">Mitch Moreland</span> flipped to Porcello covering on the Thompson play, but when Porcello slipped and collided with first-base umpire Quinn Wolcott, Anderson was able to beat the throw home.</p><p>\"I kind of figured it was way away from first, and I knew he had a long run,\" Anderson said. \"I saw him go down. I was busting it. And I was able to get in and score.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-460084A221436934CEBBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140337783\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson scores from second on a groundout</a></span></p><p>\"When he's on the bases, he can do some pretty special things,\" White Sox manager Rick Renteria said. \"He was able to take advantage of speed and the situation and scored the run. Great heads-up play by him.\"</p><p>Palka completed the scoring in the ninth, connecting on a 0-2 pitch from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F3A93356640B35066AB0\">Matt Barnes</span> for a two-run double, giving him 22 RBIs on the season.</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Fielding gem:</b> Anderson and first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F352FC9E205DF80BBB9A1\">Matt Davidson</span> combined to take a hit away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CC4A8F62FBB98029F49BA\">Xander Bogaerts</span> to end the fifth and, in the process, took a run away from the Red Sox to maintain the lead. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C784204BF18430ED5BB4\">Sandy Leon</span> on third and two outs, Bogaerts hit a grounder in the hole gloved by Anderson, who threw across his body to a stretching Davidson to nab a sliding Bogaerts.</p><p>\"I just remember getting an out and getting excited,\" Anderson said. \"It was a good play in a key situation. Was able to get out of the inning and scratch out a win.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-56D431904961877F1F5BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140276183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson delivers jump throw to end the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>That was close:</b> The Red Sox sent 13 men to the plate combined over the sixth and seventh innings and scored a grand total of one unearned run. Lopez induced a routine pop fly to Anderson from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F1B435C49B4E098FEC386\">Blake Swihart</span> to strand the bases loaded in the sixth, and after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-549ED10CFB146448E9CBD\">Yoan Moncada</span> fielding error allowed a run to score in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FC81372023C05244CC0BE\">Brock Holt</span>'s fly out to center against <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A01CA209CC332D81E0489\">Jace Fry</span> stranded the bases loaded once again.</p><p>\"Today I was able to control the situation and slow the game down and be able to be effective in that situation,\" said Lopez of the sixth.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-412467956BE5CDFFAF4B2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140416583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Lopez escapes a bases-loaded jam in the 6th</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Lopez has held opponents to seven hits in the last 45 at-bats. He is limiting opponents to a .215 average this season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The Sunday awad for hard-hitting goes to Palka, with exit velocities of 113.7, 112.8, 116.4 and 107.1 mph in four of his five at-bats, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-23730D7C7D9AA9F7C5E85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>. Palka picked up two doubles in those four at-bats.</p><p>His first three connections made Palka just the third player this season to have a game with three 112+ mph batted balls in one game, joining Davidson on Opening Day and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F7330F5A16C0560ED6CA4\">Nelson Cruz</span>.</p><p>Four 107+ mph batted balls in one game ties him with Cruz (April 28) for the most hit by any player this season. The only players to previously do this before 2018 since Statcast\u2122 began tracking data in 2015 were <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E673EA12C41DA76D45188\">Tommy Joseph</span> (May 24, 2016), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2836C14E0570C3E685693\">Wilson Ramos</span> (Aug. 1, 2016) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-234DA65DCF4B07EE7FAB9\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> (May 7, 2015).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5DAE442BC99D96A8B96BF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140873483\">Video: CWS@BOS: Palka lines a 2-out, 2-run double in the 9th</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It just goes along with what we wanted to start out in the month of June. We knew we had a bunch of good teams coming up, and we had a game plan to refresh ourselves and start out new.\" -- <i>Palka</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />The White Sox challenged a ninth-inning grounder hit by Moncada, which ricocheted off of Barnes, but was ruled an out at first after Barnes recovered. The call was overturned by video replay, giving Moncada two hits for the day.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C91ACC313F379CD2B52B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140823183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Moncada reaches first safely after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The White Sox open a seven-game homestand and a four-game set against the Indians with a first pitch of 7:10 p.m. CT Monday at Guaranteed Rate Field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3AF0395C10670B84922A4\">Lucas Giolito</span> gets the call for the White Sox, with his 39 walks ranking among the Major League leaders. The White Sox have scored one run or less in seven of Giolito's 12 starts, including zero runs five times. Cleveland will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1991AA23E3C62AA661FAC\">Carlos Carrasco</span>.</p>",

									"body" : "<p>BOSTON -- It was a good weekend for the White Sox in Boston, completed by Sunday's 5-2 victory over the Red Sox at Fenway Park before 36,998. But it was a better 10 days overall for Rick Renteria's 22-41 squad.</p><p>The White Sox took a home series last weekend from Milwaukee, the National League Central leaders, and then split four games in Minnesota. They won the series from the Red Sox, outplaying a team sitting 22 games over .500 on Sunday afternoon and held Boston to six runs in total while scoring eight. The team's 6-4 record comes on the heels of being swept in Cleveland, followed by a players-only meeting.</p><p>\"Well, yeah, we had our meeting, but it was private between the guys,\" said White Sox reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-275E1DD943030C5B5FB9D\">Joakim Soria</span>, who saved all four victories on this road trip, including a scoreless ninth Sunday. \"Whatever is working we are going to keep doing it. The chemistry of the team is a little bit better.</p><p>\"Guys just are enjoying the game. They are coming to the field expecting to win. It's pretty good lately. You have great chemistry on the team and it reflects on the field.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9FA7F2E5B8A9875EE0B94\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139791683\">Video: CWS@BOS: Abreu rips a wall-ball RBI double in the 1st</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-212DE831C266CB42802BC\">Dylan Covey</span> pitched six scoreless innings Friday, topping former White Sox ace <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E09A5C6B0D7BB2C4551B6\">Chris Sale</span> in a 1-0 final, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3055644DABCB711618A81\">Carlos Rodon</span> followed with a solid 2018 debut in Saturday's setback after rehabbing his way back from arthroscopic shoulder surgery in September. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D9DAA42490BC0B227599\">Reynaldo Lopez</span> completed that starting pitching trifecta, allowing one earned run on six hits over 6 1/3 innings Sunday, while striking out six and walking three.</p><p>Over his two starts on the road this week, Lopez yielded seven hits in 13 1/3 innings. White Sox pitching as a whole held the Red Sox to 1-for-26 with runners in scoring position, and 1-for-11 on Sunday.</p><p>\"We are playing good. We are doing the little things, and the hitters are doing their job,\" said Lopez through interpreter Billy Russo. \"The pitching staff is doing their job, too. When you as a team can do the little things and can work as a team with all the parts integrated to the things that you need to do, you will have good results, and I think that's what we've been doing the last couple of weeks.\"</p><p>\"Our pitching did awesome, and every game was close and low scoring,\" White Sox right fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-760E83788F63C48DDF7AD\">Daniel Palka</span> said. \"In that Game 1, we were like, 'Our pitching is going to be there, so play good defense and get enough runs and we've got a chance.'\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E6D877BB9EC2A8D9D039C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140010583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson draws a bases-loaded walk</a></span></p><p>In both the third and sixth innings, the White Sox scored runs without getting a hit off of Boston starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ACEB6A8D4FD80CC07ECA7\">Rick Porcello</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91AD363841ED76C7060A7\">Tim Anderson</span> walked with the bases loaded to force home a run in the third. In the sixth, Anderson walked, was bunted to second by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-68CA80F95ED6B4A6A77A8\">Charlie Tilson</span> and scored from second on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-55F7368BE04958F4173A0\">Trayce Thompson</span>'s ground out. First baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-64CD4F91E838690A6C98F\">Mitch Moreland</span> flipped to Porcello covering on the Thompson play, but when Porcello slipped and collided with first-base umpire Quinn Wolcott, Anderson was able to beat the throw home.</p><p>\"I kind of figured it was way away from first, and I knew he had a long run,\" Anderson said. \"I saw him go down. I was busting it. And I was able to get in and score.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-460084A221436934CEBBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140337783\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson scores from second on a groundout</a></span></p><p>\"When he's on the bases, he can do some pretty special things,\" White Sox manager Rick Renteria said. \"He was able to take advantage of speed and the situation and scored the run. Great heads-up play by him.\"</p><p>Palka completed the scoring in the ninth, connecting on a 0-2 pitch from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F3A93356640B35066AB0\">Matt Barnes</span> for a two-run double, giving him 22 RBIs on the season.</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Fielding gem:</b> Anderson and first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F352FC9E205DF80BBB9A1\">Matt Davidson</span> combined to take a hit away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CC4A8F62FBB98029F49BA\">Xander Bogaerts</span> to end the fifth and, in the process, took a run away from the Red Sox to maintain the lead. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C784204BF18430ED5BB4\">Sandy Leon</span> on third and two outs, Bogaerts hit a grounder in the hole gloved by Anderson, who threw across his body to a stretching Davidson to nab a sliding Bogaerts.</p><p>\"I just remember getting an out and getting excited,\" Anderson said. \"It was a good play in a key situation. Was able to get out of the inning and scratch out a win.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-56D431904961877F1F5BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140276183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Anderson delivers jump throw to end the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>That was close:</b> The Red Sox sent 13 men to the plate combined over the sixth and seventh innings and scored a grand total of one unearned run. Lopez induced a routine pop fly to Anderson from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F1B435C49B4E098FEC386\">Blake Swihart</span> to strand the bases loaded in the sixth, and after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-549ED10CFB146448E9CBD\">Yoan Moncada</span> fielding error allowed a run to score in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FC81372023C05244CC0BE\">Brock Holt</span>'s fly out to center against <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A01CA209CC332D81E0489\">Jace Fry</span> stranded the bases loaded once again.</p><p>\"Today I was able to control the situation and slow the game down and be able to be effective in that situation,\" said Lopez of the sixth.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-412467956BE5CDFFAF4B2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140416583\">Video: CWS@BOS: Lopez escapes a bases-loaded jam in the 6th</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Lopez has held opponents to seven hits in the last 45 at-bats. He is limiting opponents to a .215 average this season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The Sunday awad for hard-hitting goes to Palka, with exit velocities of 113.7, 112.8, 116.4 and 107.1 mph in four of his five at-bats, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-23730D7C7D9AA9F7C5E85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>. Palka picked up two doubles in those four at-bats.</p><p>His first three connections made Palka just the third player this season to have a game with three 112+ mph batted balls in one game, joining Davidson on Opening Day and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F7330F5A16C0560ED6CA4\">Nelson Cruz</span>.</p><p>Four 107+ mph batted balls in one game ties him with Cruz (April 28) for the most hit by any player this season. The only players to previously do this before 2018 since Statcast\u2122 began tracking data in 2015 were <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E673EA12C41DA76D45188\">Tommy Joseph</span> (May 24, 2016), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2836C14E0570C3E685693\">Wilson Ramos</span> (Aug. 1, 2016) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-234DA65DCF4B07EE7FAB9\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> (May 7, 2015).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5DAE442BC99D96A8B96BF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140873483\">Video: CWS@BOS: Palka lines a 2-out, 2-run double in the 9th</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It just goes along with what we wanted to start out in the month of June. We knew we had a bunch of good teams coming up, and we had a game plan to refresh ourselves and start out new.\" -- <i>Palka</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />The White Sox challenged a ninth-inning grounder hit by Moncada, which ricocheted off of Barnes, but was ruled an out at first after Barnes recovered. The call was overturned by video replay, giving Moncada two hits for the day.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C91ACC313F379CD2B52B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140823183\">Video: CWS@BOS: Moncada reaches first safely after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The White Sox open a seven-game homestand and a four-game set against the Indians with a first pitch of 7:10 p.m. CT Monday at Guaranteed Rate Field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3AF0395C10670B84922A4\">Lucas Giolito</span> gets the call for the White Sox, with his 39 walks ranking among the Major League leaders. The White Sox have scored one run or less in seven of Giolito's 12 starts, including zero runs five times. Cleveland will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1991AA23E3C62AA661FAC\">Carlos Carrasco</span>.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Curtis Granderson set a new career high with six RBIs, part of a 4-for-5 day in which he fell a triple shy of the cycle as Toronto completed a four-game sweep of the Orioles on Sunday at Rogers Centre. Teoscar Hernandez hit his 10th homer of the season, and Kevin Pillar and Kendrys Morales also went deep for Toronto, which rapped across 19 hits. Alex Cobb struggled for Baltimore, allowing nine earned runs over 3 2/3 innings of work to take the loss.",
									"body" : "<p>TORONTO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C0B2BEAA6DFD31524EAB\">Curtis Granderson</span> has been around the Major Leagues for 15 years, but apparently it's never too late for a career first.</p><p>Granderson set a new career high with six RBIs as part of a 4-for-5 day in which he fell a triple shy of the cycle in Toronto's 13-3 victory over the Orioles on Sunday at Rogers Centre. The veteran outfielder finished with a three-run homer, two run-scoring doubles and a walk in what will easily be considered his best game since joining the Blue Jays as a free agent during the offseason.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C23474240906E85A9AF97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140290483\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson doubles for his 6th RBI of game</a></span></p><p>Toronto also received home runs from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1CD29147D64EBEEBB8F9F\">Teoscar Hernandez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F4B9964747E6117A18D9E\">Kendrys Morales</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9537EB58E6571B5018A88\">Kevin Pillar</span> in the lopsided victory. Every member of the Blue Jays' starting lineup reached base at least once and seven players had multiple hits, while the 13 runs were two shy of the club's highest total this season as the Blue Jays set a new season high with four homers in the same game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8E0C32852C68A118C76A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140296083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Hernandez rips a 2-run homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>\"A huge day,\" Blue Jays manager John Gibbons said after his team matched its season high with a four-game winning streak. \"Grandy had been scuffling a little bit, there's no doubt. A couple of days ago I was sitting next to [bench coach] DeMarlo Hale, I said, 'You know what we need? Somebody, one guy, to just have a big game. A monster-type game.' You see that every now and then, it carries you a little bit. That's what he did today. Set the tone.\"</p><p>Granderson previously had five RBIs in a game seven times. He last accomplished the feat on April 22, 2016, as part of a two-homer game against Atlanta when Granderson was still with the Mets. This was Granderson's eighth multi-hit game of the season for Toronto and his first since May 27 at Philadelphia. The four hits were a season high, surpassing the three he had vs. Boston on April 24.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-38928BB57CE50F1C31FAD\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141869183\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson and Gibbons on 13-3 win</a></span></p><p>\"It's pretty cool to be able to do that and obviously help the team win,\" Granderson said. \"The cool thing about this game is, every time you step on that field, something could happen that's never happened before and sure enough that ended up happening today for me.\"</p><p>The Blue Jays finished the Orioles series with 56 hits, which is tied for the second-most in franchise history for a four-game set. Toronto had at least 12 hits in each of the four contests, but the series finale was the only game in which the Blue Jays scored more than five runs. The offensive outburst secured the club's second series sweep of three or more games this season and the first since a three-game set vs. Kansas City from April 17-18.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-66285580C871C449AA2AF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140335583\">Video: BAL@TOR: Pillar crushes a solo home run to center</a></span></p><p>Toronto did almost all of its damage against Orioles right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E3D3B4D9DE79219AF61B5\">Alex Cobb</span>, who was charged with nine runs on 11 hits and a walk while striking out five over 3 2/3 innings. Cobb's latest setback saw his ERA rise to 7.23, 11 starts into a four-year deal worth $57 million that he signed this spring. The nine earned runs matched Cobb's career high, which was set on June 13, 2017, vs. the Mariners.</p><p>Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E44A9E703B514FE9DCF8F\">Marco Estrada</span> picked up the easy victory for the Blue Jays as he continued Toronto's recent string of success in the rotation. Estrada allowed two runs while scattering four hits and a walk while striking out nine over six-plus innings. Toronto starters have now tossed seven consecutive quality starts and they have not allowed more than two earned runs in any of those outings. Opponents are batting .173 (27-for-156) against them over that stretch.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6745E57514242D6D69782\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141809083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Estrada strikes out 9 over 6-plus frames in win</a></span></p><p>\"Oh man, I'm going to have to knock on wood now,\" Estrada said when informed of the recent run. \"We're pitching great. We're pitching the way we're supposed to be. We have a really good rotation and it's showing as of late. It's unfortunate that we've had some ups and downs as the season has gone on, but we're starting to find our groove right now and everybody seems to be putting it together.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Blowing it open:</b> Granderson homered and the Blue Jays sent 11 batters to the plate in a six-run fourth inning that ended Cobb's afternoon. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6A498B883DC78DF271CAB\">Randal Grichuk</span> had a pair of singles in the inning while <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-457F3E65BD903C1FC8AAE\">Gio Urshela</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B952619F7911BD23953BD\">Yangervis Solarte</span>, Hernandez, Pillar and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5FB0AA57C2A4D9A752093\">Russell Martin</span> also reached base. Granderson's sixth home run of the year -- and second of the series -- was a three-run shot to right that was projected to travel approximately 383 feet. It was the fourth time the Blue Jays scored at least six runs in an inning this season and the first since April 18 vs. Kansas City. Toronto's season high for one inning is seven runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8584EAFA2CD964D3F359D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140688283\">Video: BAL@TOR: Blue Jays plate 6 runs in huge 4th inning</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 The most hits for a four-game set by Toronto was April 17-20, 2000, when the Blue Jays had 58.</p><p>\u2022 The Blue Jays also picked up their first four-game sweep since July 24-27, 2017, against the A's.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Blue Jays will open a three-game series on the road when right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-403A70FFCF76D500D0492\">Sam Gaviglio</span> takes the mound on Monday night vs. the Rays, with first pitch scheduled for 7:10 p.m. ET at Tropicana Field. Gaviglio continues to be a pleasant surprise in Toronto's rotation, giving up three runs or fewer in three of his four starts. One key for Gaviglio is that he's allowed just seven walks over 28 2/3 innings pitched this season. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2BF7F992E24CB42B8F497\">Josh Donaldson</span> remains questionable for the game with a sore left calf. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D11FB99FC582DA9D129A9\">Ryan Yarbrough</span> will start for the Rays.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Curtis Granderson set a new career high with six RBIs, part of a 4-for-5 day in which he fell a triple shy of the cycle as Toronto completed a four-game sweep of the Orioles on Sunday at Rogers Centre. 									"body" : "<p>TORONTO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C0B2BEAA6DFD31524EAB\">Curtis Granderson</span> has been around the Major Leagues for 15 years, but apparently it's never too late for a career first.</p><p>Granderson set a new career high with six RBIs as part of a 4-for-5 day in which he fell a triple shy of the cycle in Toronto's 13-3 victory over the Orioles on Sunday at Rogers Centre. The veteran outfielder finished with a three-run homer, two run-scoring doubles and a walk in what will easily be considered his best game since joining the Blue Jays as a free agent during the offseason.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C23474240906E85A9AF97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140290483\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson doubles for his 6th RBI of game</a></span></p><p>Toronto also received home runs from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1CD29147D64EBEEBB8F9F\">Teoscar Hernandez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F4B9964747E6117A18D9E\">Kendrys Morales</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9537EB58E6571B5018A88\">Kevin Pillar</span> in the lopsided victory. Every member of the Blue Jays' starting lineup reached base at least once and seven players had multiple hits, while the 13 runs were two shy of the club's highest total this season as the Blue Jays set a new season high with four homers in the same game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8E0C32852C68A118C76A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140296083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Hernandez rips a 2-run homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>\"A huge day,\" Blue Jays manager John Gibbons said after his team matched its season high with a four-game winning streak. \"Grandy had been scuffling a little bit, there's no doubt. A couple of days ago I was sitting next to [bench coach] DeMarlo Hale, I said, 'You know what we need? Somebody, one guy, to just have a big game. A monster-type game.' You see that every now and then, it carries you a little bit. That's what he did today. Set the tone.\"</p><p>Granderson previously had five RBIs in a game seven times. He last accomplished the feat on April 22, 2016, as part of a two-homer game against Atlanta when Granderson was still with the Mets. This was Granderson's eighth multi-hit game of the season for Toronto and his first since May 27 at Philadelphia. The four hits were a season high, surpassing the three he had vs. Boston on April 24.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-38928BB57CE50F1C31FAD\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141869183\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson and Gibbons on 13-3 win</a></span></p><p>\"It's pretty cool to be able to do that and obviously help the team win,\" Granderson said. \"The cool thing about this game is, every time you step on that field, something could happen that's never happened before and sure enough that ended up happening today for me.\"</p><p>The Blue Jays finished the Orioles series with 56 hits, which is tied for the second-most in franchise history for a four-game set. Toronto had at least 12 hits in each of the four contests, but the series finale was the only game in which the Blue Jays scored more than five runs. The offensive outburst secured the club's second series sweep of three or more games this season and the first since a three-game set vs. Kansas City from April 17-18.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-66285580C871C449AA2AF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140335583\">Video: BAL@TOR: Pillar crushes a solo home run to center</a></span></p><p>Toronto did almost all of its damage against Orioles right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E3D3B4D9DE79219AF61B5\">Alex Cobb</span>, who was charged with nine runs on 11 hits and a walk while striking out five over 3 2/3 innings. Cobb's latest setback saw his ERA rise to 7.23, 11 starts into a four-year deal worth $57 million that he signed this spring. The nine earned runs matched Cobb's career high, which was set on June 13, 2017, vs. the Mariners.</p><p>Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E44A9E703B514FE9DCF8F\">Marco Estrada</span> picked up the easy victory for the Blue Jays as he continued Toronto's recent string of success in the rotation. Estrada allowed two runs while scattering four hits and a walk while striking out nine over six-plus innings. Toronto starters have now tossed seven consecutive quality starts and they have not allowed more than two earned runs in any of those outings. Opponents are batting .173 (27-for-156) against them over that stretch.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6745E57514242D6D69782\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141809083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Estrada strikes out 9 over 6-plus frames in win</a></span></p><p>\"Oh man, I'm going to have to knock on wood now,\" Estrada said when informed of the recent run. \"We're pitching great. We're pitching the way we're supposed to be. We have a really good rotation and it's showing as of late. It's unfortunate that we've had some ups and downs as the season has gone on, but we're starting to find our groove right now and everybody seems to be putting it together.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Blowing it open:</b> Granderson homered and the Blue Jays sent 11 batters to the plate in a six-run fourth inning that ended Cobb's afternoon. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6A498B883DC78DF271CAB\">Randal Grichuk</span> had a pair of singles in the inning while <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-457F3E65BD903C1FC8AAE\">Gio Urshela</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B952619F7911BD23953BD\">Yangervis Solarte</span>, Hernandez, Pillar and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5FB0AA57C2A4D9A752093\">Russell Martin</span> also reached base. Granderson's sixth home run of the year -- and second of the series -- was a three-run shot to right that was projected to travel approximately 383 feet. It was the fourth time the Blue Jays scored at least six runs in an inning this season and the first since April 18 vs. Kansas City. Toronto's season high for one inning is seven runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8584EAFA2CD964D3F359D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140688283\">Video: BAL@TOR: Blue Jays plate 6 runs in huge 4th inning</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 The most hits for a four-game set by Toronto was April 17-20, 2000, when the Blue Jays had 58.</p><p>\u2022 The Blue Jays also picked up their first four-game sweep since July 24-27, 2017, against the A's.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Blue Jays will open a three-game series on the road when right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-403A70FFCF76D500D0492\">Sam Gaviglio</span> takes the mound on Monday night vs. the Rays, with first pitch scheduled for 7:10 p.m. ET at Tropicana Field. Gaviglio continues to be a pleasant surprise in Toronto's rotation, giving up three runs or fewer in three of his four starts. One key for Gaviglio is that he's allowed just seven walks over 28 2/3 innings pitched this season. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2BF7F992E24CB42B8F497\">Josh Donaldson</span> remains questionable for the game with a sore left calf. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D11FB99FC582DA9D129A9\">Ryan Yarbrough</span> will start for the Rays.</p>",

									"body" : "<p>TORONTO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9C0B2BEAA6DFD31524EAB\">Curtis Granderson</span> has been around the Major Leagues for 15 years, but apparently it's never too late for a career first.</p><p>Granderson set a new career high with six RBIs as part of a 4-for-5 day in which he fell a triple shy of the cycle in Toronto's 13-3 victory over the Orioles on Sunday at Rogers Centre. The veteran outfielder finished with a three-run homer, two run-scoring doubles and a walk in what will easily be considered his best game since joining the Blue Jays as a free agent during the offseason.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C23474240906E85A9AF97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140290483\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson doubles for his 6th RBI of game</a></span></p><p>Toronto also received home runs from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1CD29147D64EBEEBB8F9F\">Teoscar Hernandez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F4B9964747E6117A18D9E\">Kendrys Morales</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9537EB58E6571B5018A88\">Kevin Pillar</span> in the lopsided victory. Every member of the Blue Jays' starting lineup reached base at least once and seven players had multiple hits, while the 13 runs were two shy of the club's highest total this season as the Blue Jays set a new season high with four homers in the same game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8E0C32852C68A118C76A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140296083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Hernandez rips a 2-run homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>\"A huge day,\" Blue Jays manager John Gibbons said after his team matched its season high with a four-game winning streak. \"Grandy had been scuffling a little bit, there's no doubt. A couple of days ago I was sitting next to [bench coach] DeMarlo Hale, I said, 'You know what we need? Somebody, one guy, to just have a big game. A monster-type game.' You see that every now and then, it carries you a little bit. That's what he did today. Set the tone.\"</p><p>Granderson previously had five RBIs in a game seven times. He last accomplished the feat on April 22, 2016, as part of a two-homer game against Atlanta when Granderson was still with the Mets. This was Granderson's eighth multi-hit game of the season for Toronto and his first since May 27 at Philadelphia. The four hits were a season high, surpassing the three he had vs. Boston on April 24.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-38928BB57CE50F1C31FAD\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141869183\">Video: BAL@TOR: Granderson and Gibbons on 13-3 win</a></span></p><p>\"It's pretty cool to be able to do that and obviously help the team win,\" Granderson said. \"The cool thing about this game is, every time you step on that field, something could happen that's never happened before and sure enough that ended up happening today for me.\"</p><p>The Blue Jays finished the Orioles series with 56 hits, which is tied for the second-most in franchise history for a four-game set. Toronto had at least 12 hits in each of the four contests, but the series finale was the only game in which the Blue Jays scored more than five runs. The offensive outburst secured the club's second series sweep of three or more games this season and the first since a three-game set vs. Kansas City from April 17-18.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-66285580C871C449AA2AF\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140335583\">Video: BAL@TOR: Pillar crushes a solo home run to center</a></span></p><p>Toronto did almost all of its damage against Orioles right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E3D3B4D9DE79219AF61B5\">Alex Cobb</span>, who was charged with nine runs on 11 hits and a walk while striking out five over 3 2/3 innings. Cobb's latest setback saw his ERA rise to 7.23, 11 starts into a four-year deal worth $57 million that he signed this spring. The nine earned runs matched Cobb's career high, which was set on June 13, 2017, vs. the Mariners.</p><p>Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E44A9E703B514FE9DCF8F\">Marco Estrada</span> picked up the easy victory for the Blue Jays as he continued Toronto's recent string of success in the rotation. Estrada allowed two runs while scattering four hits and a walk while striking out nine over six-plus innings. Toronto starters have now tossed seven consecutive quality starts and they have not allowed more than two earned runs in any of those outings. Opponents are batting .173 (27-for-156) against them over that stretch.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6745E57514242D6D69782\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141809083\">Video: BAL@TOR: Estrada strikes out 9 over 6-plus frames in win</a></span></p><p>\"Oh man, I'm going to have to knock on wood now,\" Estrada said when informed of the recent run. \"We're pitching great. We're pitching the way we're supposed to be. We have a really good rotation and it's showing as of late. It's unfortunate that we've had some ups and downs as the season has gone on, but we're starting to find our groove right now and everybody seems to be putting it together.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Blowing it open:</b> Granderson homered and the Blue Jays sent 11 batters to the plate in a six-run fourth inning that ended Cobb's afternoon. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6A498B883DC78DF271CAB\">Randal Grichuk</span> had a pair of singles in the inning while <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-457F3E65BD903C1FC8AAE\">Gio Urshela</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B952619F7911BD23953BD\">Yangervis Solarte</span>, Hernandez, Pillar and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5FB0AA57C2A4D9A752093\">Russell Martin</span> also reached base. Granderson's sixth home run of the year -- and second of the series -- was a three-run shot to right that was projected to travel approximately 383 feet. It was the fourth time the Blue Jays scored at least six runs in an inning this season and the first since April 18 vs. Kansas City. Toronto's season high for one inning is seven runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8584EAFA2CD964D3F359D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140688283\">Video: BAL@TOR: Blue Jays plate 6 runs in huge 4th inning</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 The most hits for a four-game set by Toronto was April 17-20, 2000, when the Blue Jays had 58.</p><p>\u2022 The Blue Jays also picked up their first four-game sweep since July 24-27, 2017, against the A's.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Blue Jays will open a three-game series on the road when right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-403A70FFCF76D500D0492\">Sam Gaviglio</span> takes the mound on Monday night vs. the Rays, with first pitch scheduled for 7:10 p.m. ET at Tropicana Field. Gaviglio continues to be a pleasant surprise in Toronto's rotation, giving up three runs or fewer in three of his four starts. One key for Gaviglio is that he's allowed just seven walks over 28 2/3 innings pitched this season. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2BF7F992E24CB42B8F497\">Josh Donaldson</span> remains questionable for the game with a sore left calf. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D11FB99FC582DA9D129A9\">Ryan Yarbrough</span> will start for the Rays.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Corey Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers to win the weekend series at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season. Erik Gonzalez and Melky Cabrera had three RBIs apiece for the Indians, and Leonys Martin hit a solo homer for Detroit. Kluber struck out eight over eight innings, allowed two runs and did not walk a batter.",
									"body" : "<p>DETROIT -- After the sinker zipped over the outside corner and popped into the glove of Indians catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E973C7D95C067E9422E89\">Roberto Perez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4A8B125DFC764AAB727A7\">Nicholas Castellanos</span> dropped his bat, removed his helmet and walked away without complaint. There was no arguing the precision of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05E57D99C3CD69F05C7BC\">Corey Kluber</span>'s pitching.</p><p>Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers on Sunday at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F7A70A34D6F5C0FB3E88\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141216883\">Video: CLE@DET: Francona on Kluber's start in 9-2 win</a></span></p><p>\"He just keeps working on his game and elevating it in places wherever he can,\" Indians manager Terry Francona said. \"I mean, to beat him, you have to beat him by stringing a bunch of hits together. That's hard to do. That's part of the reason he's so successful.\"</p><p>Armed with the wealth of support, Kluber continued to practice extreme efficiency as he added eight more innings to his Major League-leading total of 99 2/3 frames on the season. The two-time AL Cy Young Award winner yielded a pair of runs and finished with eight strikeouts, but more notable was the absence of a walk once again.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F1AC4F490B957534BC2BA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140157383\">Video: CLE@DET: Kluber records 100th K of season</a></span></p><p>Sunday marked the sixth consecutive start in which Kluber did not issue a free pass, putting him into a tie with Paul Byrd (2007) and Addie Joss (1908) for the second-longest streak of that kind by an Indians starter in club history. Dick Donovan holds the franchise record with seven consecutive starts with no walks in 1963.</p><p>The MLB record for consecutive starts with no walks is 11, by Bill Fisher of the Kansas City Athletics in 1962.</p><p>Kluber has faced 168 consecutive batters without issuing a free pass, and his run of 43 1/3 innings without a walk is the longest by a Tribe pitcher since Byrd's 48-inning walk-free streak in 2007. During his six-start streak, Kluber has gone 5-0 with a 1.09 ERA and 46 strikeouts in 41 1/3 innings.</p><p>\"I'm pretty sure I had a few three-ball counts today,\" Kluber said. \"I think my focus, even when I get in those positions now or whenever, is to still try to execute a pitch. The last thing I want to do is throw a ball right down the middle just to avoid walking somebody, and then give up damage. I still want to make a quality pitch.</p><p>\"For whatever reason, either guys are swinging at them or I make those pitches in the zone.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9BBD87FF0925CB6CBA2A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141726683\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor and Francona discuss win over Tigers</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F889173B1228AC1E84FA3\">Leonys Martin</span> accounted for both Tigers runs off Kluber, collecting an RBI with a groundout in the third and later adding a homer in the sixth. In the eighth, Kluber slipped into a full count against Martin, who was frozen by a cutter for a crucial called strikeout with runners on second and third. Castellanos followed by flying out to the warning track in left field to end the threat.</p><p>\"If he throws you a pitch and it starts as a strike, it's going to be a ball,\" Tigers catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD46C0D463EB26DE473B5\">John Hicks</span> said of Kluber. \"If he throws you a pitch that starts as a ball, it's probably going to be a strike. His ball, it's like a Wiffle ball, it really is. He's throwing two-seamers that are starting a foot off the plate, and end up being on the plate. It's impressive stuff.\"</p><p>To back Kluber, the Indians scored three runs off Tigers starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E76ABAC6694B03E9CE087\">Artie Lewicki</span> and piled on six more against the Detroit bullpen. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D28FD03E38ACE143DF1BA\">Yonder Alonso</span> (RBI double), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-020A9754A3089AC08B48C\">Melky Cabrera</span> (three RBIs), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F5D6D55FC1A1735A8C91\">Erik Gonzalez</span> (three-run double) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA6AB430FA895B14D38C\">Yan Gomes</span> (two-run homer) came through for Kluber, who is now 10-2 with a 1.99 ERA on the year.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1BE5802AEE0CBAB99B882\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139831883\">Video: CLE@DET: Alonso opens scoring with ground-rule double</a></span></p><p>\"It's like facing a righty and a lefty,\" Gomes said of Kluber. \"His two-seam will come back like a lefty slider. Or a cutter, and he gets his slider going the other way and he'll pull the string on somebody. It's one of those things. He knows how to adapt.\"</p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Double trouble:</b> With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-69F211937F19241D2719A\">Jason Kipnis</span> out of the starting lineup on Sunday due to neck stiffness, Gonzalez came off the bench and got the nod at second base. The utility man made the most of his opportunity with the bases loaded in the sixth. The infielder drilled a 1-1 pitch from reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B23C7403A039BD742F790\">Drew VerHagen</span> deep into the right-center-field gap for a bases-clearing double that pushed the Indians ahead, 6-1.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-37F9A03CEE7D128E78F8E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140286383\">Video: CLE@DET: Gonzalez clears the bases with a double</a></span></p><p>\"Obviously, the big hit, the double, that spread it out for us,\" Francona said. \"It's nice to pad that lead, especially with Kluber pitching.\"</p><p><b>PEREZ EXITS, GOMES DELIVERS</b><br />Prior to the three-run double by Gonzalez, Perez was <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-7C7D7205D6AF7E6A35AB6\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/indians/news/roberto-perez-exits-after-hit-on-hand-by-pitch/c-280654444\">hit on the right hand</a></span> by an inside fastball from VerHagen to load the bases. Perez initially stayed in the game and scored on Gonzalez's hit, but the catcher was replaced in the bottom of the sixth by Gomes. Perez underwent X-rays and the Indians will know more about the severity of the injury on Monday.</p><p>\"It's a little ambiguous right now,\" Francona said. \"There's a decent chance we dodged a bullet. I don't know that. We're going to have to see, one, how he shows up tomorrow. He really got hit hard. By the time I saw him, and then he got to first, it had turned purple. So, we'll hope for the best, but we'll prepare for other.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5F4FCB0691087ABE512A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140284483\">Video: CLE@DET: Tigers challenge hit-by-pitch in 6th</a></span></p><p>Perez started over Gomes on Sunday due to the latter catching all 12 innings of Saturday's loss to the Tigers. In the eighth inning, Gomes showed no signs of fatigue when he crushed a full-count fastball from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7FFE1F12B5DE3C78BD5B3\">Zac Reininger</span> a projected 429 feet to center for a two-run home run, giving Cleveland a 9-2 advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7FEFC21E98FBD0DE662BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140509283\">Video: CLE@DET: Gomes clobbers a two-run home run</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Indians shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C2FB3EC7DD3C5A14987A4\">Francisco Lindor</span> has shown off his swim-move slide multiple times over the years and he used the technique again on a steal of second in the fourth. As Lindor slid head-first into the bag, he pulled his left arm away from the tag attempt by Tigers shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-189330D6BFCA399608FB4\">Jose Iglesias</span> while grabbing the base with his right hand. Lindor was deemed safe for his second stolen base in the game. Three batters later, Lindor sprinted home on a sacrifice fly from Cabrera.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73B814D8560F9AB7FA181\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139991783\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor steals second thanks to great slide</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Per <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EE5431A399A2EA755F985\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, Kluber entered Sunday's outing with a Major League-leading 36 called strikeouts. The right-hander also had the most called strikeouts via a two-seamer/sinker with 25. Against the Tigers, Kluber chalked up six more called strikeouts, including four with his sinker.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AF767EF443126B3CCD8AF\">Carlos Carrasco</span> (7-4, 4.23 ERA) is scheduled to take the mound for the Tribe on Monday, when the White Sox host the Indians in an 8:10 p.m. ET clash at Guaranteed Rate Field to open a four-game set. Carrasco is 3-3 with a 3.83 ERA in seven road starts this season. Chicago will counter with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-773BE241B74FA7597F780\">Lucas Giolito</span> (4-6, 7.08).</p>",

									"blurb" : "Corey Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers to win the weekend series at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season. Erik Gonzalez and Melky Cabrera had three RBIs apiece for the Indians, and Leonys Martin hit a solo homer for Detroit. Kluber struck out eight over eight innings, allowed two runs and did not walk a batter.",
									"body" : "<p>DETROIT -- After the sinker zipped over the outside corner and popped into the glove of Indians catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E973C7D95C067E9422E89\">Roberto Perez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4A8B125DFC764AAB727A7\">Nicholas Castellanos</span> dropped his bat, removed his helmet and walked away without complaint. There was no arguing the precision of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05E57D99C3CD69F05C7BC\">Corey Kluber</span>'s pitching.</p><p>Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers on Sunday at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F7A70A34D6F5C0FB3E88\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141216883\">Video: CLE@DET: Francona on Kluber's start in 9-2 win</a></span></p><p>\"He just keeps working on his game and elevating it in places wherever he can,\" Indians manager Terry Francona said. \"I mean, to beat him, you have to beat him by stringing a bunch of hits together. That's hard to do. That's part of the reason he's so successful.\"</p><p>Armed with the wealth of support, Kluber continued to practice extreme efficiency as he added eight more innings to his Major League-leading total of 99 2/3 frames on the season. The two-time AL Cy Young Award winner yielded a pair of runs and finished with eight strikeouts, but more notable was the absence of a walk once again.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F1AC4F490B957534BC2BA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140157383\">Video: CLE@DET: Kluber records 100th K of season</a></span></p><p>Sunday marked the sixth consecutive start in which Kluber did not issue a free pass, putting him into a tie with Paul Byrd (2007) and Addie Joss (1908) for the second-longest streak of that kind by an Indians starter in club history. Dick Donovan holds the franchise record with seven consecutive starts with no walks in 1963.</p><p>The MLB record for consecutive starts with no walks is 11, by Bill Fisher of the Kansas City Athletics in 1962.</p><p>Kluber has faced 168 consecutive batters without issuing a free pass, and his run of 43 1/3 innings without a walk is the longest by a Tribe pitcher since Byrd's 48-inning walk-free streak in 2007. During his six-start streak, Kluber has gone 5-0 with a 1.09 ERA and 46 strikeouts in 41 1/3 innings.</p><p>\"I'm pretty sure I had a few three-ball counts today,\" Kluber said. \"I think my focus, even when I get in those positions now or whenever, is to still try to execute a pitch. The last thing I want to do is throw a ball right down the middle just to avoid walking somebody, and then give up damage. I still want to make a quality pitch.</p><p>\"For whatever reason, either guys are swinging at them or I make those pitches in the zone.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9BBD87FF0925CB6CBA2A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141726683\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor and Francona discuss win over Tigers</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F889173B1228AC1E84FA3\">Leonys Martin</span> accounted for both Tigers runs off Kluber, collecting an RBI with a groundout in the third and later adding a homer in the sixth. In the eighth, Kluber slipped into a full count against Martin, who was frozen by a cutter for a crucial called strikeout with runners on second and third. Castellanos followed by flying out to the warning track in left field to end the threat.</p><p>\"If he throws you a pitch and it starts as a strike, it's going to be a ball,\" Tigers catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD46C0D463EB26DE473B5\">John Hicks</span> said of Kluber. \"If he throws you a pitch that starts as a ball, it's probably going to be a strike. His ball, it's like a Wiffle ball, it really is. He's throwing two-seamers that are starting a foot off the plate, and end up being on the plate. It's impressive stuff.\"</p><p>To back Kluber, the Indians scored three runs off Tigers starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E76ABAC6694B03E9CE087\">Artie Lewicki</span> and piled on six more against the Detroit bullpen. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D28FD03E38ACE143DF1BA\">Yonder Alonso</span> (RBI double), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-020A9754A3089AC08B48C\">Melky Cabrera</span> (three RBIs), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F5D6D55FC1A1735A8C91\">Erik Gonzalez</span> (three-run double) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA6AB430FA895B14D38C\">Yan Gomes</span> (two-run homer) came through for Kluber, who is now 10-2 with a 1.99 ERA on the year.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1BE5802AEE0CBAB99B882\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139831883\">Video: CLE@DET: Alonso opens scoring with ground-rule double</a></span></p><p>\"It's like facing a righty and a lefty,\" Gomes said of Kluber. \"His two-seam will come back like a lefty slider. Or a cutter, and he gets his slider going the other way and he'll pull the string on somebody. It's one of those things. He knows how to adapt.\"</p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Double trouble:</b> With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-69F211937F19241D2719A\">Jason Kipnis</span> out of the starting lineup on Sunday due to neck stiffness, Gonzalez came off the bench and got the nod at second base. The utility man made the most of his opportunity with the bases loaded in the sixth. The infielder drilled a 1-1 pitch from reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B23C7403A039BD742F790\">Drew VerHagen</span> deep into the right-center-field gap for a bases-clearing double that pushed the Indians ahead, 6-1.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-37F9A03CEE7D128E78F8E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140286383\">Video: CLE@DET: Gonzalez clears the bases with a double</a></span></p><p>\"Obviously, the big hit, the double, that spread it out for us,\" Francona said. \"It's nice to pad that lead, especially with Kluber pitching.\"</p><p><b>PEREZ EXITS, GOMES DELIVERS</b><br />Prior to the three-run double by Gonzalez, Perez was <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-7C7D7205D6AF7E6A35AB6\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/indians/news/roberto-perez-exits-after-hit-on-hand-by-pitch/c-280654444\">hit on the right hand</a></span> by an inside fastball from VerHagen to load the bases. Perez initially stayed in the game and scored on Gonzalez's hit, but the catcher was replaced in the bottom of the sixth by Gomes. Perez underwent X-rays and the Indians will know more about the severity of the injury on Monday.</p><p>\"It's a little ambiguous right now,\" Francona said. \"There's a decent chance we dodged a bullet. I don't know that. We're going to have to see, one, how he shows up tomorrow. He really got hit hard. By the time I saw him, and then he got to first, it had turned purple. So, we'll hope for the best, but we'll prepare for other.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5F4FCB0691087ABE512A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140284483\">Video: CLE@DET: Tigers challenge hit-by-pitch in 6th</a></span></p><p>Perez started over Gomes on Sunday due to the latter catching all 12 innings of Saturday's loss to the Tigers. In the eighth inning, Gomes showed no signs of fatigue when he crushed a full-count fastball from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7FFE1F12B5DE3C78BD5B3\">Zac Reininger</span> a projected 429 feet to center for a two-run home run, giving Cleveland a 9-2 advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7FEFC21E98FBD0DE662BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140509283\">Video: CLE@DET: Gomes clobbers a two-run home run</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Indians shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C2FB3EC7DD3C5A14987A4\">Francisco Lindor</span> has shown off his swim-move slide multiple times over the years and he used the technique again on a steal of second in the fourth. As Lindor slid head-first into the bag, he pulled his left arm away from the tag attempt by Tigers shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-189330D6BFCA399608FB4\">Jose Iglesias</span> while grabbing the base with his right hand. Lindor was deemed safe for his second stolen base in the game. Three batters later, Lindor sprinted home on a sacrifice fly from Cabrera.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73B814D8560F9AB7FA181\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139991783\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor steals second thanks to great slide</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Per <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EE5431A399A2EA755F985\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, Kluber entered Sunday's outing with a Major League-leading 36 called strikeouts. The right-hander also had the most called strikeouts via a two-seamer/sinker with 25. Against the Tigers, Kluber chalked up six more called strikeouts, including four with his sinker.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AF767EF443126B3CCD8AF\">Carlos Carrasco</span> (7-4, 4.23 ERA) is scheduled to take the mound for the Tribe on Monday, when the White Sox host the Indians in an 8:10 p.m. ET clash at Guaranteed Rate Field to open a four-game set. Carrasco is 3-3 with a 3.83 ERA in seven road starts this season. Chicago will counter with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-773BE241B74FA7597F780\">Lucas Giolito</span> (4-6, 7.08).</p>",
