								{
									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Corey Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers to win the weekend series at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season. Erik Gonzalez and Melky Cabrera had three RBIs apiece for the Indians, and Leonys Martin hit a solo homer for Detroit. Kluber struck out eight over eight innings, allowed two runs and did not walk a batter.",
									"body" : "<p>DETROIT -- After the sinker zipped over the outside corner and popped into the glove of Indians catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E973C7D95C067E9422E89\">Roberto Perez</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4A8B125DFC764AAB727A7\">Nicholas Castellanos</span> dropped his bat, removed his helmet and walked away without complaint. There was no arguing the precision of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05E57D99C3CD69F05C7BC\">Corey Kluber</span>'s pitching.</p><p>Kluber methodically worked his way up and down Detroit's order, while the Tribe offense put up a well-rounded showing en route to a 9-2 rout of the Tigers on Sunday at Comerica Park. With the victory, Kluber became the first pitcher in the American League to reach 10 wins this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F7A70A34D6F5C0FB3E88\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141216883\">Video: CLE@DET: Francona on Kluber's start in 9-2 win</a></span></p><p>\"He just keeps working on his game and elevating it in places wherever he can,\" Indians manager Terry Francona said. \"I mean, to beat him, you have to beat him by stringing a bunch of hits together. That's hard to do. That's part of the reason he's so successful.\"</p><p>Armed with the wealth of support, Kluber continued to practice extreme efficiency as he added eight more innings to his Major League-leading total of 99 2/3 frames on the season. The two-time AL Cy Young Award winner yielded a pair of runs and finished with eight strikeouts, but more notable was the absence of a walk once again.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F1AC4F490B957534BC2BA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140157383\">Video: CLE@DET: Kluber records 100th K of season</a></span></p><p>Sunday marked the sixth consecutive start in which Kluber did not issue a free pass, putting him into a tie with Paul Byrd (2007) and Addie Joss (1908) for the second-longest streak of that kind by an Indians starter in club history. Dick Donovan holds the franchise record with seven consecutive starts with no walks in 1963.</p><p>The MLB record for consecutive starts with no walks is 11, by Bill Fisher of the Kansas City Athletics in 1962.</p><p>Kluber has faced 168 consecutive batters without issuing a free pass, and his run of 43 1/3 innings without a walk is the longest by a Tribe pitcher since Byrd's 48-inning walk-free streak in 2007. During his six-start streak, Kluber has gone 5-0 with a 1.09 ERA and 46 strikeouts in 41 1/3 innings.</p><p>\"I'm pretty sure I had a few three-ball counts today,\" Kluber said. \"I think my focus, even when I get in those positions now or whenever, is to still try to execute a pitch. The last thing I want to do is throw a ball right down the middle just to avoid walking somebody, and then give up damage. I still want to make a quality pitch.</p><p>\"For whatever reason, either guys are swinging at them or I make those pitches in the zone.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9BBD87FF0925CB6CBA2A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141726683\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor and Francona discuss win over Tigers</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F889173B1228AC1E84FA3\">Leonys Martin</span> accounted for both Tigers runs off Kluber, collecting an RBI with a groundout in the third and later adding a homer in the sixth. In the eighth, Kluber slipped into a full count against Martin, who was frozen by a cutter for a crucial called strikeout with runners on second and third. Castellanos followed by flying out to the warning track in left field to end the threat.</p><p>\"If he throws you a pitch and it starts as a strike, it's going to be a ball,\" Tigers catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD46C0D463EB26DE473B5\">John Hicks</span> said of Kluber. \"If he throws you a pitch that starts as a ball, it's probably going to be a strike. His ball, it's like a Wiffle ball, it really is. He's throwing two-seamers that are starting a foot off the plate, and end up being on the plate. It's impressive stuff.\"</p><p>To back Kluber, the Indians scored three runs off Tigers starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E76ABAC6694B03E9CE087\">Artie Lewicki</span> and piled on six more against the Detroit bullpen. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D28FD03E38ACE143DF1BA\">Yonder Alonso</span> (RBI double), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-020A9754A3089AC08B48C\">Melky Cabrera</span> (three RBIs), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F5D6D55FC1A1735A8C91\">Erik Gonzalez</span> (three-run double) and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA6AB430FA895B14D38C\">Yan Gomes</span> (two-run homer) came through for Kluber, who is now 10-2 with a 1.99 ERA on the year.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1BE5802AEE0CBAB99B882\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139831883\">Video: CLE@DET: Alonso opens scoring with ground-rule double</a></span></p><p>\"It's like facing a righty and a lefty,\" Gomes said of Kluber. \"His two-seam will come back like a lefty slider. Or a cutter, and he gets his slider going the other way and he'll pull the string on somebody. It's one of those things. He knows how to adapt.\"</p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Double trouble:</b> With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-69F211937F19241D2719A\">Jason Kipnis</span> out of the starting lineup on Sunday due to neck stiffness, Gonzalez came off the bench and got the nod at second base. The utility man made the most of his opportunity with the bases loaded in the sixth. The infielder drilled a 1-1 pitch from reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B23C7403A039BD742F790\">Drew VerHagen</span> deep into the right-center-field gap for a bases-clearing double that pushed the Indians ahead, 6-1.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-37F9A03CEE7D128E78F8E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140286383\">Video: CLE@DET: Gonzalez clears the bases with a double</a></span></p><p>\"Obviously, the big hit, the double, that spread it out for us,\" Francona said. \"It's nice to pad that lead, especially with Kluber pitching.\"</p><p><b>PEREZ EXITS, GOMES DELIVERS</b><br />Prior to the three-run double by Gonzalez, Perez was <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-7C7D7205D6AF7E6A35AB6\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/indians/news/roberto-perez-exits-after-hit-on-hand-by-pitch/c-280654444\">hit on the right hand</a></span> by an inside fastball from VerHagen to load the bases. Perez initially stayed in the game and scored on Gonzalez's hit, but the catcher was replaced in the bottom of the sixth by Gomes. Perez underwent X-rays and the Indians will know more about the severity of the injury on Monday.</p><p>\"It's a little ambiguous right now,\" Francona said. \"There's a decent chance we dodged a bullet. I don't know that. We're going to have to see, one, how he shows up tomorrow. He really got hit hard. By the time I saw him, and then he got to first, it had turned purple. So, we'll hope for the best, but we'll prepare for other.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5F4FCB0691087ABE512A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140284483\">Video: CLE@DET: Tigers challenge hit-by-pitch in 6th</a></span></p><p>Perez started over Gomes on Sunday due to the latter catching all 12 innings of Saturday's loss to the Tigers. In the eighth inning, Gomes showed no signs of fatigue when he crushed a full-count fastball from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7FFE1F12B5DE3C78BD5B3\">Zac Reininger</span> a projected 429 feet to center for a two-run home run, giving Cleveland a 9-2 advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7FEFC21E98FBD0DE662BE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140509283\">Video: CLE@DET: Gomes clobbers a two-run home run</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Indians shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C2FB3EC7DD3C5A14987A4\">Francisco Lindor</span> has shown off his swim-move slide multiple times over the years and he used the technique again on a steal of second in the fourth. As Lindor slid head-first into the bag, he pulled his left arm away from the tag attempt by Tigers shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-189330D6BFCA399608FB4\">Jose Iglesias</span> while grabbing the base with his right hand. Lindor was deemed safe for his second stolen base in the game. Three batters later, Lindor sprinted home on a sacrifice fly from Cabrera.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73B814D8560F9AB7FA181\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139991783\">Video: CLE@DET: Lindor steals second thanks to great slide</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Per <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EE5431A399A2EA755F985\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, Kluber entered Sunday's outing with a Major League-leading 36 called strikeouts. The right-hander also had the most called strikeouts via a two-seamer/sinker with 25. Against the Tigers, Kluber chalked up six more called strikeouts, including four with his sinker.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AF767EF443126B3CCD8AF\">Carlos Carrasco</span> (7-4, 4.23 ERA) is scheduled to take the mound for the Tribe on Monday, when the White Sox host the Indians in an 8:10 p.m. ET clash at Guaranteed Rate Field to open a four-game set. Carrasco is 3-3 with a 3.83 ERA in seven road starts this season. Chicago will counter with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-773BE241B74FA7597F780\">Lucas Giolito</span> (4-6, 7.08).</p>",

That's what I dream of.\"</p><p>The 10-year veteran never came closer than he did on Sunday afternoon at Marlins Park, where the Padres reeled off their fourth straight series victory with a 3-1 win.</p><p>But for Richard -- of all pitchers -- to break the Padres' 49-year drought, it was always going to take a dash of luck. Richard is a sinkerballer who pitches to contact and gets more ground balls, on average, than any other starter in the Majors. That luck deserted him in the seventh inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73FE56D22D475C7AEDDBC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878683\">Video: SD@MIA: Green on Richard's outing, defensive effort</a></span></p><p>Richard had thrown 6 2/3 innings of no-hit ball when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F162503444CFEC22AF81\">Miguel Rojas</span> bounced a hard chopper through the middle. Just like that -- after Richard had emphatically dominated Miami's lineup all afternoon -- his chance at history was over. The Padres, who have already seen <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-13ACDBA5AF1CC23DF99BA\">Tyson Ross</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FDF39287E87C1B324894\">Jordan Lyles</span> carry their no-hitters into the eighth this season, remain the only franchise without one.</p><p>\"He's such a contact-oriented pitcher that those aren't really the guys that profile to get no-hitters very often,\" Padres manager Andy Green said. \"You're hoping no ball rolls through the hole, but there was no play anyone could've made on that one.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7D071A1FBCAE3D2EC0C90\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140373483\">Video: SD@MIA: Richard loses no-hit bid with 2 outs in 7th</a></span></p><p>Richard didn't make history, but he was spectacular nonetheless. The lone run scored when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A32E4613028FD614C2992\">JT Riddle</span> followed Rojas with a single of his own. But Richard escaped the jam to complete seven excellent innings with five strikeouts, two hits and three walks. The Padres have now won nine of 12 and are 21-16 since the start of May.</p><p>\"The confidence is really starting to ooze around here,\" said <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A433BA409058D6BE952A5\">Eric Hosmer</span>, whose two-run homer in the sixth was the difference on the scoreboard.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-A9E0E34E0D049ABBC058C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140566183\">Video: SD@MIA: Hand fans Brinson to lock down his 19th save</a></span></p><p>Until Rojas' single, Padres defenders gobbled up everything that came their way. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7CF34D79E5F77AD7595B5\">Freddy Galvis</span> made a pair of excellent plays at short. Second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-92B8DA5E1E3E67C80D793\">Jose Pirela</span> executed two nice plays on the run, robbing Riddle and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-75BD980A2FAC6679C9CA9\">Lewis Brinson</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9DF69821A140BE2EE72A7\">Manuel Margot</span> tracked down a liner to the warning track in center.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6606AC90A18517646E98C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139823183\">Video: SD@MIA: Margot chases down a liner to end threat</a></span></p><p>There was nothing Pirela or Galvis could do on Rojas' single, however. The Marlins' third baseman scorched it at 105 mph. But because of its negative launch angle, <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5DC7CA1D490AB35523D9E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> awarded the play a 43-percent hit probability.</p><p>\"Bummer,\" Richard said of his first thought. \"I wish I could've kicked it or done something to stop it. But it was a decent pitch. He put a pretty good swing on it. No regrets.\"</p><p>It wasn't to be. As the ball whirred past Richard, he pirouetted on the mound in a mixture of frustration and disappointment. The Padres' drought had reached 7,881 games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C5CF6A9EB1465D3AA6FB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141475283\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer discusses homer, win over Marlins</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Renfroe gets it right:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-804528C0EDB6908B0B899\">Hunter Renfroe</span>'s struggles against right-handed pitching feel like ancient history. Renfroe has torched right-handers lately, and he went 2-for-4 on Sunday. He doubled in the second inning before scoring the game's first run on Galvis' sacrifice fly. For some perspective: Renfroe was hitting .143/.226/.357 against righties before he landed on the disabled list with right elbow inflammation in April. He's hitting .458/.500/.750 in 26 plate appearances since.</p><p><b>Hometown Hoz:</b> Hosmer grew up watching the Marlins at Pro Player Stadium. He was in attendance for Game 7 of the 1997 World Series when Edgar Renteria walked off the Indians. On Sunday, he created a nice memory for himself <i>against</i> his hometown team. Hosmer crushed a 3-2 fastball from Marlins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CBA976567E4283E3E9E9B\">Jose Urena</span> just past the home run structure in left-center field. It was Hosmer's first career dinger against Miami.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D9214DB82A79855D1859D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140068783\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer launches a 2-run jack to left-center</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />At 34 years and 271 days old, Richard was attempting to become the oldest pitcher to throw a no-hitter since Randy Johnson's perfect game against the Braves in May 2004. Only 13 pitchers at Richard's age or older have completed a no-hitter. The last four -- Johnson, David Cone, David Wells and Dennis Martinez -- were all perfect games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-third-party token-third-party-twitter-embed\" id=\"token-31DC1509DB328F11CE0AC\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/Padres/status/1005890607770816513\">Tweet from @Padres: Quite a performance today by @CRThrees! \ud83d\udc4f pic.twitter.com/3sblYNJU7o</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99C6A24D2A561187A77BA\">Christian Villanueva</span> has struggled defensively this season, but he was sharp on Sunday with Richard on the mound. Then, in the eighth, he made arguably his best play of the season.</p><p>The rookie third baseman ranged to his left and dove for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-25B4946A8DC84F7E5F0AA\">Starlin Castro</span>'s grounder. Just as quickly, he rose to his feet and fired to first for the out. Padres reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C75FA378013EC28E08CA9\">Kirby Yates</span> clapped into his glove six times in appreciation.</p><p>\"Christian Villanueva played the best third base he's played in a long time,\" Green said. \"It was really good seeing him make some tough plays.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-410A7675F420C35808D87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140477183\">Video: SD@MIA: Villanueva slides for dazzling stop at third</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's been an unbelievable teammate to me, a partner in trying to build this and get this to where we want to be. And he's an unbelievable teammate to every guy in there. \u2026 He's exactly what you want for the young guys to see.\" -- <i>Green, on Richard</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2257B2C2C7580FB792CA6\">Jordan Lyles</span> needs to bounce back from his worst start of the season, in which he allowed eight runs and 11 hits over 4 1/3 innings against Atlanta. Otherwise, he has been solid since the Padres moved him into their rotation a month ago. Lyles takes the ball Monday in St. Louis with first pitch slated for 5:15 p.m. PT. The Cardinals counter with righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B8879991B0C58A8DE786\">Jack Flaherty</span>.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Clayton Richard lost his no-hit bid with two outs in the seventh inning on Miguel Rojas' single up the middle, but the Padres won their fourth straight series. San Diego remains the only MLB team without a no-no. Eric Hosmer's two-run homer off Jose Urena, who gave up three runs over six innings, proved to be the difference.",
									"body" : "<p>MIAMI -- Every five days, before he goes to sleep, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1BE823E3464AD53321FB1\">Clayton Richard</span> envisions his forthcoming start. And every five days when he does so, the veteran left-hander envisions becoming the first Padre in history to throw a no-hitter.</p><p>\"The night before I pitch, I visualize the game,\" Richard said. \"I don't visualize giving up any hits. I go to bed with that being my last thought. That's what I dream of.\"</p><p>The 10-year veteran never came closer than he did on Sunday afternoon at Marlins Park, where the Padres reeled off their fourth straight series victory with a 3-1 win.</p><p>But for Richard -- of all pitchers -- to break the Padres' 49-year drought, it was always going to take a dash of luck. Richard is a sinkerballer who pitches to contact and gets more ground balls, on average, than any other starter in the Majors. That luck deserted him in the seventh inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73FE56D22D475C7AEDDBC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878683\">Video: SD@MIA: Green on Richard's outing, defensive effort</a></span></p><p>Richard had thrown 6 2/3 innings of no-hit ball when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F162503444CFEC22AF81\">Miguel Rojas</span> bounced a hard chopper through the middle. Just like that -- after Richard had emphatically dominated Miami's lineup all afternoon -- his chance at history was over. The Padres, who have already seen <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-13ACDBA5AF1CC23DF99BA\">Tyson Ross</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FDF39287E87C1B324894\">Jordan Lyles</span> carry their no-hitters into the eighth this season, remain the only franchise without one.</p><p>\"He's such a contact-oriented pitcher that those aren't really the guys that profile to get no-hitters very often,\" Padres manager Andy Green said. \"You're hoping no ball rolls through the hole, but there was no play anyone could've made on that one.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7D071A1FBCAE3D2EC0C90\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140373483\">Video: SD@MIA: Richard loses no-hit bid with 2 outs in 7th</a></span></p><p>Richard didn't make history, but he was spectacular nonetheless. The lone run scored when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A32E4613028FD614C2992\">JT Riddle</span> followed Rojas with a single of his own. But Richard escaped the jam to complete seven excellent innings with five strikeouts, two hits and three walks. The Padres have now won nine of 12 and are 21-16 since the start of May.</p><p>\"The confidence is really starting to ooze around here,\" said <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A433BA409058D6BE952A5\">Eric Hosmer</span>, whose two-run homer in the sixth was the difference on the scoreboard.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-A9E0E34E0D049ABBC058C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140566183\">Video: SD@MIA: Hand fans Brinson to lock down his 19th save</a></span></p><p>Until Rojas' single, Padres defenders gobbled up everything that came their way. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7CF34D79E5F77AD7595B5\">Freddy Galvis</span> made a pair of excellent plays at short. Second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-92B8DA5E1E3E67C80D793\">Jose Pirela</span> executed two nice plays on the run, robbing Riddle and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-75BD980A2FAC6679C9CA9\">Lewis Brinson</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9DF69821A140BE2EE72A7\">Manuel Margot</span> tracked down a liner to the warning track in center.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6606AC90A18517646E98C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139823183\">Video: SD@MIA: Margot chases down a liner to end threat</a></span></p><p>There was nothing Pirela or Galvis could do on Rojas' single, however. The Marlins' third baseman scorched it at 105 mph. But because of its negative launch angle, <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5DC7CA1D490AB35523D9E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> awarded the play a 43-percent hit probability.</p><p>\"Bummer,\" Richard said of his first thought. \"I wish I could've kicked it or done something to stop it. But it was a decent pitch. He put a pretty good swing on it. No regrets.\"</p><p>It wasn't to be. As the ball whirred past Richard, he pirouetted on the mound in a mixture of frustration and disappointment. The Padres' drought had reached 7,881 games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C5CF6A9EB1465D3AA6FB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141475283\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer discusses homer, win over Marlins</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Renfroe gets it right:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-804528C0EDB6908B0B899\">Hunter Renfroe</span>'s struggles against right-handed pitching feel like ancient history. Renfroe has torched right-handers lately, and he went 2-for-4 on Sunday. He doubled in the second inning before scoring the game's first run on Galvis' sacrifice fly. For some perspective: Renfroe was hitting .143/.226/.357 against righties before he landed on the disabled list with right elbow inflammation in April. He's hitting .458/.500/.750 in 26 plate appearances since.</p><p><b>Hometown Hoz:</b> Hosmer grew up watching the Marlins at Pro Player Stadium. He was in attendance for Game 7 of the 1997 World Series when Edgar Renteria walked off the Indians. On Sunday, he created a nice memory for himself <i>against</i> his hometown team. Hosmer crushed a 3-2 fastball from Marlins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CBA976567E4283E3E9E9B\">Jose Urena</span> just past the home run structure in left-center field. It was Hosmer's first career dinger against Miami.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D9214DB82A79855D1859D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140068783\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer launches a 2-run jack to left-center</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />At 34 years and 271 days old, Richard was attempting to become the oldest pitcher to throw a no-hitter since Randy Johnson's perfect game against the Braves in May 2004. Only 13 pitchers at Richard's age or older have completed a no-hitter. The last four -- Johnson, David Cone, David Wells and Dennis Martinez -- were all perfect games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-third-party token-third-party-twitter-embed\" id=\"token-31DC1509DB328F11CE0AC\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/Padres/status/1005890607770816513\">Tweet from @Padres: Quite a performance today by @CRThrees! \ud83d\udc4f pic.twitter.com/3sblYNJU7o</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99C6A24D2A561187A77BA\">Christian Villanueva</span> has struggled defensively this season, but he was sharp on Sunday with Richard on the mound. Then, in the eighth, he made arguably his best play of the season.</p><p>The rookie third baseman ranged to his left and dove for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-25B4946A8DC84F7E5F0AA\">Starlin Castro</span>'s grounder. Just as quickly, he rose to his feet and fired to first for the out. Padres reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C75FA378013EC28E08CA9\">Kirby Yates</span> clapped into his glove six times in appreciation.</p><p>\"Christian Villanueva played the best third base he's played in a long time,\" Green said. \"It was really good seeing him make some tough plays.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-410A7675F420C35808D87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140477183\">Video: SD@MIA: Villanueva slides for dazzling stop at third</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's been an unbelievable teammate to me, a partner in trying to build this and get this to where we want to be. And he's an unbelievable teammate to every guy in there. \u2026 He's exactly what you want for the young guys to see.\" -- <i>Green, on Richard</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2257B2C2C7580FB792CA6\">Jordan Lyles</span> needs to bounce back from his worst start of the season, in which he allowed eight runs and 11 hits over 4 1/3 innings against Atlanta. Otherwise, he has been solid since the Padres moved him into their rotation a month ago. Lyles takes the ball Monday in St. Louis with first pitch slated for 5:15 p.m. PT. The Cardinals counter with righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B8879991B0C58A8DE786\">Jack Flaherty</span>.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Clayton Richard lost his no-hit bid with two outs in the seventh inning on Miguel Rojas' single up the middle, but the Padres won their fourth straight series. San Diego remains the only MLB team without a no-no. Eric Hosmer's two-run homer off Jose Urena, who gave up three runs over six innings, proved to be the difference.",
									"body" : "<p>MIAMI -- Every five days, before he goes to sleep, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1BE823E3464AD53321FB1\">Clayton Richard</span> envisions his forthcoming start. And every five days when he does so, the veteran left-hander envisions becoming the first Padre in history to throw a no-hitter.</p><p>\"The night before I pitch, I visualize the game,\" Richard said. \"I don't visualize giving up any hits. I go to bed with that being my last thought. That's what I dream of.\"</p><p>The 10-year veteran never came closer than he did on Sunday afternoon at Marlins Park, where the Padres reeled off their fourth straight series victory with a 3-1 win.</p><p>But for Richard -- of all pitchers -- to break the Padres' 49-year drought, it was always going to take a dash of luck. Richard is a sinkerballer who pitches to contact and gets more ground balls, on average, than any other starter in the Majors. That luck deserted him in the seventh inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-73FE56D22D475C7AEDDBC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878683\">Video: SD@MIA: Green on Richard's outing, defensive effort</a></span></p><p>Richard had thrown 6 2/3 innings of no-hit ball when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5F162503444CFEC22AF81\">Miguel Rojas</span> bounced a hard chopper through the middle. Just like that -- after Richard had emphatically dominated Miami's lineup all afternoon -- his chance at history was over. The Padres, who have already seen <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-13ACDBA5AF1CC23DF99BA\">Tyson Ross</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FDF39287E87C1B324894\">Jordan Lyles</span> carry their no-hitters into the eighth this season, remain the only franchise without one.</p><p>\"He's such a contact-oriented pitcher that those aren't really the guys that profile to get no-hitters very often,\" Padres manager Andy Green said. \"You're hoping no ball rolls through the hole, but there was no play anyone could've made on that one.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-7D071A1FBCAE3D2EC0C90\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140373483\">Video: SD@MIA: Richard loses no-hit bid with 2 outs in 7th</a></span></p><p>Richard didn't make history, but he was spectacular nonetheless. The lone run scored when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A32E4613028FD614C2992\">JT Riddle</span> followed Rojas with a single of his own. But Richard escaped the jam to complete seven excellent innings with five strikeouts, two hits and three walks. The Padres have now won nine of 12 and are 21-16 since the start of May.</p><p>\"The confidence is really starting to ooze around here,\" said <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A433BA409058D6BE952A5\">Eric Hosmer</span>, whose two-run homer in the sixth was the difference on the scoreboard.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-A9E0E34E0D049ABBC058C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140566183\">Video: SD@MIA: Hand fans Brinson to lock down his 19th save</a></span></p><p>Until Rojas' single, Padres defenders gobbled up everything that came their way. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7CF34D79E5F77AD7595B5\">Freddy Galvis</span> made a pair of excellent plays at short. Second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-92B8DA5E1E3E67C80D793\">Jose Pirela</span> executed two nice plays on the run, robbing Riddle and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-75BD980A2FAC6679C9CA9\">Lewis Brinson</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9DF69821A140BE2EE72A7\">Manuel Margot</span> tracked down a liner to the warning track in center.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6606AC90A18517646E98C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139823183\">Video: SD@MIA: Margot chases down a liner to end threat</a></span></p><p>There was nothing Pirela or Galvis could do on Rojas' single, however. The Marlins' third baseman scorched it at 105 mph. But because of its negative launch angle, <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5DC7CA1D490AB35523D9E\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> awarded the play a 43-percent hit probability.</p><p>\"Bummer,\" Richard said of his first thought. \"I wish I could've kicked it or done something to stop it. But it was a decent pitch. He put a pretty good swing on it. No regrets.\"</p><p>It wasn't to be. As the ball whirred past Richard, he pirouetted on the mound in a mixture of frustration and disappointment. The Padres' drought had reached 7,881 games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C5CF6A9EB1465D3AA6FB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141475283\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer discusses homer, win over Marlins</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Renfroe gets it right:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-804528C0EDB6908B0B899\">Hunter Renfroe</span>'s struggles against right-handed pitching feel like ancient history. Renfroe has torched right-handers lately, and he went 2-for-4 on Sunday. He doubled in the second inning before scoring the game's first run on Galvis' sacrifice fly. For some perspective: Renfroe was hitting .143/.226/.357 against righties before he landed on the disabled list with right elbow inflammation in April. He's hitting .458/.500/.750 in 26 plate appearances since.</p><p><b>Hometown Hoz:</b> Hosmer grew up watching the Marlins at Pro Player Stadium. He was in attendance for Game 7 of the 1997 World Series when Edgar Renteria walked off the Indians. On Sunday, he created a nice memory for himself <i>against</i> his hometown team. Hosmer crushed a 3-2 fastball from Marlins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CBA976567E4283E3E9E9B\">Jose Urena</span> just past the home run structure in left-center field. It was Hosmer's first career dinger against Miami.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D9214DB82A79855D1859D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140068783\">Video: SD@MIA: Hosmer launches a 2-run jack to left-center</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />At 34 years and 271 days old, Richard was attempting to become the oldest pitcher to throw a no-hitter since Randy Johnson's perfect game against the Braves in May 2004. Only 13 pitchers at Richard's age or older have completed a no-hitter. The last four -- Johnson, David Cone, David Wells and Dennis Martinez -- were all perfect games.</p><p><span class=\"token token-third-party token-third-party-twitter-embed\" id=\"token-31DC1509DB328F11CE0AC\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/Padres/status/1005890607770816513\">Tweet from @Padres: Quite a performance today by @CRThrees! \ud83d\udc4f pic.twitter.com/3sblYNJU7o</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99C6A24D2A561187A77BA\">Christian Villanueva</span> has struggled defensively this season, but he was sharp on Sunday with Richard on the mound. Then, in the eighth, he made arguably his best play of the season.</p><p>The rookie third baseman ranged to his left and dove for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-25B4946A8DC84F7E5F0AA\">Starlin Castro</span>'s grounder. Just as quickly, he rose to his feet and fired to first for the out. Padres reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C75FA378013EC28E08CA9\">Kirby Yates</span> clapped into his glove six times in appreciation.</p><p>\"Christian Villanueva played the best third base he's played in a long time,\" Green said. \"It was really good seeing him make some tough plays.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-410A7675F420C35808D87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140477183\">Video: SD@MIA: Villanueva slides for dazzling stop at third</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's been an unbelievable teammate to me, a partner in trying to build this and get this to where we want to be. And he's an unbelievable teammate to every guy in there. \u2026 He's exactly what you want for the young guys to see.\" -- <i>Green, on Richard</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2257B2C2C7580FB792CA6\">Jordan Lyles</span> needs to bounce back from his worst start of the season, in which he allowed eight runs and 11 hits over 4 1/3 innings against Atlanta. Otherwise, he has been solid since the Padres moved him into their rotation a month ago. Lyles takes the ball Monday in St. Louis with first pitch slated for 5:15 p.m. PT. The Cardinals counter with righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B8879991B0C58A8DE786\">Jack Flaherty</span>.</p>",

									"blurb" : "James Paxton fired seven innings, notching 10 strikeouts, to help the Mariners secure a 5-4 win over the Rays at Tropicana Field on Sunday afternoon. The Rays' offense jumped out to an early lead on Paxton, highlighted by a C.J. Cron solo homer in the fourth. Nathan Eovaldi battled a high pitch count in his home debut, but nearly left with the lead before giving up a two-run homer to Mike Zunino in the sixth. Kyle Seager's two-run home run in the seventh would provide the winning run, but Tampa Bay nearly tied the game in the bottom of the 9th, but the runner was thrown out at the plate.",
									"body" : "<p>ST. PETERSBURG -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E21184507C5F3D50DB6B7\">James Paxton</span> didn't have his no-hit stuff Sunday, but even a less-than-perfect Paxton is pretty impressive, as the big lefty shook off a mid-game cramp in his left forearm and struck out 10 over seven innings in a 5-4 victory over the Rays at Tropicana Field.</p><p>The Mariners' offense supported Paxton with a trio of home runs -- including a go-ahead two-run shot by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D45E9BEA4A13EF51DEBAA\">Kyle Seager</span> in the seventh -- as Seattle now heads home holding onto first place in the American League West at 41-24 after completing a 4-2 road trip.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-52486AA7D796B2255BFAC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140361183\">Video: SEA@TB: Seager smashes a 2-run homer deep to right</a></span></p><p>Paxton, who has dealt with a series of injuries in previous years, said he grew a little hesitant with some of his pitches in the fourth when he gave up two runs on a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B6862EBB8098F3A7844B2\">C.J. Cron</span> solo homer and a pair of doubles, but then worked through his forearm issue and retired 11 of the final 12 hitters he faced.</p><p>\"Once I figured out I was OK, I started letting it rip again,\" Paxton said. \"We checked it out and it's all fine. It was just a little something where I was getting in a bad position on my cutter, I think. I just have to get the hand back on top to allow it to be easier on my arm a little bit.\"</p><p>Paxton certainly isn't being easy on opposing batters, as he's 5-0 with a 1.87 ERA over his last eight starts.</p><p>\"If his struggles are seven innings and three runs, that's pretty good. We'll take that,\" said Seager. \"He's been incredible. They put him on the ropes a little the one inning, but he still kept his pitch count down and worked through seven. If that's your off-day, I'll take that guy on my team.\"</p><p>The Mariners have won 17 of their past 22 games and continue surviving on the edge. They're 21-9 in one-run games -- the most in the Majors. The Rays, on the flip side, have lost 17 one-run games, also the most in MLB.</p><p>\"We're winning, so that's all right,' said Seager. \"Whether we're winning by 10 or one, as long as we're winning, that's what we're worried about.\"</p><p>Seattle finished the season series with a 6-1 advantage over the Rays, with the six wins coming by a combined seven runs.</p><p>Paxton allowed three runs -- equaling the most he's given up in his past nine starts -- and five hits in a solid seven-inning outing. The lefty didn't walk a batter while racking up his fifth double-digit strikeout game of the season, and is now 6-1 with a 3.02 ERA in 14 starts.</p><p>Still, Paxton trailed 3-1 until <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E4172A6C64523DEA10F86\">Mike Zunino</span> tied it with a two-run homer in the sixth and Seager followed with his own two-run blast in the seventh.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B5C1EE76A29C4B9565FA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140158183\">Video: SEA@TB: Zunino crushes a 2-run home run to left</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A95061722FE9A77D1DFBF\">Nelson Cruz</span> got Seattle on the board with a leadoff homer off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5B69AE3AA1EF011AAD4B3\">Nathan Eovaldi</span> in the second and now shares the team lead with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-66A3AAAD4DD83FCA1879F\">Mitch Haniger</span> at 13. Seager now has a dozen homers and Zunino is at 10.</p><p> <span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-484BB1EF60EDADE1B5F87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139830383\">Video: SEA@TB: Cruz drills a solo homer to left-center field</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br />Former Rays closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F8E4C5685995705F88B92\">Alex Colome</span> allowed a run-scoring single in the eighth as Tampa Bay closed within a run, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C00E691B0A55A2DD43EB8\">Edwin Diaz</span> hung on for his MLB-leading 23rd save when Haniger got the final out by throwing out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9F9B02979A0DF3CC4778D\">Johnny Field</span> trying to score from first after Haniger momentarily lost a bloop single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC19D53DD6052509AD1A3\">Mallex Smith</span> on a sliding attempt.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CC0C3139115704DDCD9B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140757683\">Video: SEA@TB: Haniger nabs Field at home to end the game</a></span></p><p>\"We were playing no-doubles, and it was kind of a soft flare, so I just tried to make the catch. And when I knew I wasn't going to get to it, I tried to keep it in front,\" Haniger said. \"It kind of popped up and I didn't know where it was, but I found it and just threw home. I wasn't sure if he was going to go home or not, but I just came up firing.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Cruz is definitely heating up, which is a good sign for the Mariners' offense. The designated hitter has homered in back-to-back games, and has hit six home runs in his past 15 games after totaling seven in his first 37 games of the year. He's batted .327 (18-for-55) with 14 RBIs in that span to lift his season totals to .254 and 33 RBIs.</p><p>The Mariners 21 one-run wins are the most in a team's first 65 games of a season since data became available in 1908, according to Baseball-Reference.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4AA54B21F152FC8DF76AF\">Ben Gamel</span> has played left field most of the season. But with Haniger starting in center in order to give <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0A1129926CF5AB0429CBF\">Guillermo Heredia</span> a day off, Gamel moved to right and flashed some impressive leather, including a full-out diving catch of a foul ball down the line to get Paxton out of the fifth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F982C7EC74EC42B045292\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140128983\">Video: SEA@TB: Gamel goes airborne for a spectacular catch</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Sometimes, when Paxton is out there, he can dominate and it looks easy. [Today], it wasn't easy. 									"blurb" : "James Paxton fired seven innings, notching 10 strikeouts, to help the Mariners secure a 5-4 win over the Rays at Tropicana Field on Sunday afternoon. The Rays' offense jumped out to an early lead on Paxton, highlighted by a C.J. Cron solo homer in the fourth. Nathan Eovaldi battled a high pitch count in his home debut, but nearly left with the lead before giving up a two-run homer to Mike Zunino in the sixth. Kyle Seager's two-run home run in the seventh would provide the winning run, but Tampa Bay nearly tied the game in the bottom of the 9th, but the runner was thrown out at the plate.",
									"body" : "<p>ST. PETERSBURG -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E21184507C5F3D50DB6B7\">James Paxton</span> didn't have his no-hit stuff Sunday, but even a less-than-perfect Paxton is pretty impressive, as the big lefty shook off a mid-game cramp in his left forearm and struck out 10 over seven innings in a 5-4 victory over the Rays at Tropicana Field.</p><p>The Mariners' offense supported Paxton with a trio of home runs -- including a go-ahead two-run shot by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D45E9BEA4A13EF51DEBAA\">Kyle Seager</span> in the seventh -- as Seattle now heads home holding onto first place in the American League West at 41-24 after completing a 4-2 road trip.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-52486AA7D796B2255BFAC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140361183\">Video: SEA@TB: Seager smashes a 2-run homer deep to right</a></span></p><p>Paxton, who has dealt with a series of injuries in previous years, said he grew a little hesitant with some of his pitches in the fourth when he gave up two runs on a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B6862EBB8098F3A7844B2\">C.J. Cron</span> solo homer and a pair of doubles, but then worked through his forearm issue and retired 11 of the final 12 hitters he faced.</p><p>\"Once I figured out I was OK, I started letting it rip again,\" Paxton said. \"We checked it out and it's all fine. It was just a little something where I was getting in a bad position on my cutter, I think. I just have to get the hand back on top to allow it to be easier on my arm a little bit.\"</p><p>Paxton certainly isn't being easy on opposing batters, as he's 5-0 with a 1.87 ERA over his last eight starts.</p><p>\"If his struggles are seven innings and three runs, that's pretty good. We'll take that,\" said Seager. \"He's been incredible. They put him on the ropes a little the one inning, but he still kept his pitch count down and worked through seven. If that's your off-day, I'll take that guy on my team.\"</p><p>The Mariners have won 17 of their past 22 games and continue surviving on the edge. They're 21-9 in one-run games -- the most in the Majors. The Rays, on the flip side, have lost 17 one-run games, also the most in MLB.</p><p>\"We're winning, so that's all right,' said Seager. \"Whether we're winning by 10 or one, as long as we're winning, that's what we're worried about.\"</p><p>Seattle finished the season series with a 6-1 advantage over the Rays, with the six wins coming by a combined seven runs.</p><p>Paxton allowed three runs -- equaling the most he's given up in his past nine starts -- and five hits in a solid seven-inning outing. The lefty didn't walk a batter while racking up his fifth double-digit strikeout game of the season, and is now 6-1 with a 3.02 ERA in 14 starts.</p><p>Still, Paxton trailed 3-1 until <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E4172A6C64523DEA10F86\">Mike Zunino</span> tied it with a two-run homer in the sixth and Seager followed with his own two-run blast in the seventh.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B5C1EE76A29C4B9565FA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140158183\">Video: SEA@TB: Zunino crushes a 2-run home run to left</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A95061722FE9A77D1DFBF\">Nelson Cruz</span> got Seattle on the board with a leadoff homer off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5B69AE3AA1EF011AAD4B3\">Nathan Eovaldi</span> in the second and now shares the team lead with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-66A3AAAD4DD83FCA1879F\">Mitch Haniger</span> at 13. Seager now has a dozen homers and Zunino is at 10.</p><p> <span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-484BB1EF60EDADE1B5F87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139830383\">Video: SEA@TB: Cruz drills a solo homer to left-center field</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br />Former Rays closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F8E4C5685995705F88B92\">Alex Colome</span> allowed a run-scoring single in the eighth as Tampa Bay closed within a run, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C00E691B0A55A2DD43EB8\">Edwin Diaz</span> hung on for his MLB-leading 23rd save when Haniger got the final out by throwing out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9F9B02979A0DF3CC4778D\">Johnny Field</span> trying to score from first after Haniger momentarily lost a bloop single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC19D53DD6052509AD1A3\">Mallex Smith</span> on a sliding attempt.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CC0C3139115704DDCD9B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140757683\">Video: SEA@TB: Haniger nabs Field at home to end the game</a></span></p><p>\"We were playing no-doubles, and it was kind of a soft flare, so I just tried to make the catch. And when I knew I wasn't going to get to it, I tried to keep it in front,\" Haniger said. \"It kind of popped up and I didn't know where it was, but I found it and just threw home. I wasn't sure if he was going to go home or not, but I just came up firing.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Cruz is definitely heating up, which is a good sign for the Mariners' offense. The designated hitter has homered in back-to-back games, and has hit six home runs in his past 15 games after totaling seven in his first 37 games of the year. He's batted .327 (18-for-55) with 14 RBIs in that span to lift his season totals to .254 and 33 RBIs.</p><p>The Mariners 21 one-run wins are the most in a team's first 65 games of a season since data became available in 1908, according to Baseball-Reference.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4AA54B21F152FC8DF76AF\">Ben Gamel</span> has played left field most of the season. But with Haniger starting in center in order to give <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0A1129926CF5AB0429CBF\">Guillermo Heredia</span> a day off, Gamel moved to right and flashed some impressive leather, including a full-out diving catch of a foul ball down the line to get Paxton out of the fifth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F982C7EC74EC42B045292\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140128983\">Video: SEA@TB: Gamel goes airborne for a spectacular catch</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Sometimes, when Paxton is out there, he can dominate and it looks easy. [Today], it wasn't easy. It wasn't easy at all, but after giving up the three runs, he really buckled down.\" -- <i>Mariners manager Scott</i> <i>Servais</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD5788037C4E041210AA5\">Wade LeBlanc</span> (1-0, 2.95 ERA) gets the ball for Monday's 7:10 p.m. PT series opener at Safeco Field against Angels lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AD10645A4F87DE5EB0BAE\">Andrew Heaney</span> (3-4, 4.12). LeBlanc has allowed just nine earned runs in seven starts since moving into the rotation, with the Mariners going 5-2 in those games. The 33-year-old pitched 10 games for the Angels in 2014, but this will be the first time he's faced the Halos in his 10-year career.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "James Paxton fired seven innings, notching 10 strikeouts, to help the Mariners secure a 5-4 win over the Rays at Tropicana Field on Sunday afternoon. The Rays' offense jumped out to an early lead on Paxton, highlighted by a C.J. Cron solo homer in the fourth. Nathan Eovaldi battled a high pitch count in his home debut, but nearly left with the lead before giving up a two-run homer to Mike Zunino in the sixth. Kyle Seager's two-run home run in the seventh would provide the winning run, but Tampa Bay nearly tied the game in the bottom of the 9th, but the runner was thrown out at the plate.",
									"body" : "<p>ST. PETERSBURG -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E21184507C5F3D50DB6B7\">James Paxton</span> didn't have his no-hit stuff Sunday, but even a less-than-perfect Paxton is pretty impressive, as the big lefty shook off a mid-game cramp in his left forearm and struck out 10 over seven innings in a 5-4 victory over the Rays at Tropicana Field.</p><p>The Mariners' offense supported Paxton with a trio of home runs -- including a go-ahead two-run shot by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D45E9BEA4A13EF51DEBAA\">Kyle Seager</span> in the seventh -- as Seattle now heads home holding onto first place in the American League West at 41-24 after completing a 4-2 road trip.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-52486AA7D796B2255BFAC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140361183\">Video: SEA@TB: Seager smashes a 2-run homer deep to right</a></span></p><p>Paxton, who has dealt with a series of injuries in previous years, said he grew a little hesitant with some of his pitches in the fourth when he gave up two runs on a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B6862EBB8098F3A7844B2\">C.J. Cron</span> solo homer and a pair of doubles, but then worked through his forearm issue and retired 11 of the final 12 hitters he faced.</p><p>\"Once I figured out I was OK, I started letting it rip again,\" Paxton said. \"We checked it out and it's all fine. It was just a little something where I was getting in a bad position on my cutter, I think. I just have to get the hand back on top to allow it to be easier on my arm a little bit.\"</p><p>Paxton certainly isn't being easy on opposing batters, as he's 5-0 with a 1.87 ERA over his last eight starts.</p><p>\"If his struggles are seven innings and three runs, that's pretty good. We'll take that,\" said Seager. \"He's been incredible. They put him on the ropes a little the one inning, but he still kept his pitch count down and worked through seven. If that's your off-day, I'll take that guy on my team.\"</p><p>The Mariners have won 17 of their past 22 games and continue surviving on the edge. They're 21-9 in one-run games -- the most in the Majors. The Rays, on the flip side, have lost 17 one-run games, also the most in MLB.</p><p>\"We're winning, so that's all right,' said Seager. \"Whether we're winning by 10 or one, as long as we're winning, that's what we're worried about.\"</p><p>Seattle finished the season series with a 6-1 advantage over the Rays, with the six wins coming by a combined seven runs.</p><p>Paxton allowed three runs -- equaling the most he's given up in his past nine starts -- and five hits in a solid seven-inning outing. The lefty didn't walk a batter while racking up his fifth double-digit strikeout game of the season, and is now 6-1 with a 3.02 ERA in 14 starts.</p><p>Still, Paxton trailed 3-1 until <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E4172A6C64523DEA10F86\">Mike Zunino</span> tied it with a two-run homer in the sixth and Seager followed with his own two-run blast in the seventh.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B5C1EE76A29C4B9565FA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140158183\">Video: SEA@TB: Zunino crushes a 2-run home run to left</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A95061722FE9A77D1DFBF\">Nelson Cruz</span> got Seattle on the board with a leadoff homer off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5B69AE3AA1EF011AAD4B3\">Nathan Eovaldi</span> in the second and now shares the team lead with <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-66A3AAAD4DD83FCA1879F\">Mitch Haniger</span> at 13. Seager now has a dozen homers and Zunino is at 10.</p><p> <span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-484BB1EF60EDADE1B5F87\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139830383\">Video: SEA@TB: Cruz drills a solo homer to left-center field</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENT THAT MATTERED</b><br />Former Rays closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F8E4C5685995705F88B92\">Alex Colome</span> allowed a run-scoring single in the eighth as Tampa Bay closed within a run, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C00E691B0A55A2DD43EB8\">Edwin Diaz</span> hung on for his MLB-leading 23rd save when Haniger got the final out by throwing out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9F9B02979A0DF3CC4778D\">Johnny Field</span> trying to score from first after Haniger momentarily lost a bloop single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC19D53DD6052509AD1A3\">Mallex Smith</span> on a sliding attempt.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CC0C3139115704DDCD9B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140757683\">Video: SEA@TB: Haniger nabs Field at home to end the game</a></span></p><p>\"We were playing no-doubles, and it was kind of a soft flare, so I just tried to make the catch. And when I knew I wasn't going to get to it, I tried to keep it in front,\" Haniger said. \"It kind of popped up and I didn't know where it was, but I found it and just threw home. I wasn't sure if he was going to go home or not, but I just came up firing.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Cruz is definitely heating up, which is a good sign for the Mariners' offense. The designated hitter has homered in back-to-back games, and has hit six home runs in his past 15 games after totaling seven in his first 37 games of the year. He's batted .327 (18-for-55) with 14 RBIs in that span to lift his season totals to .254 and 33 RBIs.</p><p>The Mariners 21 one-run wins are the most in a team's first 65 games of a season since data became available in 1908, according to Baseball-Reference.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4AA54B21F152FC8DF76AF\">Ben Gamel</span> has played left field most of the season. But with Haniger starting in center in order to give <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0A1129926CF5AB0429CBF\">Guillermo Heredia</span> a day off, Gamel moved to right and flashed some impressive leather, including a full-out diving catch of a foul ball down the line to get Paxton out of the fifth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F982C7EC74EC42B045292\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140128983\">Video: SEA@TB: Gamel goes airborne for a spectacular catch</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Sometimes, when Paxton is out there, he can dominate and it looks easy. [Today], it wasn't easy. It wasn't easy at all, but after giving up the three runs, he really buckled down.\" -- <i>Mariners manager Scott</i> <i>Servais</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br /><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD5788037C4E041210AA5\">Wade LeBlanc</span> (1-0, 2.95 ERA) gets the ball for Monday's 7:10 p.m. PT series opener at Safeco Field against Angels lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AD10645A4F87DE5EB0BAE\">Andrew Heaney</span> (3-4, 4.12). LeBlanc has allowed just nine earned runs in seven starts since moving into the rotation, with the Mariners going 5-2 in those games. The 33-year-old pitched 10 games for the Angels in 2014, but this will be the first time he's faced the Halos in his 10-year career.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Billy Hamilton used his speed to score two runs and get two assists, and the Reds took 11 free passes to snap a 13-game losing streak to the Cardinals. Cincy scored four runs in the fourth and overcame some baserunning blunders to get Anthony DeSclafani his first win since 2016. Carlos Martinez struggled in his second start off the DL, walking seven and allowing five runs in 3 2/3 innings to take the loss.",
									"body" : "<p>CINCINNATI -- As many wonder why the Reds keep <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4BFDDDF8D2722BCE14B9E\">Billy Hamilton</span> in the starting lineup as he struggles to hit and the center fielder himself considers <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EB8B0C94A2755E7867D88\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/reds/news/reds-billy-hamilton-may-stop-switch-hitting/c-280628980\">giving up switch-hitting</a></span>, Sunday's game vs. the Cardinals underscored the reason: Hamilton's speed changes a game.</p><p>In a 6-3 win over the Cardinals at Great American Ball Park, Hamilton created two runs for Cincinnati at the plate and his defense took at least one away from St. Louis. That -- and a season-high 11 walks -- helped the Reds snap a 13-game losing streak against the Cardinals.</p><p>\"That's why he's so important,\" Reds interim manager Jim Riggleman said. \"With all due respect to everybody else that goes out there, nobody else can do the things that he does -- and I mean throughout the league. It was just really special. \u2026 He was on display today.\"</p><p>Leading off the third inning against Cardinals starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D54C011E1AB9599CC109C\">Carlos Martinez</span> as the Reds trailed, 2-0, Hamilton lifted a ball through the gap in left field, and turned on the afterburners to third base for a triple. According to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-070C5B4CF3C6A0525EF8A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, his sprint speed was 30.6 feet per second. Hamilton scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D98EE3E8307B8F045AFB2\">Scott Schebler</span>'s groundout to second base.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6F19EA16BAF005F8A9890\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140031383\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton legs out a triple in 3rd</a></span></p><p>\"Where he hit that ball, you don't see that many triples to left-center. Right-center is where the triples go,\" Riggleman noted about the cozy confines of the ballpark.</p><p>In the fourth inning, Hamilton worked a two-out walk from Martinez. He then took off on a ball-four wild pitch to Schebler and went from first base to third base without stopping. Once again, his speed was a force as Statcast\u2122 tracked him running at 31.2 feet per second. That's more than a foot per second over the 30-feet-per-second threshold, which is considered elite.</p><p>Hamilton scored the tying run on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F09F92BD69607DA9FA58A\">Tucker Barnhart</span>'s RBI single to set up the decisive four-run rally that gave Reds starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8895755EBF6C843217193\">Anthony DeSclafani</span> his first victory since Sept. 28, 2016.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6D2EAF6B75B43DAFAE6B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140275583\">Video: STL@CIN: Barnhart singles home Hamilton</a></span></p><p>\"I feel like it was a big win overall,\" Hamilton said. \"Everybody played well -- defensively and offensively. Disco did a really good job on the mound. The bullpen guys came in and did their job. As a whole today, I felt like we all contributed on some part.\"</p><p>In his second start since returning from the disabled list after missing all of 2017, DeSclafani gave up three runs (two earned) and 10 hits over five-plus innings, with two walks and six strikeouts.</p><p>Despite a good afternoon, DeSclafani spent a lot of time working out of jams. He gave up two singles in the second inning, but struck out the side. He faced the most trouble in the third inning, when a bases-loaded single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4DAA1881652DB60C7A69D\">Marcell Ozuna</span> went off the left-field wall -- and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5CE56514A2C581E3548BB\">Jesse Winker</span>'s glove. Initially, an out was called, but it was overturned on review. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5286121206A18BC880CA1\">Yadier Molina</span>'s sacrifice fly made it a 2-0 game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-22D7AA24310E5C01DD7A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139911483\">Video: STL@CIN: DeSclafani strands two</a></span></p><p>\"That's a lot of battling throughout a game,\" said DeSclafani, who came back after a strained left oblique sustained in March. \"You're not giving yourself a good chance to succeed giving up that many hits. It's definitely something to build on.\"</p><p>Hamilton's first superb defensive play of the day ended the first inning, when he raced to cut off a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0BC3D6C3440A378947E9E\">Jose Martinez</span> liner in the left-center-field gap and threw out Martinez trying to stretch the hit into a double. His second stellar defensive play bailed out DeSclafani in the fourth. Following a two-out single by Carlos Martinez, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1017E26B4547892961C93\">Matt Carpenter</span> hit a double to right-center field that Hamilton just missed with a dive. After the ball kicked off his glove and rolled away, Hamilton was able to retrieve it and get Martinez at the plate with a one-hop throw to Barnhart.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A5BB893872F8C8C67DB9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140087883\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton nabs Martinez at home</a></span></p><p>\"I could have just been mad and let the ball roll and not get to it in time to let him score,\" Hamilton said. \"But I knew I didn't make the play. I was already mad about not making the play. For me, just getting the ball and getting it in to save a run was big. Every day for me, I'm going to give 100 percent out there.\"</p><p>DeSclafani called plays like that \"fun to watch,\" but defensive plays like that, for pitchers like him who give up a lot of contact, are serious business, as well.</p><p>\"He's definitely saved my butt a couple of times out there today and previously, and I'm sure he will again down the road,\" DeSclafani said. \"As a pitcher, it helps build momentum into an inning. If he makes a great play for Out 1, you've kind of snuck away with an out right there if he's making a diving catch or robbing a home run.\"</p><p>In the eighth and ninth innings, Hamilton also made leaping catches at the fence to take away hits from the Cardinals. Those two late outs helped <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F97DBB4ABBD980541AC92\">Jared Hughes</span> work two scoreless innings in relief for his fourth save, with closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-14FD201B1642E4F7C22AE\">Raisel Iglesias</span> getting an extra day of rest.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DC4D65D0323293BD9FFBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141167683\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton makes fine jumping grab at the wall</a></span></p><p>\"That's what it's been about for me the whole time -- catching the balls out there when I get a chance to,\" Hamilton said. \"I tell the pitcher: If it's anywhere inside the park, and I can get to it, I'm making the effort to get to it. That's why they trust me out there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-864AD60BCF6F538F88098\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141195183\">Video: STL@CIN: Hughes induces ground out, locks down save</a></span></p><p>Hamilton is batting .193./287/.284 in 62 games this season. He's been batting ninth, behind the pitcher, since Riggleman took over from Bryan Price as manager in April. Before Sunday's game, he talked about simplifying things mentally and clearing his thoughts in the batter's box.</p><p>\"I've been through slumps like this before. I've also came out of slumps like this,\" Hamilton said. \"Once I get out of my head -- and I hope today is one of those days where I can get out of my head -- and not think about anything, just going up there like, 'It's me and you.' Just me and the pitcher and not worry about mechanics and not worry about any type of thing. Just go up there and relax and hit.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BE0C2097C4F2C19F66CA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953383\">Video: STL@CIN: Reds on Sunday's 6-3 win over Cardinals</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Gennett comes through:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6AA83D1F06D61FA4B04A0\">Scooter Gennett</span> made outs with two men on in both the first and third innings. But after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-284542EA81AA0A8F9F3BA\">Joey Votto</span> walk in the fourth, Gennett delivered with a two-run single to right field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD6AB438DB39A46267791\">Eugenio Suarez</span> added an RBI single to left to give the Reds a 5-2 lead. Suarez's 48 RBIs lead the National League, while Gennett is ranked second with 47.</p><p>\"The first two at-bats weren't too good,\" Gennett said. \"[Martinez] is a really good pitcher. He's got really good stuff. You mix that with Yadi behind the plate and the way he calls the game and catches the ball, it can be tough. It can be a grind up there. We were able to take advantage of key situations.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B073BFD6F6F1A54561AAA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140301983\">Video: STL@CIN: Gennett plates two with a bases-loaded hit</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's great. He's making the [plays] expected of him. When that ball is hit and he doesn't catch it, it's like, 'What happened?' That's a good thing. He's very valuable and he's a game-changer when he's on and doing his thing and able to get out there and play. We're just really fortunate to have him.\" <i> -- Gennett, on Hamilton's defense</i></p><p>\"He gets to some plays that most people don't get to. He is a good defender. The throw he made was great, too.\" <i> -- Cardinals manager Mike Matheny, also on Hamilton</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAYS OF THE DAY</b><br /><b>Ozuna gets a hit:</b> St. Louis' early lead came with the help of replay review. The Cardinals had the bases loaded in the top of the third inning when Ozuna lifted the ball towards the left-field wall. It initially appeared that Winker made a nice leaping catch before throwing to second base for an inning-ending double play. But after the Cardinals challenged the call on the field, replay review showed Winker caught the ball on a carom off the wall, and the call was overturned, giving Ozuna an RBI single.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2005A2B8966B82D1465B0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139996983\">Video: STL@CIN: Ozuna singles home a run after review</a></span></p><p><b>Safe at third base:</b> Hamilton was on first base after a two-out walk in the fourth inning when Martinez threw a wild pitch on ball four to Schebler. As the ball got away, Molina was too casual in retrieving it behind the plate. Hamilton didn't stop running until he slid headfirst into third base. The call was challenged by the Cardinals, but stood upon review. Matheny seemed to think Molina thought the ball hit Schebler.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EEC2396B3AA201D183BB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140257083\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton safe at third, call stands in 4th</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Reds resume Interleague Play with a two-game series vs. the Royals in Kansas City at 8:15 p.m. ET on Tuesday. Riggleman doesn't love the designated hitter, but will likely use it to give partial rests to regular players. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-914A425A0D1A67AE16FB4\">Sal Romano</span> will start for Cincinnati and try to turn things around. Romano has a 10.72 ERA over his last five starts, having given up 27 earned runs over the stretch of 22 2/3 innings. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2713B53B467F1FC0859A4\">Ian Kennedy</span> will pitch for the Royals.</p>",
