									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Billy Hamilton used his speed to score two runs and get two assists, and the Reds took 11 free passes to snap a 13-game losing streak to the Cardinals. Cincy scored four runs in the fourth and overcame some baserunning blunders to get Anthony DeSclafani his first win since 2016. Carlos Martinez struggled in his second start off the DL, walking seven and allowing five runs in 3 2/3 innings to take the loss.",
									"body" : "<p>CINCINNATI -- As many wonder why the Reds keep <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4BFDDDF8D2722BCE14B9E\">Billy Hamilton</span> in the starting lineup as he struggles to hit and the center fielder himself considers <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EB8B0C94A2755E7867D88\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/reds/news/reds-billy-hamilton-may-stop-switch-hitting/c-280628980\">giving up switch-hitting</a></span>, Sunday's game vs. the Cardinals underscored the reason: Hamilton's speed changes a game.</p><p>In a 6-3 win over the Cardinals at Great American Ball Park, Hamilton created two runs for Cincinnati at the plate and his defense took at least one away from St. Louis. That -- and a season-high 11 walks -- helped the Reds snap a 13-game losing streak against the Cardinals.</p><p>\"That's why he's so important,\" Reds interim manager Jim Riggleman said. \"With all due respect to everybody else that goes out there, nobody else can do the things that he does -- and I mean throughout the league. It was just really special. \u2026 He was on display today.\"</p><p>Leading off the third inning against Cardinals starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D54C011E1AB9599CC109C\">Carlos Martinez</span> as the Reds trailed, 2-0, Hamilton lifted a ball through the gap in left field, and turned on the afterburners to third base for a triple. According to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-070C5B4CF3C6A0525EF8A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, his sprint speed was 30.6 feet per second. Hamilton scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D98EE3E8307B8F045AFB2\">Scott Schebler</span>'s groundout to second base.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6F19EA16BAF005F8A9890\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140031383\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton legs out a triple in 3rd</a></span></p><p>\"Where he hit that ball, you don't see that many triples to left-center. Right-center is where the triples go,\" Riggleman noted about the cozy confines of the ballpark.</p><p>In the fourth inning, Hamilton worked a two-out walk from Martinez. He then took off on a ball-four wild pitch to Schebler and went from first base to third base without stopping. Once again, his speed was a force as Statcast\u2122 tracked him running at 31.2 feet per second. That's more than a foot per second over the 30-feet-per-second threshold, which is considered elite.</p><p>Hamilton scored the tying run on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F09F92BD69607DA9FA58A\">Tucker Barnhart</span>'s RBI single to set up the decisive four-run rally that gave Reds starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8895755EBF6C843217193\">Anthony DeSclafani</span> his first victory since Sept. 28, 2016.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6D2EAF6B75B43DAFAE6B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140275583\">Video: STL@CIN: Barnhart singles home Hamilton</a></span></p><p>\"I feel like it was a big win overall,\" Hamilton said. \"Everybody played well -- defensively and offensively. Disco did a really good job on the mound. The bullpen guys came in and did their job. As a whole today, I felt like we all contributed on some part.\"</p><p>In his second start since returning from the disabled list after missing all of 2017, DeSclafani gave up three runs (two earned) and 10 hits over five-plus innings, with two walks and six strikeouts.</p><p>Despite a good afternoon, DeSclafani spent a lot of time working out of jams. He gave up two singles in the second inning, but struck out the side. He faced the most trouble in the third inning, when a bases-loaded single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4DAA1881652DB60C7A69D\">Marcell Ozuna</span> went off the left-field wall -- and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5CE56514A2C581E3548BB\">Jesse Winker</span>'s glove. Initially, an out was called, but it was overturned on review. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5286121206A18BC880CA1\">Yadier Molina</span>'s sacrifice fly made it a 2-0 game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-22D7AA24310E5C01DD7A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139911483\">Video: STL@CIN: DeSclafani strands two</a></span></p><p>\"That's a lot of battling throughout a game,\" said DeSclafani, who came back after a strained left oblique sustained in March. \"You're not giving yourself a good chance to succeed giving up that many hits. It's definitely something to build on.\"</p><p>Hamilton's first superb defensive play of the day ended the first inning, when he raced to cut off a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0BC3D6C3440A378947E9E\">Jose Martinez</span> liner in the left-center-field gap and threw out Martinez trying to stretch the hit into a double. His second stellar defensive play bailed out DeSclafani in the fourth. Following a two-out single by Carlos Martinez, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1017E26B4547892961C93\">Matt Carpenter</span> hit a double to right-center field that Hamilton just missed with a dive. After the ball kicked off his glove and rolled away, Hamilton was able to retrieve it and get Martinez at the plate with a one-hop throw to Barnhart.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A5BB893872F8C8C67DB9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140087883\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton nabs Martinez at home</a></span></p><p>\"I could have just been mad and let the ball roll and not get to it in time to let him score,\" Hamilton said. \"But I knew I didn't make the play. I was already mad about not making the play. For me, just getting the ball and getting it in to save a run was big. Every day for me, I'm going to give 100 percent out there.\"</p><p>DeSclafani called plays like that \"fun to watch,\" but defensive plays like that, for pitchers like him who give up a lot of contact, are serious business, as well.</p><p>\"He's definitely saved my butt a couple of times out there today and previously, and I'm sure he will again down the road,\" DeSclafani said. \"As a pitcher, it helps build momentum into an inning. If he makes a great play for Out 1, you've kind of snuck away with an out right there if he's making a diving catch or robbing a home run.\"</p><p>In the eighth and ninth innings, Hamilton also made leaping catches at the fence to take away hits from the Cardinals. Those two late outs helped <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F97DBB4ABBD980541AC92\">Jared Hughes</span> work two scoreless innings in relief for his fourth save, with closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-14FD201B1642E4F7C22AE\">Raisel Iglesias</span> getting an extra day of rest.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DC4D65D0323293BD9FFBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141167683\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton makes fine jumping grab at the wall</a></span></p><p>\"That's what it's been about for me the whole time -- catching the balls out there when I get a chance to,\" Hamilton said. \"I tell the pitcher: If it's anywhere inside the park, and I can get to it, I'm making the effort to get to it. That's why they trust me out there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-864AD60BCF6F538F88098\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141195183\">Video: STL@CIN: Hughes induces ground out, locks down save</a></span></p><p>Hamilton is batting .193./287/.284 in 62 games this season. He's been batting ninth, behind the pitcher, since Riggleman took over from Bryan Price as manager in April. Before Sunday's game, he talked about simplifying things mentally and clearing his thoughts in the batter's box.</p><p>\"I've been through slumps like this before. I've also came out of slumps like this,\" Hamilton said. \"Once I get out of my head -- and I hope today is one of those days where I can get out of my head -- and not think about anything, just going up there like, 'It's me and you.' Just me and the pitcher and not worry about mechanics and not worry about any type of thing. Just go up there and relax and hit.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BE0C2097C4F2C19F66CA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953383\">Video: STL@CIN: Reds on Sunday's 6-3 win over Cardinals</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Gennett comes through:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6AA83D1F06D61FA4B04A0\">Scooter Gennett</span> made outs with two men on in both the first and third innings. But after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-284542EA81AA0A8F9F3BA\">Joey Votto</span> walk in the fourth, Gennett delivered with a two-run single to right field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD6AB438DB39A46267791\">Eugenio Suarez</span> added an RBI single to left to give the Reds a 5-2 lead. Suarez's 48 RBIs lead the National League, while Gennett is ranked second with 47.</p><p>\"The first two at-bats weren't too good,\" Gennett said. \"[Martinez] is a really good pitcher. He's got really good stuff. You mix that with Yadi behind the plate and the way he calls the game and catches the ball, it can be tough. It can be a grind up there. We were able to take advantage of key situations.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B073BFD6F6F1A54561AAA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140301983\">Video: STL@CIN: Gennett plates two with a bases-loaded hit</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's great. He's making the [plays] expected of him. When that ball is hit and he doesn't catch it, it's like, 'What happened?' That's a good thing. He's very valuable and he's a game-changer when he's on and doing his thing and able to get out there and play. We're just really fortunate to have him.\" <i> -- Gennett, on Hamilton's defense</i></p><p>\"He gets to some plays that most people don't get to. He is a good defender. The throw he made was great, too.\" <i> -- Cardinals manager Mike Matheny, also on Hamilton</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAYS OF THE DAY</b><br /><b>Ozuna gets a hit:</b> St. Louis' early lead came with the help of replay review. The Cardinals had the bases loaded in the top of the third inning when Ozuna lifted the ball towards the left-field wall. It initially appeared that Winker made a nice leaping catch before throwing to second base for an inning-ending double play. But after the Cardinals challenged the call on the field, replay review showed Winker caught the ball on a carom off the wall, and the call was overturned, giving Ozuna an RBI single.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2005A2B8966B82D1465B0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139996983\">Video: STL@CIN: Ozuna singles home a run after review</a></span></p><p><b>Safe at third base:</b> Hamilton was on first base after a two-out walk in the fourth inning when Martinez threw a wild pitch on ball four to Schebler. As the ball got away, Molina was too casual in retrieving it behind the plate. Hamilton didn't stop running until he slid headfirst into third base. The call was challenged by the Cardinals, but stood upon review. Matheny seemed to think Molina thought the ball hit Schebler.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EEC2396B3AA201D183BB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140257083\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton safe at third, call stands in 4th</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Reds resume Interleague Play with a two-game series vs. the Royals in Kansas City at 8:15 p.m. ET on Tuesday. Riggleman doesn't love the designated hitter, but will likely use it to give partial rests to regular players. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-914A425A0D1A67AE16FB4\">Sal Romano</span> will start for Cincinnati and try to turn things around. Romano has a 10.72 ERA over his last five starts, having given up 27 earned runs over the stretch of 22 2/3 innings. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2713B53B467F1FC0859A4\">Ian Kennedy</span> will pitch for the Royals.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Billy Hamilton used his speed to score two runs and get two assists, and the Reds took 11 free passes to snap a 13-game losing streak to the Cardinals. Cincy scored four runs in the fourth and overcame some baserunning blunders to get Anthony DeSclafani his first win since 2016. Carlos Martinez struggled in his second start off the DL, walking seven and allowing five runs in 3 2/3 innings to take the loss.",
									"body" : "<p>CINCINNATI -- As many wonder why the Reds keep <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4BFDDDF8D2722BCE14B9E\">Billy Hamilton</span> in the starting lineup as he struggles to hit and the center fielder himself considers <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EB8B0C94A2755E7867D88\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/reds/news/reds-billy-hamilton-may-stop-switch-hitting/c-280628980\">giving up switch-hitting</a></span>, Sunday's game vs. the Cardinals underscored the reason: Hamilton's speed changes a game.</p><p>In a 6-3 win over the Cardinals at Great American Ball Park, Hamilton created two runs for Cincinnati at the plate and his defense took at least one away from St. Louis. That -- and a season-high 11 walks -- helped the Reds snap a 13-game losing streak against the Cardinals.</p><p>\"That's why he's so important,\" Reds interim manager Jim Riggleman said. \"With all due respect to everybody else that goes out there, nobody else can do the things that he does -- and I mean throughout the league. It was just really special. \u2026 He was on display today.\"</p><p>Leading off the third inning against Cardinals starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D54C011E1AB9599CC109C\">Carlos Martinez</span> as the Reds trailed, 2-0, Hamilton lifted a ball through the gap in left field, and turned on the afterburners to third base for a triple. According to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-070C5B4CF3C6A0525EF8A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span>, his sprint speed was 30.6 feet per second. Hamilton scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D98EE3E8307B8F045AFB2\">Scott Schebler</span>'s groundout to second base.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6F19EA16BAF005F8A9890\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140031383\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton legs out a triple in 3rd</a></span></p><p>\"Where he hit that ball, you don't see that many triples to left-center. Right-center is where the triples go,\" Riggleman noted about the cozy confines of the ballpark.</p><p>In the fourth inning, Hamilton worked a two-out walk from Martinez. He then took off on a ball-four wild pitch to Schebler and went from first base to third base without stopping. Once again, his speed was a force as Statcast\u2122 tracked him running at 31.2 feet per second. That's more than a foot per second over the 30-feet-per-second threshold, which is considered elite.</p><p>Hamilton scored the tying run on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F09F92BD69607DA9FA58A\">Tucker Barnhart</span>'s RBI single to set up the decisive four-run rally that gave Reds starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8895755EBF6C843217193\">Anthony DeSclafani</span> his first victory since Sept. 28, 2016.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-6D2EAF6B75B43DAFAE6B5\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140275583\">Video: STL@CIN: Barnhart singles home Hamilton</a></span></p><p>\"I feel like it was a big win overall,\" Hamilton said. \"Everybody played well -- defensively and offensively. Disco did a really good job on the mound. The bullpen guys came in and did their job. As a whole today, I felt like we all contributed on some part.\"</p><p>In his second start since returning from the disabled list after missing all of 2017, DeSclafani gave up three runs (two earned) and 10 hits over five-plus innings, with two walks and six strikeouts.</p><p>Despite a good afternoon, DeSclafani spent a lot of time working out of jams. He gave up two singles in the second inning, but struck out the side. He faced the most trouble in the third inning, when a bases-loaded single by <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4DAA1881652DB60C7A69D\">Marcell Ozuna</span> went off the left-field wall -- and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5CE56514A2C581E3548BB\">Jesse Winker</span>'s glove. Initially, an out was called, but it was overturned on review. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5286121206A18BC880CA1\">Yadier Molina</span>'s sacrifice fly made it a 2-0 game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-22D7AA24310E5C01DD7A6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139911483\">Video: STL@CIN: DeSclafani strands two</a></span></p><p>\"That's a lot of battling throughout a game,\" said DeSclafani, who came back after a strained left oblique sustained in March. \"You're not giving yourself a good chance to succeed giving up that many hits. It's definitely something to build on.\"</p><p>Hamilton's first superb defensive play of the day ended the first inning, when he raced to cut off a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0BC3D6C3440A378947E9E\">Jose Martinez</span> liner in the left-center-field gap and threw out Martinez trying to stretch the hit into a double. His second stellar defensive play bailed out DeSclafani in the fourth. Following a two-out single by Carlos Martinez, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1017E26B4547892961C93\">Matt Carpenter</span> hit a double to right-center field that Hamilton just missed with a dive. After the ball kicked off his glove and rolled away, Hamilton was able to retrieve it and get Martinez at the plate with a one-hop throw to Barnhart.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A5BB893872F8C8C67DB9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140087883\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton nabs Martinez at home</a></span></p><p>\"I could have just been mad and let the ball roll and not get to it in time to let him score,\" Hamilton said. \"But I knew I didn't make the play. I was already mad about not making the play. For me, just getting the ball and getting it in to save a run was big. Every day for me, I'm going to give 100 percent out there.\"</p><p>DeSclafani called plays like that \"fun to watch,\" but defensive plays like that, for pitchers like him who give up a lot of contact, are serious business, as well.</p><p>\"He's definitely saved my butt a couple of times out there today and previously, and I'm sure he will again down the road,\" DeSclafani said. \"As a pitcher, it helps build momentum into an inning. If he makes a great play for Out 1, you've kind of snuck away with an out right there if he's making a diving catch or robbing a home run.\"</p><p>In the eighth and ninth innings, Hamilton also made leaping catches at the fence to take away hits from the Cardinals. Those two late outs helped <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F97DBB4ABBD980541AC92\">Jared Hughes</span> work two scoreless innings in relief for his fourth save, with closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-14FD201B1642E4F7C22AE\">Raisel Iglesias</span> getting an extra day of rest.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DC4D65D0323293BD9FFBE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141167683\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton makes fine jumping grab at the wall</a></span></p><p>\"That's what it's been about for me the whole time -- catching the balls out there when I get a chance to,\" Hamilton said. \"I tell the pitcher: If it's anywhere inside the park, and I can get to it, I'm making the effort to get to it. That's why they trust me out there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-864AD60BCF6F538F88098\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141195183\">Video: STL@CIN: Hughes induces ground out, locks down save</a></span></p><p>Hamilton is batting .193./287/.284 in 62 games this season. He's been batting ninth, behind the pitcher, since Riggleman took over from Bryan Price as manager in April. Before Sunday's game, he talked about simplifying things mentally and clearing his thoughts in the batter's box.</p><p>\"I've been through slumps like this before. I've also came out of slumps like this,\" Hamilton said. \"Once I get out of my head -- and I hope today is one of those days where I can get out of my head -- and not think about anything, just going up there like, 'It's me and you.' Just me and the pitcher and not worry about mechanics and not worry about any type of thing. Just go up there and relax and hit.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BE0C2097C4F2C19F66CA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953383\">Video: STL@CIN: Reds on Sunday's 6-3 win over Cardinals</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Gennett comes through:</b> <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6AA83D1F06D61FA4B04A0\">Scooter Gennett</span> made outs with two men on in both the first and third innings. But after a <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-284542EA81AA0A8F9F3BA\">Joey Votto</span> walk in the fourth, Gennett delivered with a two-run single to right field. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DD6AB438DB39A46267791\">Eugenio Suarez</span> added an RBI single to left to give the Reds a 5-2 lead. Suarez's 48 RBIs lead the National League, while Gennett is ranked second with 47.</p><p>\"The first two at-bats weren't too good,\" Gennett said. \"[Martinez] is a really good pitcher. He's got really good stuff. You mix that with Yadi behind the plate and the way he calls the game and catches the ball, it can be tough. It can be a grind up there. We were able to take advantage of key situations.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-B073BFD6F6F1A54561AAA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140301983\">Video: STL@CIN: Gennett plates two with a bases-loaded hit</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"He's great. He's making the [plays] expected of him. When that ball is hit and he doesn't catch it, it's like, 'What happened?' That's a good thing. He's very valuable and he's a game-changer when he's on and doing his thing and able to get out there and play. We're just really fortunate to have him.\" <i> -- Gennett, on Hamilton's defense</i></p><p>\"He gets to some plays that most people don't get to. He is a good defender. The throw he made was great, too.\" <i> -- Cardinals manager Mike Matheny, also on Hamilton</i></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAYS OF THE DAY</b><br /><b>Ozuna gets a hit:</b> St. Louis' early lead came with the help of replay review. The Cardinals had the bases loaded in the top of the third inning when Ozuna lifted the ball towards the left-field wall. It initially appeared that Winker made a nice leaping catch before throwing to second base for an inning-ending double play. But after the Cardinals challenged the call on the field, replay review showed Winker caught the ball on a carom off the wall, and the call was overturned, giving Ozuna an RBI single.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2005A2B8966B82D1465B0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139996983\">Video: STL@CIN: Ozuna singles home a run after review</a></span></p><p><b>Safe at third base:</b> Hamilton was on first base after a two-out walk in the fourth inning when Martinez threw a wild pitch on ball four to Schebler. As the ball got away, Molina was too casual in retrieving it behind the plate. Hamilton didn't stop running until he slid headfirst into third base. The call was challenged by the Cardinals, but stood upon review. Matheny seemed to think Molina thought the ball hit Schebler.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EEC2396B3AA201D183BB2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140257083\">Video: STL@CIN: Hamilton safe at third, call stands in 4th</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Reds resume Interleague Play with a two-game series vs. the Royals in Kansas City at 8:15 p.m. ET on Tuesday. Riggleman doesn't love the designated hitter, but will likely use it to give partial rests to regular players. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-914A425A0D1A67AE16FB4\">Sal Romano</span> will start for Cincinnati and try to turn things around. Romano has a 10.72 ERA over his last five starts, having given up 27 earned runs over the stretch of 22 2/3 innings. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2713B53B467F1FC0859A4\">Ian Kennedy</span> will pitch for the Royals.</p>",

									"blurb" : "The Phillies salvaged their series against the Brewers with a win Sunday afternoon at Citizens Bank Park. The Brewers made it a nail-biter in the ninth, putting the potential tying run on third with two outs, but Tommy Hunter closed the door, earning his first save of the year.",
									"body" : "<p>PHILADELPHIA -- The Phillies recalled their series-salvaging victory through a thick haze inside their clubhouse Sunday at Citizens Bank Park.</p><p>It seemed like the Phillies let their fog machine run a little longer following a 4-3 victory over the Brewers. They could be forgiven for that. They have not used their laser lights or fog machine much the past couple of weeks. They have celebrated only four victories since they moved into first place in the National League East on May 26. Sunday's victory snapped a four-game losing streak, improving them to just 4-10 since they held first for a day.</p><p>\"When you have a team that beats us twice in a row, you really kind of bear down,\" Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91A96AB72040DB15F0889\">Zach Eflin</span> said. \"You want to make sure you limit your mistakes and put a stop to what's happening.\"</p><p>It helped that the Phillies offense manufactured its runs. The Phillies had just four hits, scoring their runs on two groundouts, a sacrifice fly and a bases-loaded walk.</p><p>Good things can happen when the ball is put in play.</p><p>\"We've been really focused on putting together better at-bats,\" Phillies catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-02AE741A1216657EB1EA3\">Andrew Knapp</span> said. \"You're not always going to get hits, but if you can get on base and work counts and make the defense make plays, that's how you get through stretches like this where maybe you're not getting as many hits or scoring as many runs as you want. I thought it was really good for us today to put those at-bats together and put pressure on the defense.\"</p><p>The Phillies hit .237 with a .322 on-base percentage and a .398 slugging percentage through May 26. They have hit .204 with a .282 on-base percentage and a .309 slugging percentage in 14 games since. They have struck out more and walked less in that 4-10 stretch.</p><p>The Phillies entered the game with an MLB-high 25.9 percent strikeout rate, putting them on pace for the highest strikeout rate in baseball history. They are on pace for 1,574 strikeouts, which would shatter the franchise record (1,417) set last season and edge the 2017 Brewers (1,571) for the most strikeouts in baseball history.</p><p>\"We do strike out a lot, but that's just us,\" Phillies shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-525BAB7BA21A8C4171196\">J.P. Crawford</span> said. \"We do need to put the ball in play a lot more, I think. Everyone knows that, but we're not going to tell everyone that, because everyone already knows that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C3E6904C99D6546B4D1A6\">Cesar Hernandez</span> singled in the first inning and advanced to third on a throwing error from Brewers pitcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3B4A3A61505C0DAB9B296\">Brandon Woodruff</span>. He scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-131E682AB43965E3CD08D\">Rhys Hoskins</span>' fielder's choice to hand the Phillies a 1-0 lead.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EB80AFBF5ECC14E2B7A97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139919483\">Video: MI@PHI: Hoskins tallies a run on a groundout</a></span></p><p>The Phillies scored three runs in the fifth to take a 4-2 lead. After Crawford hit a leadoff single and Knapp reached on an error. Eflin dropped a sacrifice bunt. Crawford got a great jump and beat the throw to third.</p><p>\"I think that's probably the biggest moment of the game,\" Phillies manager Gabe Kapler said.</p><p>Hernandez worked a bases-loaded walk to score Crawford and tie the game, Hoskins' sacrifice fly scored Knapp to hand the Phillies a 3-2 lead and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A930040748B7AD6919CB7\">Odubel Herrera</span>'s groundout to first scored Eflin to make it 4-2.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BC7FA51814A6539D0E198\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140430883\">Video: MIL@PHI: Herrera hits a fielder's choice for a run</a></span></p><p>\"You only get a few hits during the game, but you score runs because you move runners and you drive runners in from third base with less than two outs,\" Kapler said. \"I thought that was well played all the way around.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Seranthony questions:</b> Kapler said he prefers to use <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD041A7D69BDD9C7BE3BB\">Seranthony Dominguez</span> in high-leverage situations, so it raised questions when he faced the bottom of the lineup in the seventh. Dominguez gave up an RBI single in the eighth, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05947572D06DE1DB8A298\">Luis Garcia</span> ran into trouble after retiring the first two batters in the ninth. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-40A59E33FB628C84D12A6\">Tommy Hunter</span> entered the game with runners on second and third, but got <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-81D360AE1966FE4A13498\">Christian Yelich</span> to ground out to end the game.</p><p>\"You might think because we're at the bottom of the order that might not be quite as high leverage,\" Kapler said. \"But the idea that we're going to use [Dominguez] for two innings, we know he's probably going to face the middle of the lineup, too. We just felt like there was no time to deploy him like then. We just wanted to preserve that lead.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F29ABE717AA237771A58D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141189083\">Video: MIL@PHI: Hunter locks down the win for the Phillies</a></span></p><p><b>Eflin recovers: </b>Eflin hit both <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7F4D4B46F0D3F3E6B948B\">Manny Pina</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD527524FFFCC134E68AD\">Eric Sogard</span> with pitches to load the bases with one out in the fifth inning. The Brewers sent <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-09331C5A2FC68D6A37C8C\">Hernan Perez</span> to the plate to hit for Woodruff, sensing the game could be on the line. Perez struck out swinging for the second out, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E8B97B8BC1CCFE672D84\">Lorenzo Cain</span> hit a ball off Eflin's right hand to score a run before Eflin walked Yelich to score another run to hand the Brewers a 2-1 lead. But <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1919A40BACD45BF456583\">Jesus Aguilar</span> struck out looking to end the inning. It could have been much worse for Eflin, who then struck out the side in the sixth. Eflin allowed three hits, two runs, one walk and struck out a career-high nine in six innings.</p><p>\"Extremely frustrated after the fifth, but being a starting pitcher you have to kind of swallow that and flush it down the toilet and come back out the next inning, and go right after them like I had been doing in the first four innings,\" Eflin said. \"Being able to come back out and put an end to what they were starting in the fifth inning was crucial.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-ABC0CCBD80F4B6A73E183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140385183\">Video: MIL@PHI: Eflin ends frame with a big strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Hoskins has 14 go-ahead RBIs this season. Entering Sunday, only Chicago's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF7DBB43C1BEC8B7E0583\">Anthony Rizzo</span> (15) and Colorado's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F9E4FCCF2958D99771DB5\">Nolan Arenado</span> (14) had 14 or more go-ahead RBIs in the National League.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Crawford singled to center field in the fifth and doubled to right-center field in the sixth. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-C95E7E943D1FADFDB65A2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> measured the exit velocity on those hits at 97.1 mph and 97.7 mph, respectively. Crawford entered the game with an average exit velocity of 85.9 mph on balls in play, which ranked 294th out of 355 players in baseball (minimum 50 plate appearances).</p><p>\"I'm feeling good,\" Crawford said. \"The confidence never dropped. I was just having some tough breaks. Today, I finally found some holes and found some open grass. Helped my team get a W.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8BC82DBF7A9FF9D0E9795\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142253483\">Video: MIL@PHI: Crawford splits the gap for a 2-out double</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"If you add pressure on it, that's just going to complicate your season. I have a lot of confidence in what I do and I have a lot of confidence in the guys. There's no saying if you leave Luis out there he punches him out on three pitches.\" -- <i>Hunter, on facing Yelich with the game on the line </i></p><p>He is the sixth Phillies pitcher to record a save this season.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />After an off-day on Monday, the Phillies resume action Tuesday when they open a three-game series against the Rockies at Citizens Bank Park at 7:05 p.m. ET. Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6EA6D99DA254E66ECA4BF\">Aaron Nola</span> (7-2, 2.35 ERA) faces Rockies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-325C6E6F0D4C917F612AC\">Jon Gray</span> (6-6, 5.66 ERA). Nola has allowed more than three runs in just one of 13 starts this season.</p>",

									"blurb" : "The Phillies salvaged their series against the Brewers with a win Sunday afternoon at Citizens Bank Park. The Brewers made it a nail-biter in the ninth, putting the potential tying run on third with two outs, but Tommy Hunter closed the door, earning his first save of the year.",
									"body" : "<p>PHILADELPHIA -- The Phillies recalled their series-salvaging victory through a thick haze inside their clubhouse Sunday at Citizens Bank Park.</p><p>It seemed like the Phillies let their fog machine run a little longer following a 4-3 victory over the Brewers. They could be forgiven for that. They have not used their laser lights or fog machine much the past couple of weeks. They have celebrated only four victories since they moved into first place in the National League East on May 26. Sunday's victory snapped a four-game losing streak, improving them to just 4-10 since they held first for a day.</p><p>\"When you have a team that beats us twice in a row, you really kind of bear down,\" Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91A96AB72040DB15F0889\">Zach Eflin</span> said. \"You want to make sure you limit your mistakes and put a stop to what's happening.\"</p><p>It helped that the Phillies offense manufactured its runs. The Phillies had just four hits, scoring their runs on two groundouts, a sacrifice fly and a bases-loaded walk.</p><p>Good things can happen when the ball is put in play.</p><p>\"We've been really focused on putting together better at-bats,\" Phillies catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-02AE741A1216657EB1EA3\">Andrew Knapp</span> said. \"You're not always going to get hits, but if you can get on base and work counts and make the defense make plays, that's how you get through stretches like this where maybe you're not getting as many hits or scoring as many runs as you want. I thought it was really good for us today to put those at-bats together and put pressure on the defense.\"</p><p>The Phillies hit .237 with a .322 on-base percentage and a .398 slugging percentage through May 26. They have hit .204 with a .282 on-base percentage and a .309 slugging percentage in 14 games since. They have struck out more and walked less in that 4-10 stretch.</p><p>The Phillies entered the game with an MLB-high 25.9 percent strikeout rate, putting them on pace for the highest strikeout rate in baseball history. They are on pace for 1,574 strikeouts, which would shatter the franchise record (1,417) set last season and edge the 2017 Brewers (1,571) for the most strikeouts in baseball history.</p><p>\"We do strike out a lot, but that's just us,\" Phillies shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-525BAB7BA21A8C4171196\">J.P. Crawford</span> said. \"We do need to put the ball in play a lot more, I think. Everyone knows that, but we're not going to tell everyone that, because everyone already knows that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C3E6904C99D6546B4D1A6\">Cesar Hernandez</span> singled in the first inning and advanced to third on a throwing error from Brewers pitcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3B4A3A61505C0DAB9B296\">Brandon Woodruff</span>. He scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-131E682AB43965E3CD08D\">Rhys Hoskins</span>' fielder's choice to hand the Phillies a 1-0 lead.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EB80AFBF5ECC14E2B7A97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139919483\">Video: MI@PHI: Hoskins tallies a run on a groundout</a></span></p><p>The Phillies scored three runs in the fifth to take a 4-2 lead. After Crawford hit a leadoff single and Knapp reached on an error. Eflin dropped a sacrifice bunt. Crawford got a great jump and beat the throw to third.</p><p>\"I think that's probably the biggest moment of the game,\" Phillies manager Gabe Kapler said.</p><p>Hernandez worked a bases-loaded walk to score Crawford and tie the game, Hoskins' sacrifice fly scored Knapp to hand the Phillies a 3-2 lead and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A930040748B7AD6919CB7\">Odubel Herrera</span>'s groundout to first scored Eflin to make it 4-2.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BC7FA51814A6539D0E198\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140430883\">Video: MIL@PHI: Herrera hits a fielder's choice for a run</a></span></p><p>\"You only get a few hits during the game, but you score runs because you move runners and you drive runners in from third base with less than two outs,\" Kapler said. \"I thought that was well played all the way around.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Seranthony questions:</b> Kapler said he prefers to use <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD041A7D69BDD9C7BE3BB\">Seranthony Dominguez</span> in high-leverage situations, so it raised questions when he faced the bottom of the lineup in the seventh. Dominguez gave up an RBI single in the eighth, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05947572D06DE1DB8A298\">Luis Garcia</span> ran into trouble after retiring the first two batters in the ninth. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-40A59E33FB628C84D12A6\">Tommy Hunter</span> entered the game with runners on second and third, but got <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-81D360AE1966FE4A13498\">Christian Yelich</span> to ground out to end the game.</p><p>\"You might think because we're at the bottom of the order that might not be quite as high leverage,\" Kapler said. \"But the idea that we're going to use [Dominguez] for two innings, we know he's probably going to face the middle of the lineup, too. We just felt like there was no time to deploy him like then. We just wanted to preserve that lead.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F29ABE717AA237771A58D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141189083\">Video: MIL@PHI: Hunter locks down the win for the Phillies</a></span></p><p><b>Eflin recovers: </b>Eflin hit both <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7F4D4B46F0D3F3E6B948B\">Manny Pina</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD527524FFFCC134E68AD\">Eric Sogard</span> with pitches to load the bases with one out in the fifth inning. The Brewers sent <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-09331C5A2FC68D6A37C8C\">Hernan Perez</span> to the plate to hit for Woodruff, sensing the game could be on the line. Perez struck out swinging for the second out, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E8B97B8BC1CCFE672D84\">Lorenzo Cain</span> hit a ball off Eflin's right hand to score a run before Eflin walked Yelich to score another run to hand the Brewers a 2-1 lead. But <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1919A40BACD45BF456583\">Jesus Aguilar</span> struck out looking to end the inning. It could have been much worse for Eflin, who then struck out the side in the sixth. Eflin allowed three hits, two runs, one walk and struck out a career-high nine in six innings.</p><p>\"Extremely frustrated after the fifth, but being a starting pitcher you have to kind of swallow that and flush it down the toilet and come back out the next inning, and go right after them like I had been doing in the first four innings,\" Eflin said. \"Being able to come back out and put an end to what they were starting in the fifth inning was crucial.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-ABC0CCBD80F4B6A73E183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140385183\">Video: MIL@PHI: Eflin ends frame with a big strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Hoskins has 14 go-ahead RBIs this season. Entering Sunday, only Chicago's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF7DBB43C1BEC8B7E0583\">Anthony Rizzo</span> (15) and Colorado's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F9E4FCCF2958D99771DB5\">Nolan Arenado</span> (14) had 14 or more go-ahead RBIs in the National League.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Crawford singled to center field in the fifth and doubled to right-center field in the sixth. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-C95E7E943D1FADFDB65A2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> measured the exit velocity on those hits at 97.1 mph and 97.7 mph, respectively. Crawford entered the game with an average exit velocity of 85.9 mph on balls in play, which ranked 294th out of 355 players in baseball (minimum 50 plate appearances).</p><p>\"I'm feeling good,\" Crawford said. \"The confidence never dropped. I was just having some tough breaks. Today, I finally found some holes and found some open grass. Helped my team get a W.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8BC82DBF7A9FF9D0E9795\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142253483\">Video: MIL@PHI: Crawford splits the gap for a 2-out double</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"If you add pressure on it, that's just going to complicate your season. I have a lot of confidence in what I do and I have a lot of confidence in the guys. There's no saying if you leave Luis out there he punches him out on three pitches.\" -- <i>Hunter, on facing Yelich with the game on the line </i></p><p>He is the sixth Phillies pitcher to record a save this season.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />After an off-day on Monday, the Phillies resume action Tuesday when they open a three-game series against the Rockies at Citizens Bank Park at 7:05 p.m. ET. Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6EA6D99DA254E66ECA4BF\">Aaron Nola</span> (7-2, 2.35 ERA) faces Rockies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-325C6E6F0D4C917F612AC\">Jon Gray</span> (6-6, 5.66 ERA). Nola has allowed more than three runs in just one of 13 starts this season.</p>",

									"blurb" : "The Phillies salvaged their series against the Brewers with a win Sunday afternoon at Citizens Bank Park. The Brewers made it a nail-biter in the ninth, putting the potential tying run on third with two outs, but Tommy Hunter closed the door, earning his first save of the year.",
									"body" : "<p>PHILADELPHIA -- The Phillies recalled their series-salvaging victory through a thick haze inside their clubhouse Sunday at Citizens Bank Park.</p><p>It seemed like the Phillies let their fog machine run a little longer following a 4-3 victory over the Brewers. They could be forgiven for that. They have not used their laser lights or fog machine much the past couple of weeks. They have celebrated only four victories since they moved into first place in the National League East on May 26. Sunday's victory snapped a four-game losing streak, improving them to just 4-10 since they held first for a day.</p><p>\"When you have a team that beats us twice in a row, you really kind of bear down,\" Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91A96AB72040DB15F0889\">Zach Eflin</span> said. \"You want to make sure you limit your mistakes and put a stop to what's happening.\"</p><p>It helped that the Phillies offense manufactured its runs. The Phillies had just four hits, scoring their runs on two groundouts, a sacrifice fly and a bases-loaded walk.</p><p>Good things can happen when the ball is put in play.</p><p>\"We've been really focused on putting together better at-bats,\" Phillies catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-02AE741A1216657EB1EA3\">Andrew Knapp</span> said. \"You're not always going to get hits, but if you can get on base and work counts and make the defense make plays, that's how you get through stretches like this where maybe you're not getting as many hits or scoring as many runs as you want. I thought it was really good for us today to put those at-bats together and put pressure on the defense.\"</p><p>The Phillies hit .237 with a .322 on-base percentage and a .398 slugging percentage through May 26. They have hit .204 with a .282 on-base percentage and a .309 slugging percentage in 14 games since. They have struck out more and walked less in that 4-10 stretch.</p><p>The Phillies entered the game with an MLB-high 25.9 percent strikeout rate, putting them on pace for the highest strikeout rate in baseball history. They are on pace for 1,574 strikeouts, which would shatter the franchise record (1,417) set last season and edge the 2017 Brewers (1,571) for the most strikeouts in baseball history.</p><p>\"We do strike out a lot, but that's just us,\" Phillies shortstop <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-525BAB7BA21A8C4171196\">J.P. Crawford</span> said. \"We do need to put the ball in play a lot more, I think. Everyone knows that, but we're not going to tell everyone that, because everyone already knows that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C3E6904C99D6546B4D1A6\">Cesar Hernandez</span> singled in the first inning and advanced to third on a throwing error from Brewers pitcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3B4A3A61505C0DAB9B296\">Brandon Woodruff</span>. He scored on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-131E682AB43965E3CD08D\">Rhys Hoskins</span>' fielder's choice to hand the Phillies a 1-0 lead.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-EB80AFBF5ECC14E2B7A97\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2139919483\">Video: MI@PHI: Hoskins tallies a run on a groundout</a></span></p><p>The Phillies scored three runs in the fifth to take a 4-2 lead. After Crawford hit a leadoff single and Knapp reached on an error. Eflin dropped a sacrifice bunt. Crawford got a great jump and beat the throw to third.</p><p>\"I think that's probably the biggest moment of the game,\" Phillies manager Gabe Kapler said.</p><p>Hernandez worked a bases-loaded walk to score Crawford and tie the game, Hoskins' sacrifice fly scored Knapp to hand the Phillies a 3-2 lead and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A930040748B7AD6919CB7\">Odubel Herrera</span>'s groundout to first scored Eflin to make it 4-2.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-BC7FA51814A6539D0E198\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140430883\">Video: MIL@PHI: Herrera hits a fielder's choice for a run</a></span></p><p>\"You only get a few hits during the game, but you score runs because you move runners and you drive runners in from third base with less than two outs,\" Kapler said. \"I thought that was well played all the way around.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Seranthony questions:</b> Kapler said he prefers to use <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD041A7D69BDD9C7BE3BB\">Seranthony Dominguez</span> in high-leverage situations, so it raised questions when he faced the bottom of the lineup in the seventh. Dominguez gave up an RBI single in the eighth, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-05947572D06DE1DB8A298\">Luis Garcia</span> ran into trouble after retiring the first two batters in the ninth. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-40A59E33FB628C84D12A6\">Tommy Hunter</span> entered the game with runners on second and third, but got <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-81D360AE1966FE4A13498\">Christian Yelich</span> to ground out to end the game.</p><p>\"You might think because we're at the bottom of the order that might not be quite as high leverage,\" Kapler said. \"But the idea that we're going to use [Dominguez] for two innings, we know he's probably going to face the middle of the lineup, too. We just felt like there was no time to deploy him like then. We just wanted to preserve that lead.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-F29ABE717AA237771A58D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141189083\">Video: MIL@PHI: Hunter locks down the win for the Phillies</a></span></p><p><b>Eflin recovers: </b>Eflin hit both <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7F4D4B46F0D3F3E6B948B\">Manny Pina</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD527524FFFCC134E68AD\">Eric Sogard</span> with pitches to load the bases with one out in the fifth inning. The Brewers sent <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-09331C5A2FC68D6A37C8C\">Hernan Perez</span> to the plate to hit for Woodruff, sensing the game could be on the line. Perez struck out swinging for the second out, then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E8B97B8BC1CCFE672D84\">Lorenzo Cain</span> hit a ball off Eflin's right hand to score a run before Eflin walked Yelich to score another run to hand the Brewers a 2-1 lead. But <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1919A40BACD45BF456583\">Jesus Aguilar</span> struck out looking to end the inning. It could have been much worse for Eflin, who then struck out the side in the sixth. Eflin allowed three hits, two runs, one walk and struck out a career-high nine in six innings.</p><p>\"Extremely frustrated after the fifth, but being a starting pitcher you have to kind of swallow that and flush it down the toilet and come back out the next inning, and go right after them like I had been doing in the first four innings,\" Eflin said. \"Being able to come back out and put an end to what they were starting in the fifth inning was crucial.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-ABC0CCBD80F4B6A73E183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140385183\">Video: MIL@PHI: Eflin ends frame with a big strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Hoskins has 14 go-ahead RBIs this season. Entering Sunday, only Chicago's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF7DBB43C1BEC8B7E0583\">Anthony Rizzo</span> (15) and Colorado's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F9E4FCCF2958D99771DB5\">Nolan Arenado</span> (14) had 14 or more go-ahead RBIs in the National League.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />Crawford singled to center field in the fifth and doubled to right-center field in the sixth. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-C95E7E943D1FADFDB65A2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> measured the exit velocity on those hits at 97.1 mph and 97.7 mph, respectively. Crawford entered the game with an average exit velocity of 85.9 mph on balls in play, which ranked 294th out of 355 players in baseball (minimum 50 plate appearances).</p><p>\"I'm feeling good,\" Crawford said. \"The confidence never dropped. I was just having some tough breaks. Today, I finally found some holes and found some open grass. Helped my team get a W.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8BC82DBF7A9FF9D0E9795\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142253483\">Video: MIL@PHI: Crawford splits the gap for a 2-out double</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"If you add pressure on it, that's just going to complicate your season. I have a lot of confidence in what I do and I have a lot of confidence in the guys. There's no saying if you leave Luis out there he punches him out on three pitches.\" -- <i>Hunter, on facing Yelich with the game on the line </i></p><p>He is the sixth Phillies pitcher to record a save this season.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />After an off-day on Monday, the Phillies resume action Tuesday when they open a three-game series against the Rockies at Citizens Bank Park at 7:05 p.m. ET. Phillies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6EA6D99DA254E66ECA4BF\">Aaron Nola</span> (7-2, 2.35 ERA) faces Rockies right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-325C6E6F0D4C917F612AC\">Jon Gray</span> (6-6, 5.66 ERA). Nola has allowed more than three runs in just one of 13 starts this season.</p>",

									"body" : "<p>MINNEAPOLIS -- Before Sunday's game, manager Paul Molitor said he is trying to \"be creative without being foolish\" when it comes to filling out his lineup card each day.</p><p>With the Twins hindered by a handful of injuries to everyday players, Molitor unveiled one of his most creative batting orders of the season on Sunday, and it paid major dividends. The Twins topped the Angels, 7-5, at Target Field to salvage a win after scoring just three runs in the first two games of the series.</p><p>\"It feels good,\" Molitor said. \"[Wins] have been hard to come by. As much as we've had a winning homestand, it kind of feels like a roller coaster. When you lose, it's been tough because the games have felt winnable. That's kind of been the theme. All of our losses feel like, 'Man, just so close and not finding ways.'''</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2D1004923EAF1526F8C81\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141842283\">Video: LAA@MIN: Molitor on battling, contributions from all</a></span></p><p>In his second game back from Triple-A Rochester, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D1C936FAD8E7FB2960A3\">Jake Cave</span> went 3-for-4 and launched a 418-foot, two-run homer in the fifth inning. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AE13DCA77AB5E5C238D96\">Brian Dozier</span> out of the lineup for a rest day, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-965804858147E711BBDA7\">Eduardo Escobar</span> made his first start at second base since August and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CED72F9484959B5E5E8A3\">Robbie Grossman</span> batted leadoff for the third time this season.</p><p>The unconventional combination produced seven runs in the first six innings and helped alleviate some early struggles from Twins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-748E8715DE7C703B363BD\">Fernando Romero</span>.</p><p>Romero walked the Angels' first batter of the game, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C1AA59A330DD13689138B\">Ian Kinsler</span>, on five pitches, and the outing nearly snowballed from there. He threw a wild pitch to <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA38780E0D36911690096\">Mike Trout</span> and then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E9BAFFD7C98371BA1389D\">Mitch Garver</span> let another pitch by, allowing Kinsler to advance to third. Romero then intentionally walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4916780C4CF9BD3B22099\">Justin Upton</span> after he ran him up to a 3-0 count, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-710FCFBA6F2FE3A761E99\">Albert Pujols</span> followed with an RBI single to center field.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-30AAEC5419E5CFBE0619B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140047783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Pujols singles, passes Musial in career RBIs</a></span></p><p>In the fourth inning, Romero put on four of the first five batters he faced and had already surrendered two runs with the Angels' 2-3-4 hitters due up, but he worked his way out of the jam.</p><p>\"I think he had Trout and Pujols coming up in the situation, where it could have turned into a big inning,\" Molitor said. \"He did a nice job there. I was trying to give him an opportunity the best I could and it worked out today. It might not in the future, but sometimes you've got to give an opportunity to a guy to get out of his own mess.\"</p><p>In five innings, Romero struck out five, but threw two wild pitches, walked two batters and hit two more. Minnesota's offense came to his rescue immediately and didn't let up the rest of the afternoon.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C079D392173F6252A9B96\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140271583\">Video: LAA@MIN: Romero induces a lineout, strands a pair</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8B1CBDAB3AEBB9A166A2\">Logan Morrison</span> blasted a two-run homer in the bottom of the first to give the Twins the lead back. In the fifth inning, Garver doubled to right and Cave followed with a single to drive him home. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71491BF388DB005F10385\">Ehire Adrianza</span> then drilled a triple to the right-field corner and later scored when Escobar smacked his 25th double of the season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0C2DC1EE6F9A4340DFCA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140642783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Adrianza adds to lead with an RBI triple</a></span></p><p>After drawing a walk in the sixth, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5D62DC906634BE78EFCB4\">Max Kepler</span> stole his first base of the season. He didn't stay put long. Two batters later, Cave deposited <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AA104BAE32C34D8AFA1A2\">Jim Johnson</span>'s 3-2 fastball into the Minnesota bullpen.</p><p>\"It definitely made my job easier when I was coming up to bat with guys on second base or guys just drew walks,\" Cave said. \"I could stand on deck and time up some pitches and that kind of thing. That's where hitters help each other out and where stuff gets kind of contagious.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA8C7775F48B125F296AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140986983\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave drills a two-run homer to center</a></span></p><p>A Minnesota bullpen quartet of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6702818DD29E09D9A22A7\">Taylor Rogers</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99BC3D2DE1717F82E2999\">Addison Reed</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B3E5E87E867AE2D9B27AC\">Zach Duke</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-252B7A2AD40FEA145BD85\">Fernando Rodney</span> each threw an inning to finish off the last half of the game. Rodney allowed the first two runners he faced to reach base in the ninth, and later gave up a two-run single to Pujols. Rodney then walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E8FDD64E18F3710D7EE89\">Luis Valbuena</span> to bring the go-ahead run to the plate. But he forced <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC53EE2DE0CA847341D8B\">Zack Cozart</span> to pop out and end the game.</p><p>The Twins are 26-13 this season in games in which they score four or more runs. They are 14-11 in games in which they score first.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1A23A0729B946F42B568D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307383\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave, Escobar on hot hitting in the win</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I didn't know, I just knew I hit it well. I put my head down and, obviously, I know who's out there in center field. I saw him kind of jump and I didn't see the ball, but I heard the crowd start cheering, so I was like, 'Oh, I think that ball got by him.' So that was cool. I know I'm probably not allowed to say this, but he's probably my favorite player. So to be able to hit some balls out there to him today and to be on the same field as him, it was an honor, really.\" <i>-- Cave, on his eighth-inning double over the head of a leaping Trout</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-51C9117EDCCFBD4113183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307083\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave rips a double, picks up his third hit</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Twins will get a day off on Monday before traveling to Detroit for a three-game set with the Tigers. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1A7FC9AA0C41A32752294\">Jake Odorizzi</span> will get the start for Minnesota in search of his fourth win of the season. He will square off with Detroit lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E258FBC355B5959040BC\">Blaine Hardy</span> (2-1, 3.66 ERA).</p>",

									"blurb" : "Twins manager Paul Molitor unveiled one of his most creative batting orders of the season on Sunday, and it paid major dividends. The Twins topped the Angels, 7-5 at Target Field to salvage a win after scoring just three runs in the first two games of the series. 									"body" : "<p>MINNEAPOLIS -- Before Sunday's game, manager Paul Molitor said he is trying to \"be creative without being foolish\" when it comes to filling out his lineup card each day.</p><p>With the Twins hindered by a handful of injuries to everyday players, Molitor unveiled one of his most creative batting orders of the season on Sunday, and it paid major dividends. The Twins topped the Angels, 7-5, at Target Field to salvage a win after scoring just three runs in the first two games of the series.</p><p>\"It feels good,\" Molitor said. \"[Wins] have been hard to come by. As much as we've had a winning homestand, it kind of feels like a roller coaster. When you lose, it's been tough because the games have felt winnable. That's kind of been the theme. All of our losses feel like, 'Man, just so close and not finding ways.'''</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2D1004923EAF1526F8C81\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141842283\">Video: LAA@MIN: Molitor on battling, contributions from all</a></span></p><p>In his second game back from Triple-A Rochester, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D1C936FAD8E7FB2960A3\">Jake Cave</span> went 3-for-4 and launched a 418-foot, two-run homer in the fifth inning. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AE13DCA77AB5E5C238D96\">Brian Dozier</span> out of the lineup for a rest day, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-965804858147E711BBDA7\">Eduardo Escobar</span> made his first start at second base since August and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CED72F9484959B5E5E8A3\">Robbie Grossman</span> batted leadoff for the third time this season.</p><p>The unconventional combination produced seven runs in the first six innings and helped alleviate some early struggles from Twins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-748E8715DE7C703B363BD\">Fernando Romero</span>.</p><p>Romero walked the Angels' first batter of the game, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C1AA59A330DD13689138B\">Ian Kinsler</span>, on five pitches, and the outing nearly snowballed from there. He threw a wild pitch to <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA38780E0D36911690096\">Mike Trout</span> and then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E9BAFFD7C98371BA1389D\">Mitch Garver</span> let another pitch by, allowing Kinsler to advance to third. Romero then intentionally walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4916780C4CF9BD3B22099\">Justin Upton</span> after he ran him up to a 3-0 count, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-710FCFBA6F2FE3A761E99\">Albert Pujols</span> followed with an RBI single to center field.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-30AAEC5419E5CFBE0619B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140047783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Pujols singles, passes Musial in career RBIs</a></span></p><p>In the fourth inning, Romero put on four of the first five batters he faced and had already surrendered two runs with the Angels' 2-3-4 hitters due up, but he worked his way out of the jam.</p><p>\"I think he had Trout and Pujols coming up in the situation, where it could have turned into a big inning,\" Molitor said. \"He did a nice job there. I was trying to give him an opportunity the best I could and it worked out today. It might not in the future, but sometimes you've got to give an opportunity to a guy to get out of his own mess.\"</p><p>In five innings, Romero struck out five, but threw two wild pitches, walked two batters and hit two more. Minnesota's offense came to his rescue immediately and didn't let up the rest of the afternoon.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C079D392173F6252A9B96\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140271583\">Video: LAA@MIN: Romero induces a lineout, strands a pair</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8B1CBDAB3AEBB9A166A2\">Logan Morrison</span> blasted a two-run homer in the bottom of the first to give the Twins the lead back. In the fifth inning, Garver doubled to right and Cave followed with a single to drive him home. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71491BF388DB005F10385\">Ehire Adrianza</span> then drilled a triple to the right-field corner and later scored when Escobar smacked his 25th double of the season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0C2DC1EE6F9A4340DFCA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140642783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Adrianza adds to lead with an RBI triple</a></span></p><p>After drawing a walk in the sixth, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5D62DC906634BE78EFCB4\">Max Kepler</span> stole his first base of the season. He didn't stay put long. Two batters later, Cave deposited <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AA104BAE32C34D8AFA1A2\">Jim Johnson</span>'s 3-2 fastball into the Minnesota bullpen.</p><p>\"It definitely made my job easier when I was coming up to bat with guys on second base or guys just drew walks,\" Cave said. \"I could stand on deck and time up some pitches and that kind of thing. That's where hitters help each other out and where stuff gets kind of contagious.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA8C7775F48B125F296AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140986983\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave drills a two-run homer to center</a></span></p><p>A Minnesota bullpen quartet of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6702818DD29E09D9A22A7\">Taylor Rogers</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99BC3D2DE1717F82E2999\">Addison Reed</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B3E5E87E867AE2D9B27AC\">Zach Duke</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-252B7A2AD40FEA145BD85\">Fernando Rodney</span> each threw an inning to finish off the last half of the game. Rodney allowed the first two runners he faced to reach base in the ninth, and later gave up a two-run single to Pujols. Rodney then walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E8FDD64E18F3710D7EE89\">Luis Valbuena</span> to bring the go-ahead run to the plate. But he forced <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC53EE2DE0CA847341D8B\">Zack Cozart</span> to pop out and end the game.</p><p>The Twins are 26-13 this season in games in which they score four or more runs. They are 14-11 in games in which they score first.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1A23A0729B946F42B568D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307383\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave, Escobar on hot hitting in the win</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I didn't know, I just knew I hit it well. I put my head down and, obviously, I know who's out there in center field. I saw him kind of jump and I didn't see the ball, but I heard the crowd start cheering, so I was like, 'Oh, I think that ball got by him.' So that was cool. I know I'm probably not allowed to say this, but he's probably my favorite player. So to be able to hit some balls out there to him today and to be on the same field as him, it was an honor, really.\" <i>-- Cave, on his eighth-inning double over the head of a leaping Trout</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-51C9117EDCCFBD4113183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307083\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave rips a double, picks up his third hit</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Twins will get a day off on Monday before traveling to Detroit for a three-game set with the Tigers. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1A7FC9AA0C41A32752294\">Jake Odorizzi</span> will get the start for Minnesota in search of his fourth win of the season. He will square off with Detroit lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E258FBC355B5959040BC\">Blaine Hardy</span> (2-1, 3.66 ERA).</p>",

									"blurb" : "Twins manager Paul Molitor unveiled one of his most creative batting orders of the season on Sunday, and it paid major dividends. The Twins topped the Angels, 7-5 at Target Field to salvage a win after scoring just three runs in the first two games of the series. Jake Cave went 3-for-4 and launched a 418-foot, two-run homer in the fifth inning. Logan Morrison also hit a two-run homer. The unconventional combination produced seven runs in the first six innings and helped alleviate some early struggles from Twins starter Fernando Romero.",
									"body" : "<p>MINNEAPOLIS -- Before Sunday's game, manager Paul Molitor said he is trying to \"be creative without being foolish\" when it comes to filling out his lineup card each day.</p><p>With the Twins hindered by a handful of injuries to everyday players, Molitor unveiled one of his most creative batting orders of the season on Sunday, and it paid major dividends. The Twins topped the Angels, 7-5, at Target Field to salvage a win after scoring just three runs in the first two games of the series.</p><p>\"It feels good,\" Molitor said. \"[Wins] have been hard to come by. As much as we've had a winning homestand, it kind of feels like a roller coaster. When you lose, it's been tough because the games have felt winnable. That's kind of been the theme. All of our losses feel like, 'Man, just so close and not finding ways.'''</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2D1004923EAF1526F8C81\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141842283\">Video: LAA@MIN: Molitor on battling, contributions from all</a></span></p><p>In his second game back from Triple-A Rochester, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8D1C936FAD8E7FB2960A3\">Jake Cave</span> went 3-for-4 and launched a 418-foot, two-run homer in the fifth inning. With <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AE13DCA77AB5E5C238D96\">Brian Dozier</span> out of the lineup for a rest day, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-965804858147E711BBDA7\">Eduardo Escobar</span> made his first start at second base since August and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CED72F9484959B5E5E8A3\">Robbie Grossman</span> batted leadoff for the third time this season.</p><p>The unconventional combination produced seven runs in the first six innings and helped alleviate some early struggles from Twins starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-748E8715DE7C703B363BD\">Fernando Romero</span>.</p><p>Romero walked the Angels' first batter of the game, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C1AA59A330DD13689138B\">Ian Kinsler</span>, on five pitches, and the outing nearly snowballed from there. He threw a wild pitch to <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA38780E0D36911690096\">Mike Trout</span> and then <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E9BAFFD7C98371BA1389D\">Mitch Garver</span> let another pitch by, allowing Kinsler to advance to third. Romero then intentionally walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4916780C4CF9BD3B22099\">Justin Upton</span> after he ran him up to a 3-0 count, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-710FCFBA6F2FE3A761E99\">Albert Pujols</span> followed with an RBI single to center field.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-30AAEC5419E5CFBE0619B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140047783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Pujols singles, passes Musial in career RBIs</a></span></p><p>In the fourth inning, Romero put on four of the first five batters he faced and had already surrendered two runs with the Angels' 2-3-4 hitters due up, but he worked his way out of the jam.</p><p>\"I think he had Trout and Pujols coming up in the situation, where it could have turned into a big inning,\" Molitor said. \"He did a nice job there. I was trying to give him an opportunity the best I could and it worked out today. It might not in the future, but sometimes you've got to give an opportunity to a guy to get out of his own mess.\"</p><p>In five innings, Romero struck out five, but threw two wild pitches, walked two batters and hit two more. Minnesota's offense came to his rescue immediately and didn't let up the rest of the afternoon.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C079D392173F6252A9B96\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140271583\">Video: LAA@MIN: Romero induces a lineout, strands a pair</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8B1CBDAB3AEBB9A166A2\">Logan Morrison</span> blasted a two-run homer in the bottom of the first to give the Twins the lead back. In the fifth inning, Garver doubled to right and Cave followed with a single to drive him home. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71491BF388DB005F10385\">Ehire Adrianza</span> then drilled a triple to the right-field corner and later scored when Escobar smacked his 25th double of the season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0C2DC1EE6F9A4340DFCA2\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140642783\">Video: LAA@MIN: Adrianza adds to lead with an RBI triple</a></span></p><p>After drawing a walk in the sixth, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5D62DC906634BE78EFCB4\">Max Kepler</span> stole his first base of the season. He didn't stay put long. Two batters later, Cave deposited <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AA104BAE32C34D8AFA1A2\">Jim Johnson</span>'s 3-2 fastball into the Minnesota bullpen.</p><p>\"It definitely made my job easier when I was coming up to bat with guys on second base or guys just drew walks,\" Cave said. \"I could stand on deck and time up some pitches and that kind of thing. That's where hitters help each other out and where stuff gets kind of contagious.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA8C7775F48B125F296AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140986983\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave drills a two-run homer to center</a></span></p><p>A Minnesota bullpen quartet of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6702818DD29E09D9A22A7\">Taylor Rogers</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-99BC3D2DE1717F82E2999\">Addison Reed</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B3E5E87E867AE2D9B27AC\">Zach Duke</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-252B7A2AD40FEA145BD85\">Fernando Rodney</span> each threw an inning to finish off the last half of the game. Rodney allowed the first two runners he faced to reach base in the ninth, and later gave up a two-run single to Pujols. Rodney then walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E8FDD64E18F3710D7EE89\">Luis Valbuena</span> to bring the go-ahead run to the plate. But he forced <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DC53EE2DE0CA847341D8B\">Zack Cozart</span> to pop out and end the game.</p><p>The Twins are 26-13 this season in games in which they score four or more runs. They are 14-11 in games in which they score first.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-1A23A0729B946F42B568D\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307383\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave, Escobar on hot hitting in the win</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I didn't know, I just knew I hit it well. I put my head down and, obviously, I know who's out there in center field. I saw him kind of jump and I didn't see the ball, but I heard the crowd start cheering, so I was like, 'Oh, I think that ball got by him.' So that was cool. I know I'm probably not allowed to say this, but he's probably my favorite player. So to be able to hit some balls out there to him today and to be on the same field as him, it was an honor, really.\" <i>-- Cave, on his eighth-inning double over the head of a leaping Trout</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-51C9117EDCCFBD4113183\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142307083\">Video: LAA@MIN: Cave rips a double, picks up his third hit</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Twins will get a day off on Monday before traveling to Detroit for a three-game set with the Tigers. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1A7FC9AA0C41A32752294\">Jake Odorizzi</span> will get the start for Minnesota in search of his fourth win of the season. He will square off with Detroit lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5E258FBC355B5959040BC\">Blaine Hardy</span> (2-1, 3.66 ERA).</p>",
