									"body" : "<p>CHICAGO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9B1067E1332C4D152B1AD\">Ivan Nova</span> pitched through knee pain most of last season, and he was not particularly interested in going on the disabled list two weeks ago. But after a brutal month on the mound, Nova finally admitted his sprained right ring finger was a problem he should no longer attempt to pitch through.</p><p>Nova's return to the rotation on Sunday afternoon proved not only his health, but also his effectiveness when healthy. The veteran right-hander allowed only four hits, struck out eight and recorded eight outs on the ground over 5 2/3 innings as the Pirates beat the Cubs, 7-1, at Wrigley Field.</p><p>\"He was hitting the corners all day, keeping the ball down,\" Cubs first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1763F37EE500EF4E84E83\">Anthony Rizzo</span> said. \"It's tough to do anything when he's on like that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-537662B35E180A527F7A0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140499783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Nova K's Bryant to escape a jam in the 3rd</a></span></p><p>The Pirates activated Nova without having him make a Minor League start or any other organized outing since his last appearance on May 24, when his ERA climbed to 4.96. Still, the Bucs decided Nova was prepared after watching him work in bullpen sessions with pitching coach Ray Searage and a two-inning simulated game at PNC Park.</p><p>\"He was ready to pitch,\" manager Clint Hurdle said. \"At the end of the day, he showed you he was ready to pitch.\"</p><p>Nova's injured finger mostly impaired his offspeed stuff, but it affected every pitch he threw. Fully healed, he regained command of his fastball, bite on his curveball and movement on his changeup.</p><p>Nova pitched around <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD4BEFC7BB8BD00D5A5A9\">Josh Harrison</span>'s two-out error in the third inning and did the same when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7A458795BD4B0D95651B7\">Jordy Mercer</span> bobbled a grounder in the fifth, inducing a ground-ball double play from pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-59C91F284D3472DE5B08D\">Tommy La Stella</span>, then striking out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2F1CE8C3537D39C3B42A3\">Javier Baez</span> to end the inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0676E8BC26CADB6BAD3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140707783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison, Mercer turn the double play in 5th</a></span></p><p>\"Just the way that the ball was coming out of my hand, I could tell the difference right away,\" Nova said. \"To be able to pitch a game like today \u2026 I think that's kind of a lesson for you. Don't force it.\"</p><p>After days of trying to force some kind of offensive outburst, the Pirates finally broke through. Harrison jump-started a Pittsburgh lineup that managed only one hit on Saturday and one run over the previous two days, pulling his second leadoff home run of the season to left field off Cubs starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0055D3A7A18B4580C8F8C\">Kyle Hendricks</span>. The Pirates did most of their damage against the Cubs' bullpen in the sixth, however.</p><p>With one out and runners on the corners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E34215A0C5DCD9035DC83\">Elias Diaz</span> ended the Pirates' 0-for-19 skid with runners in scoring position by slapping a single to right off lefty reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-10D15272527BD16B97E84\">Brian Duensing</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0DE01F3020C5A5A702F9A\">Josh Bell</span> drew a walk, one of his three on the day, to load the bases for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9A446B4684FA2B2656ABE\">Gregory Polanco</span>. The struggling right fielder broke the game open with a bases-clearing triple to right field to highlight the five-run frame.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2753FA17589D44632BB9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141029483\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco plates 3 with a triple in the 6th</a></span></p><p>\"He put a good swing on that ball,\" Hurdle said. \"Those kinds of things can [be a] catalyst into something or another, but we'll see. Just take it one day at a time. Big swing for us today.\"</p><p>As the Pirates left Chicago on Sunday night bound for Arizona, they could look back at a well-rounded victory after a trio of incomplete performances. They hit plenty but didn't pitch well enough to beat the Dodgers on Thursday. It was the opposite story on Friday and Saturday at Wrigley Field -- good enough pitching, not enough hitting. They finally put it all together on Sunday.</p><p>\"It's good to win a game. We're more surprised when we don't win than when we do win. That's not going to change,\" Hurdle said. \"These men go out there and they expect to win. They have to play well to win. We played well today.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-72D8015C5A42F10EC718C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141341683\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco's triple highlights a 5-run 6th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Timing is everything:</b> Before Sunday, the Pirates' last hit with a man in scoring position came on Thursday. In the eighth inning of their 8-7 loss to the Dodgers, Diaz launched a three-run homer to left field. Between then and the sixth inning on Sunday, the Pirates had no hits in 19 at-bats with RISP; they went 0-for-13 in those situations in Friday's series-opening, 3-1 loss. But Diaz delivered against Duensing.</p><p>After falling behind in the count, 3-0, the lefty fired a sinker down and away from Diaz. He was looking for a fastball, but ideally something over the plate a little more.</p><p>\"Next time,\" Diaz said, smiling, \"I've got to look for a better pitch.\"</p><p>It worked out, anyway. Starting in place of the injured <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD7E5318FC7C9816CD7B0\">Francisco Cervelli</span>, Diaz smacked the pitch to shallow right field to bring home <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-013C382D3D890D3B1FEA7\">Austin Meadows</span>, who had reached on a leadoff double, and give the Bucs a 2-0 lead.</p><p>\"He still stayed with the pitch. It was smart hitting,\" Hurdle said. \"He didn't try to get too big or try to create something that wasn't there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E0E410C8AC996EB11CB85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Diaz plates Meadows with a single to right</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Harrison's home run was the seventh leadoff shot of his career. His only other one this season was also against Hendricks, on May 30 at PNC Park. His last four leadoff home runs have been against the Cubs. He has the fifth-most leadoff homers in club history, trailing Barry Bonds (20), Al Martin (10), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-845B0B9C1B8874A7C2CB6\">Andrew McCutchen</span> (eight) and Bob Bailey (eight).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-43A0D255D3D202BDEFCB3\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140071883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison rips a leadoff homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>The Pirates had not scored five runs in an inning since scoring six times in the sixth inning against the Reds on April 6.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Just using their energy in my favor. If you hear all the stuff the guys say to you in the bullpen, that motivates you a little more. Let's show them I can pitch with 40,000 fans not in my favor. That's the way they are. I like the ballpark. I just try to use that energy in my favor.\" <i>-- Nova, on winning two games at Wrigley Field this season</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B5E715791898691F8D780\">Joe Musgrove</span> will start for the Pirates as they begin a three-game series against the D-backs on Monday night at Chase Field. Musgrove is coming off his first loss as a Pirate, but he still owns a 1.89 ERA after three starts. Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C159A044375814C6307A2\">Patrick Corbin</span> will start for Arizona at 9:40 p.m. ET.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Josh Harrison hit a leadoff homer, Ivan Nova returned from the disabled list with an encouraging 5 2/3-inning start and Gregory Polanco's three-run triple highlighted a five-run sixth inning as the Pirates snapped a three-game losing streak with a 7-1 win over the Cubs in Sunday's finale at Wrigley Field.",
									"body" : "<p>CHICAGO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9B1067E1332C4D152B1AD\">Ivan Nova</span> pitched through knee pain most of last season, and he was not particularly interested in going on the disabled list two weeks ago. But after a brutal month on the mound, Nova finally admitted his sprained right ring finger was a problem he should no longer attempt to pitch through.</p><p>Nova's return to the rotation on Sunday afternoon proved not only his health, but also his effectiveness when healthy. The veteran right-hander allowed only four hits, struck out eight and recorded eight outs on the ground over 5 2/3 innings as the Pirates beat the Cubs, 7-1, at Wrigley Field.</p><p>\"He was hitting the corners all day, keeping the ball down,\" Cubs first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1763F37EE500EF4E84E83\">Anthony Rizzo</span> said. \"It's tough to do anything when he's on like that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-537662B35E180A527F7A0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140499783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Nova K's Bryant to escape a jam in the 3rd</a></span></p><p>The Pirates activated Nova without having him make a Minor League start or any other organized outing since his last appearance on May 24, when his ERA climbed to 4.96. Still, the Bucs decided Nova was prepared after watching him work in bullpen sessions with pitching coach Ray Searage and a two-inning simulated game at PNC Park.</p><p>\"He was ready to pitch,\" manager Clint Hurdle said. \"At the end of the day, he showed you he was ready to pitch.\"</p><p>Nova's injured finger mostly impaired his offspeed stuff, but it affected every pitch he threw. Fully healed, he regained command of his fastball, bite on his curveball and movement on his changeup.</p><p>Nova pitched around <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD4BEFC7BB8BD00D5A5A9\">Josh Harrison</span>'s two-out error in the third inning and did the same when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7A458795BD4B0D95651B7\">Jordy Mercer</span> bobbled a grounder in the fifth, inducing a ground-ball double play from pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-59C91F284D3472DE5B08D\">Tommy La Stella</span>, then striking out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2F1CE8C3537D39C3B42A3\">Javier Baez</span> to end the inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0676E8BC26CADB6BAD3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140707783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison, Mercer turn the double play in 5th</a></span></p><p>\"Just the way that the ball was coming out of my hand, I could tell the difference right away,\" Nova said. \"To be able to pitch a game like today \u2026 I think that's kind of a lesson for you. Don't force it.\"</p><p>After days of trying to force some kind of offensive outburst, the Pirates finally broke through. Harrison jump-started a Pittsburgh lineup that managed only one hit on Saturday and one run over the previous two days, pulling his second leadoff home run of the season to left field off Cubs starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0055D3A7A18B4580C8F8C\">Kyle Hendricks</span>. The Pirates did most of their damage against the Cubs' bullpen in the sixth, however.</p><p>With one out and runners on the corners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E34215A0C5DCD9035DC83\">Elias Diaz</span> ended the Pirates' 0-for-19 skid with runners in scoring position by slapping a single to right off lefty reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-10D15272527BD16B97E84\">Brian Duensing</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0DE01F3020C5A5A702F9A\">Josh Bell</span> drew a walk, one of his three on the day, to load the bases for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9A446B4684FA2B2656ABE\">Gregory Polanco</span>. The struggling right fielder broke the game open with a bases-clearing triple to right field to highlight the five-run frame.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2753FA17589D44632BB9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141029483\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco plates 3 with a triple in the 6th</a></span></p><p>\"He put a good swing on that ball,\" Hurdle said. \"Those kinds of things can [be a] catalyst into something or another, but we'll see. Just take it one day at a time. Big swing for us today.\"</p><p>As the Pirates left Chicago on Sunday night bound for Arizona, they could look back at a well-rounded victory after a trio of incomplete performances. They hit plenty but didn't pitch well enough to beat the Dodgers on Thursday. It was the opposite story on Friday and Saturday at Wrigley Field -- good enough pitching, not enough hitting. They finally put it all together on Sunday.</p><p>\"It's good to win a game. We're more surprised when we don't win than when we do win. That's not going to change,\" Hurdle said. \"These men go out there and they expect to win. They have to play well to win. We played well today.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-72D8015C5A42F10EC718C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141341683\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco's triple highlights a 5-run 6th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Timing is everything:</b> Before Sunday, the Pirates' last hit with a man in scoring position came on Thursday. In the eighth inning of their 8-7 loss to the Dodgers, Diaz launched a three-run homer to left field. Between then and the sixth inning on Sunday, the Pirates had no hits in 19 at-bats with RISP; they went 0-for-13 in those situations in Friday's series-opening, 3-1 loss. But Diaz delivered against Duensing.</p><p>After falling behind in the count, 3-0, the lefty fired a sinker down and away from Diaz. He was looking for a fastball, but ideally something over the plate a little more.</p><p>\"Next time,\" Diaz said, smiling, \"I've got to look for a better pitch.\"</p><p>It worked out, anyway. Starting in place of the injured <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD7E5318FC7C9816CD7B0\">Francisco Cervelli</span>, Diaz smacked the pitch to shallow right field to bring home <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-013C382D3D890D3B1FEA7\">Austin Meadows</span>, who had reached on a leadoff double, and give the Bucs a 2-0 lead.</p><p>\"He still stayed with the pitch. It was smart hitting,\" Hurdle said. \"He didn't try to get too big or try to create something that wasn't there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E0E410C8AC996EB11CB85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Diaz plates Meadows with a single to right</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Harrison's home run was the seventh leadoff shot of his career. His only other one this season was also against Hendricks, on May 30 at PNC Park. His last four leadoff home runs have been against the Cubs. He has the fifth-most leadoff homers in club history, trailing Barry Bonds (20), Al Martin (10), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-845B0B9C1B8874A7C2CB6\">Andrew McCutchen</span> (eight) and Bob Bailey (eight).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-43A0D255D3D202BDEFCB3\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140071883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison rips a leadoff homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>The Pirates had not scored five runs in an inning since scoring six times in the sixth inning against the Reds on April 6.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Just using their energy in my favor. If you hear all the stuff the guys say to you in the bullpen, that motivates you a little more. Let's show them I can pitch with 40,000 fans not in my favor. That's the way they are. I like the ballpark. I just try to use that energy in my favor.\" <i>-- Nova, on winning two games at Wrigley Field this season</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B5E715791898691F8D780\">Joe Musgrove</span> will start for the Pirates as they begin a three-game series against the D-backs on Monday night at Chase Field. Musgrove is coming off his first loss as a Pirate, but he still owns a 1.89 ERA after three starts. Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C159A044375814C6307A2\">Patrick Corbin</span> will start for Arizona at 9:40 p.m. ET.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Josh Harrison hit a leadoff homer, Ivan Nova returned from the disabled list with an encouraging 5 2/3-inning start and Gregory Polanco's three-run triple highlighted a five-run sixth inning as the Pirates snapped a three-game losing streak with a 7-1 win over the Cubs in Sunday's finale at Wrigley Field.",
									"body" : "<p>CHICAGO -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9B1067E1332C4D152B1AD\">Ivan Nova</span> pitched through knee pain most of last season, and he was not particularly interested in going on the disabled list two weeks ago. But after a brutal month on the mound, Nova finally admitted his sprained right ring finger was a problem he should no longer attempt to pitch through.</p><p>Nova's return to the rotation on Sunday afternoon proved not only his health, but also his effectiveness when healthy. The veteran right-hander allowed only four hits, struck out eight and recorded eight outs on the ground over 5 2/3 innings as the Pirates beat the Cubs, 7-1, at Wrigley Field.</p><p>\"He was hitting the corners all day, keeping the ball down,\" Cubs first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1763F37EE500EF4E84E83\">Anthony Rizzo</span> said. \"It's tough to do anything when he's on like that.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-537662B35E180A527F7A0\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140499783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Nova K's Bryant to escape a jam in the 3rd</a></span></p><p>The Pirates activated Nova without having him make a Minor League start or any other organized outing since his last appearance on May 24, when his ERA climbed to 4.96. Still, the Bucs decided Nova was prepared after watching him work in bullpen sessions with pitching coach Ray Searage and a two-inning simulated game at PNC Park.</p><p>\"He was ready to pitch,\" manager Clint Hurdle said. \"At the end of the day, he showed you he was ready to pitch.\"</p><p>Nova's injured finger mostly impaired his offspeed stuff, but it affected every pitch he threw. Fully healed, he regained command of his fastball, bite on his curveball and movement on his changeup.</p><p>Nova pitched around <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD4BEFC7BB8BD00D5A5A9\">Josh Harrison</span>'s two-out error in the third inning and did the same when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7A458795BD4B0D95651B7\">Jordy Mercer</span> bobbled a grounder in the fifth, inducing a ground-ball double play from pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-59C91F284D3472DE5B08D\">Tommy La Stella</span>, then striking out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-2F1CE8C3537D39C3B42A3\">Javier Baez</span> to end the inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0676E8BC26CADB6BAD3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140707783\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison, Mercer turn the double play in 5th</a></span></p><p>\"Just the way that the ball was coming out of my hand, I could tell the difference right away,\" Nova said. \"To be able to pitch a game like today \u2026 I think that's kind of a lesson for you. Don't force it.\"</p><p>After days of trying to force some kind of offensive outburst, the Pirates finally broke through. Harrison jump-started a Pittsburgh lineup that managed only one hit on Saturday and one run over the previous two days, pulling his second leadoff home run of the season to left field off Cubs starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0055D3A7A18B4580C8F8C\">Kyle Hendricks</span>. The Pirates did most of their damage against the Cubs' bullpen in the sixth, however.</p><p>With one out and runners on the corners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E34215A0C5DCD9035DC83\">Elias Diaz</span> ended the Pirates' 0-for-19 skid with runners in scoring position by slapping a single to right off lefty reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-10D15272527BD16B97E84\">Brian Duensing</span>. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0DE01F3020C5A5A702F9A\">Josh Bell</span> drew a walk, one of his three on the day, to load the bases for <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9A446B4684FA2B2656ABE\">Gregory Polanco</span>. The struggling right fielder broke the game open with a bases-clearing triple to right field to highlight the five-run frame.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2753FA17589D44632BB9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141029483\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco plates 3 with a triple in the 6th</a></span></p><p>\"He put a good swing on that ball,\" Hurdle said. \"Those kinds of things can [be a] catalyst into something or another, but we'll see. Just take it one day at a time. Big swing for us today.\"</p><p>As the Pirates left Chicago on Sunday night bound for Arizona, they could look back at a well-rounded victory after a trio of incomplete performances. They hit plenty but didn't pitch well enough to beat the Dodgers on Thursday. It was the opposite story on Friday and Saturday at Wrigley Field -- good enough pitching, not enough hitting. They finally put it all together on Sunday.</p><p>\"It's good to win a game. We're more surprised when we don't win than when we do win. That's not going to change,\" Hurdle said. \"These men go out there and they expect to win. They have to play well to win. We played well today.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-72D8015C5A42F10EC718C\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141341683\">Video: PIT@CHC: Polanco's triple highlights a 5-run 6th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Timing is everything:</b> Before Sunday, the Pirates' last hit with a man in scoring position came on Thursday. In the eighth inning of their 8-7 loss to the Dodgers, Diaz launched a three-run homer to left field. Between then and the sixth inning on Sunday, the Pirates had no hits in 19 at-bats with RISP; they went 0-for-13 in those situations in Friday's series-opening, 3-1 loss. But Diaz delivered against Duensing.</p><p>After falling behind in the count, 3-0, the lefty fired a sinker down and away from Diaz. He was looking for a fastball, but ideally something over the plate a little more.</p><p>\"Next time,\" Diaz said, smiling, \"I've got to look for a better pitch.\"</p><p>It worked out, anyway. Starting in place of the injured <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CD7E5318FC7C9816CD7B0\">Francisco Cervelli</span>, Diaz smacked the pitch to shallow right field to bring home <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-013C382D3D890D3B1FEA7\">Austin Meadows</span>, who had reached on a leadoff double, and give the Bucs a 2-0 lead.</p><p>\"He still stayed with the pitch. It was smart hitting,\" Hurdle said. \"He didn't try to get too big or try to create something that wasn't there.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-E0E410C8AC996EB11CB85\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140878883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Diaz plates Meadows with a single to right</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Harrison's home run was the seventh leadoff shot of his career. His only other one this season was also against Hendricks, on May 30 at PNC Park. His last four leadoff home runs have been against the Cubs. He has the fifth-most leadoff homers in club history, trailing Barry Bonds (20), Al Martin (10), <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-845B0B9C1B8874A7C2CB6\">Andrew McCutchen</span> (eight) and Bob Bailey (eight).</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-43A0D255D3D202BDEFCB3\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140071883\">Video: PIT@CHC: Harrison rips a leadoff homer to left-center</a></span></p><p>The Pirates had not scored five runs in an inning since scoring six times in the sixth inning against the Reds on April 6.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Just using their energy in my favor. If you hear all the stuff the guys say to you in the bullpen, that motivates you a little more. Let's show them I can pitch with 40,000 fans not in my favor. That's the way they are. I like the ballpark. I just try to use that energy in my favor.\" <i>-- Nova, on winning two games at Wrigley Field this season</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B5E715791898691F8D780\">Joe Musgrove</span> will start for the Pirates as they begin a three-game series against the D-backs on Monday night at Chase Field. Musgrove is coming off his first loss as a Pirate, but he still owns a 1.89 ERA after three starts. Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C159A044375814C6307A2\">Patrick Corbin</span> will start for Arizona at 9:40 p.m. ET.</p>",

								{
									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "George Springer hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, Yuli Gurriel slugged his way to four hits and Jose Altuve added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics. But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a \u2026 balk? Rangers reliever Keone Kela was called for a balk with two outs in the ninth, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run. Before that, the Rangers had erased a six-run deficit with the help of two-run hits by Shin-Soo Choo and Carlos Perez. Texas tied it again in the eighth on an Adrian Beltre RBI single after Gurriel had put the Astros up with a solo homer in the seventh.",
									"body" : "<p>ARLINGTON -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C0E5BD48806EA05D8E1B3\">George Springer</span> hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A713AE88B171CF6DE2584\">Yuli Gurriel</span> slugged his way to four hits and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71FE836A3546F7800028F\">Jose Altuve</span> added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics.</p><p>But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a ... balk?</p><p>The Astros added a tie-breaking run in the ninth inning Sunday on a strange turn of events that involved an <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF85C9CB2643D2241AFBE\">Evan Gattis</span> check swing and an astute observation by AJ Hinch, who popped out of the dugout to point out that Rangers reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ED59CC7C7EBD1C981D9AD\">Keone Kela</span> did not stop during his delivery between setting up for the pitch and throwing it.</p><p>The four umpires got together for a quick discussion and ruled the balk call, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run from third.</p><p>\"It's clear as day what happened,\" Hinch said. \"It's a weird play ... caught everybody off-guard, including the umpire crew. It's an illegal pitch with a runner on third. Kela does that all the time with nobody on third. He was so focused on the hitter, he decided to go to a quick pitch, which you can't do. It's a balk. Once the umpires convened, they got the call right.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-4947D300F5746CB9327A9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142334783\">Video: HOU@TEX: Hinch talks game-winning balk, 4-game sweep</a></span></p><p>Was it a call that would have been made had Hinch not pointed it out? According to umpire crew chief Sam Holbrook, it would have -- after there was an interpretation about Kela's intentions.</p><p>\"When he came and brought the pitch without stopping, we had to get together to make sure he hadn't announced to [home plate umpire Alfonzo Marquez] that he was throwing from the windup position,\" Holbrook said. \"So when Fonzie said 'No, he did not announce that to me,' then he was throwing from the stretch position, and he did not stop, so that was what the balk was called for.\"</p><p>Though no one called the balk as the pitch was being thrown, Holbrook said all four umpires saw the balk. Hinch, however, was the first to verbalize it. This was irksome to Rangers manager Jeff Banister, who argued the ruling and was eventually ejected from the game.</p><p>\"My concern is that nobody on the field originally called a balk,\" Banister said. \"There was nothing. No umpire called a balk. Their manager came out, and, I guess, was arguing for a balk. The explanation was to me was Keone didn't tell anybody he was going out of the windup. Unfortunate. I've never seen a non-balk call turned over and called a balk.</p><p>\"My argument was I didn't know we could come out and get the umpires to convene to see what everybody came up with.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DBC3DD3DD9962086D98B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141861383\">Video: HOU@TEX: Banister ejected for arguing balk in the 9th</a></span></p><p>Springer, who scored three runs, set up the bizarre ninth by drawing a leadoff walk off Kela and advancing to second on a wild pitch. With one out, the Rangers opted to intentionally walk Altuve. Springer advanced to third on Gurriel's fly ball to center, putting him in position to trot home on the game-winning balk.</p><p>The series marks the first time the Astros (42-25) have ever swept a four-game series with the Rangers. Houston's winning streak is now five heading into a three-game series in Oakland that begins Tuesday.</p><p>\"These are in-division games, halfway through June, and it's a good test for us,\" Springer said. \"A good stretch of division games for us, any time you can take a series from a division opponent is big.\"</p><p><iframe scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up/episodes/8f41b0ee-050e-4aa7-bfa3-69b19ea3b0b5/embed\" style=\"width: 100%; height: 200px; border: 0 none;\"></iframe></p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-4F9CEBFCB2BCB7C1F93AE\"><a href=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up\">Listen and subscribe to the Morning Lineup Podcast</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />Gurriel's second home run of the season put the Astros ahead, 7-6, in the seventh inning. The homer, hit off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CCF87B3D65FD49EECC6A4\">Jesse Chavez</span>, traveled 399 feet and left his bat at 101.2 mph, and it was one of four hits Gurriel had in the game, matching his career high. It was Gurriel's first career game with three extra-base hits, as he doubled in the first and fifth innings.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-90B46B4771085F9F64087\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142044883\">Video: HOU@TEX: Gurriel homers as part of a 4-hit game</a></span></p><p>\"I'm very pleased, especially with a hot day out there,\" Gurriel said through an interpreter. \"We needed every run, and I was happy to contribute to this game and help us out.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Altuve hit safely in all four games of the Rangers series, going 8-for-16 with a double, home run, four RBIs and two stolen bases. He's batting .364 in 14 games vs. Texas this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA864C7498ED439B5D095\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140591083\">Video: HOU@TEX: Altuve plates Bregman with an RBI double</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-06D8C451D01C967B2A889\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/astros/news/george-springer-hits-5th-leadoff-homer-of-2018/c-280632780\">Springer's leadoff homer</a></span> traveled 423 feet and landed on the grassy berm in straightaway center field. Springer now has 23 leadoff homers for his career. That ranks second on Houston's all-time list, behind Hall of Famer Craig Biggio, who had 53 leadoff homers during his 20-year Astros career.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8EDE4E47E55E8945128AC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140411283\">Video: HOU@TEX: Springer rips his 3rd leadoff HR vs. Rangers</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I'm not surprised by anything our guys do. It could be Yuli today, Jose [Altuve] tomorrow, it could be [Carlos] Correa the next day. Bregman's done his fair share. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-238BE16B560DAFB40A8B3\">Max Stassi</span> ... You look down our order, we have a chance for any one guy to be the hero of the day. We needed a couple of them today.\" -- <i>Hinch</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Astros will open a three-game road series with the A's on Tuesday at 9:05 p.m CT. Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88767604C712FA84DE2B4\">Lance McCullers Jr.</span> (7-2, 3.94) will take the mound for the Astros seeking his third win of 2018 over the A's. In two prior outings against Oakland, McCullers has allowed two earned runs over 12 innings, walking four and striking out 10. The A's will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-896C4E49DF74696BBBB8E\">Daniel Mengden</span> (6-5, 3.45).</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "George Springer hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, Yuli Gurriel slugged his way to four hits and Jose Altuve added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics. But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a \u2026 balk? Rangers reliever Keone Kela was called for a balk with two outs in the ninth, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run. Before that, the Rangers had erased a six-run deficit with the help of two-run hits by Shin-Soo Choo and Carlos Perez. Texas tied it again in the eighth on an Adrian Beltre RBI single after Gurriel had put the Astros up with a solo homer in the seventh.",
									"body" : "<p>ARLINGTON -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C0E5BD48806EA05D8E1B3\">George Springer</span> hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A713AE88B171CF6DE2584\">Yuli Gurriel</span> slugged his way to four hits and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71FE836A3546F7800028F\">Jose Altuve</span> added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics.</p><p>But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a ... balk?</p><p>The Astros added a tie-breaking run in the ninth inning Sunday on a strange turn of events that involved an <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF85C9CB2643D2241AFBE\">Evan Gattis</span> check swing and an astute observation by AJ Hinch, who popped out of the dugout to point out that Rangers reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ED59CC7C7EBD1C981D9AD\">Keone Kela</span> did not stop during his delivery between setting up for the pitch and throwing it.</p><p>The four umpires got together for a quick discussion and ruled the balk call, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run from third.</p><p>\"It's clear as day what happened,\" Hinch said. \"It's a weird play ... caught everybody off-guard, including the umpire crew. It's an illegal pitch with a runner on third. Kela does that all the time with nobody on third. He was so focused on the hitter, he decided to go to a quick pitch, which you can't do. It's a balk. Once the umpires convened, they got the call right.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-4947D300F5746CB9327A9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142334783\">Video: HOU@TEX: Hinch talks game-winning balk, 4-game sweep</a></span></p><p>Was it a call that would have been made had Hinch not pointed it out? According to umpire crew chief Sam Holbrook, it would have -- after there was an interpretation about Kela's intentions.</p><p>\"When he came and brought the pitch without stopping, we had to get together to make sure he hadn't announced to [home plate umpire Alfonzo Marquez] that he was throwing from the windup position,\" Holbrook said. \"So when Fonzie said 'No, he did not announce that to me,' then he was throwing from the stretch position, and he did not stop, so that was what the balk was called for.\"</p><p>Though no one called the balk as the pitch was being thrown, Holbrook said all four umpires saw the balk. Hinch, however, was the first to verbalize it. This was irksome to Rangers manager Jeff Banister, who argued the ruling and was eventually ejected from the game.</p><p>\"My concern is that nobody on the field originally called a balk,\" Banister said. \"There was nothing. No umpire called a balk. Their manager came out, and, I guess, was arguing for a balk. The explanation was to me was Keone didn't tell anybody he was going out of the windup. Unfortunate. I've never seen a non-balk call turned over and called a balk.</p><p>\"My argument was I didn't know we could come out and get the umpires to convene to see what everybody came up with.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DBC3DD3DD9962086D98B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141861383\">Video: HOU@TEX: Banister ejected for arguing balk in the 9th</a></span></p><p>Springer, who scored three runs, set up the bizarre ninth by drawing a leadoff walk off Kela and advancing to second on a wild pitch. With one out, the Rangers opted to intentionally walk Altuve. Springer advanced to third on Gurriel's fly ball to center, putting him in position to trot home on the game-winning balk.</p><p>The series marks the first time the Astros (42-25) have ever swept a four-game series with the Rangers. Houston's winning streak is now five heading into a three-game series in Oakland that begins Tuesday.</p><p>\"These are in-division games, halfway through June, and it's a good test for us,\" Springer said. \"A good stretch of division games for us, any time you can take a series from a division opponent is big.\"</p><p><iframe scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up/episodes/8f41b0ee-050e-4aa7-bfa3-69b19ea3b0b5/embed\" style=\"width: 100%; height: 200px; border: 0 none;\"></iframe></p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-4F9CEBFCB2BCB7C1F93AE\"><a href=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up\">Listen and subscribe to the Morning Lineup Podcast</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />Gurriel's second home run of the season put the Astros ahead, 7-6, in the seventh inning. The homer, hit off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CCF87B3D65FD49EECC6A4\">Jesse Chavez</span>, traveled 399 feet and left his bat at 101.2 mph, and it was one of four hits Gurriel had in the game, matching his career high. It was Gurriel's first career game with three extra-base hits, as he doubled in the first and fifth innings.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-90B46B4771085F9F64087\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142044883\">Video: HOU@TEX: Gurriel homers as part of a 4-hit game</a></span></p><p>\"I'm very pleased, especially with a hot day out there,\" Gurriel said through an interpreter. \"We needed every run, and I was happy to contribute to this game and help us out.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Altuve hit safely in all four games of the Rangers series, going 8-for-16 with a double, home run, four RBIs and two stolen bases. He's batting .364 in 14 games vs. Texas this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA864C7498ED439B5D095\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140591083\">Video: HOU@TEX: Altuve plates Bregman with an RBI double</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-06D8C451D01C967B2A889\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/astros/news/george-springer-hits-5th-leadoff-homer-of-2018/c-280632780\">Springer's leadoff homer</a></span> traveled 423 feet and landed on the grassy berm in straightaway center field. Springer now has 23 leadoff homers for his career. That ranks second on Houston's all-time list, behind Hall of Famer Craig Biggio, who had 53 leadoff homers during his 20-year Astros career.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8EDE4E47E55E8945128AC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140411283\">Video: HOU@TEX: Springer rips his 3rd leadoff HR vs. Rangers</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I'm not surprised by anything our guys do. It could be Yuli today, Jose [Altuve] tomorrow, it could be [Carlos] Correa the next day. Bregman's done his fair share. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-238BE16B560DAFB40A8B3\">Max Stassi</span> ... You look down our order, we have a chance for any one guy to be the hero of the day. We needed a couple of them today.\" -- <i>Hinch</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Astros will open a three-game road series with the A's on Tuesday at 9:05 p.m CT. Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88767604C712FA84DE2B4\">Lance McCullers Jr.</span> (7-2, 3.94) will take the mound for the Astros seeking his third win of 2018 over the A's. In two prior outings against Oakland, McCullers has allowed two earned runs over 12 innings, walking four and striking out 10. The A's will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-896C4E49DF74696BBBB8E\">Daniel Mengden</span> (6-5, 3.45).</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "George Springer hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, Yuli Gurriel slugged his way to four hits and Jose Altuve added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics. But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a \u2026 balk? Rangers reliever Keone Kela was called for a balk with two outs in the ninth, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run. Before that, the Rangers had erased a six-run deficit with the help of two-run hits by Shin-Soo Choo and Carlos Perez. Texas tied it again in the eighth on an Adrian Beltre RBI single after Gurriel had put the Astros up with a solo homer in the seventh.",
									"body" : "<p>ARLINGTON -- <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-C0E5BD48806EA05D8E1B3\">George Springer</span> hit his MLB-leading fifth leadoff homer, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A713AE88B171CF6DE2584\">Yuli Gurriel</span> slugged his way to four hits and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71FE836A3546F7800028F\">Jose Altuve</span> added three more hits to his already eye-popping road statistics.</p><p>But the Astros beat the Rangers, 8-7, on a ... balk?</p><p>The Astros added a tie-breaking run in the ninth inning Sunday on a strange turn of events that involved an <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF85C9CB2643D2241AFBE\">Evan Gattis</span> check swing and an astute observation by AJ Hinch, who popped out of the dugout to point out that Rangers reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-ED59CC7C7EBD1C981D9AD\">Keone Kela</span> did not stop during his delivery between setting up for the pitch and throwing it.</p><p>The four umpires got together for a quick discussion and ruled the balk call, allowing Springer to score the go-ahead run from third.</p><p>\"It's clear as day what happened,\" Hinch said. \"It's a weird play ... caught everybody off-guard, including the umpire crew. It's an illegal pitch with a runner on third. Kela does that all the time with nobody on third. He was so focused on the hitter, he decided to go to a quick pitch, which you can't do. It's a balk. Once the umpires convened, they got the call right.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-4947D300F5746CB9327A9\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142334783\">Video: HOU@TEX: Hinch talks game-winning balk, 4-game sweep</a></span></p><p>Was it a call that would have been made had Hinch not pointed it out? According to umpire crew chief Sam Holbrook, it would have -- after there was an interpretation about Kela's intentions.</p><p>\"When he came and brought the pitch without stopping, we had to get together to make sure he hadn't announced to [home plate umpire Alfonzo Marquez] that he was throwing from the windup position,\" Holbrook said. \"So when Fonzie said 'No, he did not announce that to me,' then he was throwing from the stretch position, and he did not stop, so that was what the balk was called for.\"</p><p>Though no one called the balk as the pitch was being thrown, Holbrook said all four umpires saw the balk. Hinch, however, was the first to verbalize it. This was irksome to Rangers manager Jeff Banister, who argued the ruling and was eventually ejected from the game.</p><p>\"My concern is that nobody on the field originally called a balk,\" Banister said. \"There was nothing. No umpire called a balk. Their manager came out, and, I guess, was arguing for a balk. The explanation was to me was Keone didn't tell anybody he was going out of the windup. Unfortunate. I've never seen a non-balk call turned over and called a balk.</p><p>\"My argument was I didn't know we could come out and get the umpires to convene to see what everybody came up with.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DBC3DD3DD9962086D98B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141861383\">Video: HOU@TEX: Banister ejected for arguing balk in the 9th</a></span></p><p>Springer, who scored three runs, set up the bizarre ninth by drawing a leadoff walk off Kela and advancing to second on a wild pitch. With one out, the Rangers opted to intentionally walk Altuve. Springer advanced to third on Gurriel's fly ball to center, putting him in position to trot home on the game-winning balk.</p><p>The series marks the first time the Astros (42-25) have ever swept a four-game series with the Rangers. Houston's winning streak is now five heading into a three-game series in Oakland that begins Tuesday.</p><p>\"These are in-division games, halfway through June, and it's a good test for us,\" Springer said. \"A good stretch of division games for us, any time you can take a series from a division opponent is big.\"</p><p><iframe scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up/episodes/8f41b0ee-050e-4aa7-bfa3-69b19ea3b0b5/embed\" style=\"width: 100%; height: 200px; border: 0 none;\"></iframe></p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-4F9CEBFCB2BCB7C1F93AE\"><a href=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up\">Listen and subscribe to the Morning Lineup Podcast</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />Gurriel's second home run of the season put the Astros ahead, 7-6, in the seventh inning. The homer, hit off <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CCF87B3D65FD49EECC6A4\">Jesse Chavez</span>, traveled 399 feet and left his bat at 101.2 mph, and it was one of four hits Gurriel had in the game, matching his career high. It was Gurriel's first career game with three extra-base hits, as he doubled in the first and fifth innings.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-90B46B4771085F9F64087\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142044883\">Video: HOU@TEX: Gurriel homers as part of a 4-hit game</a></span></p><p>\"I'm very pleased, especially with a hot day out there,\" Gurriel said through an interpreter. \"We needed every run, and I was happy to contribute to this game and help us out.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Altuve hit safely in all four games of the Rangers series, going 8-for-16 with a double, home run, four RBIs and two stolen bases. He's batting .364 in 14 games vs. Texas this season.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-DA864C7498ED439B5D095\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140591083\">Video: HOU@TEX: Altuve plates Bregman with an RBI double</a></span></p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br /><span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-06D8C451D01C967B2A889\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/astros/news/george-springer-hits-5th-leadoff-homer-of-2018/c-280632780\">Springer's leadoff homer</a></span> traveled 423 feet and landed on the grassy berm in straightaway center field. Springer now has 23 leadoff homers for his career. That ranks second on Houston's all-time list, behind Hall of Famer Craig Biggio, who had 53 leadoff homers during his 20-year Astros career.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8EDE4E47E55E8945128AC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140411283\">Video: HOU@TEX: Springer rips his 3rd leadoff HR vs. Rangers</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I'm not surprised by anything our guys do. It could be Yuli today, Jose [Altuve] tomorrow, it could be [Carlos] Correa the next day. Bregman's done his fair share. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-238BE16B560DAFB40A8B3\">Max Stassi</span> ... You look down our order, we have a chance for any one guy to be the hero of the day. We needed a couple of them today.\" -- <i>Hinch</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Astros will open a three-game road series with the A's on Tuesday at 9:05 p.m CT. Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88767604C712FA84DE2B4\">Lance McCullers Jr.</span> (7-2, 3.94) will take the mound for the Astros seeking his third win of 2018 over the A's. In two prior outings against Oakland, McCullers has allowed two earned runs over 12 innings, walking four and striking out 10. The A's will counter with right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-896C4E49DF74696BBBB8E\">Daniel Mengden</span> (6-5, 3.45).</p>",

On that 1-8 road trip, they scored a total of 18 runs, with seven coming in one game.</p><p>\"This is a good place to hit,\" Descalso said of Coors Field. \"But I thought we did a good job of taking good at-bats, taking the walks when they were there, getting it to the next guy. We hit some home runs, we hit a lot of extra-base hits, some big innings, answered some of their run-scoring innings after they scored. That's a good recipe for success obviously.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CD0D1A32B252CB1328B9A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141534283\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte doubles for his 3rd RBI of the game</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BA252399CE2C5F9194790\">Zack Godley</span> (6-5) bounced back from a rough start in San Francisco to get the win, allowing two runs on five hits over 5 2/3 innings.</p><p>\"He was attacking the zone from pitch one to the last one that he threw,\" Lovullo said. \"He was around the zone attacking with a three or four-pitch mix.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2884443F1CDB74F7E97A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141220883\">Video: ARI@COL: Godley strikes out the side in the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Bracho gets it done:</b> Godley ran into some trouble in the sixth when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D65725A7C3014B742D999\">Ian Desmond</span> drove home a pair of runs with a single to right. With two out and two on and the D-backs clinging to a 4-2 lead, Lovullo elected to bring in right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88AB56442BF560EA449A1\">Silvino Bracho</span>, who had thrown two innings Saturday night. Bracho struck out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E6C96FBA7639E73BCE9D\">Noel Cuevas</span> to end the threat and the D-backs tacked on three in the seventh to take command.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-213D74984AAA195477685\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141453783\">Video: ARI@COL: Bracho K's Cuevas to escape a tight spot</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 D-backs second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4201CDF79A2F9160671B3\">Ketel Marte</span>'s home run in the second was his 10th straight extra-base hit, which tied a club record. The streak came to an end in the sixth when Marte singled to left. The last player to have an extra-base hit streak longer than 10 games was the Yankees' <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-868303FF0484A110D1293\">Aaron Judge</span> in September of last season, according to the Elias Sports Bureau.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-594687C9B2CA65E5CB496\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140586483\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte belts a solo homer in the 2nd inning</a></span></p><p>\u2022 Per ESPN Stats & Info, Goldschmidt is the first player with multiple extra-base hits and multiple RBIs in four straight games since the leagues were split into divisions in 1969. The last player to accomplish the feat was Frank Howard, who did it with the Washington Senators in 1968.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It came at a very good time, day game after a night game, maybe they were a little flat and we scored some early runs and got ahead and played downhill baseball. So, it was a good effort by him to set the tone.\" <i>-- Lovullo, on Godley</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The D-backs return home Monday night to open a three-game series with the Pirates. The homestand will also feature a four-game series with the Mets. Left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-85AD0DE8698EA728E5D9C\">Patrick Corbin</span> (6-2, 2.87 ERA) will get the start for the D-backs against Pirates righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FCF78BB01006B90686088\">Joe Musgrove</span> in the opener. Corbin is coming off a start in which he allowed one run over 6 1/3 innings against the Giants at AT&T Park.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Paul Goldschmidt stayed hot during Arizona's 8-3 win over the Rockies at Coors Field on Sunday afternoon. He added a pair of extra-base hits and drove in two to back Zack Godley, who picked up his sixth win of the year while striking out eight in 5 2/3 innings.",
									"body" : "<p>DENVER -- This flight back to Phoenix will be far different than the last one for the D-backs.</p><p>When they returned from their last road trip, they did so carrying a 1-8 record and an offense that had lost its way.</p><p>After Sunday afternoon's 8-3 win over the Rockies at Coors Field, the D-backs head home having swept Colorado, and with a 4-2 mark on the road, which also included a stop in San Francisco, where they coughed up a ninth-inning lead in the final game of the series.</p><p>\"Much better feeling this time,\" veteran infielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-896463C5DE287BB120E80\">Daniel Descalso</span> said. \"Winning road trip, probably had a chance to go really 5-1 on the trip, but couldn't pull that one out in San Francisco. But, nice to come in and get a sweep after losing a tough one to the Giants.\"</p><p>Even more important, their offense, led by five-time All-Star first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B7B473A156B5AFEF56FA3\">Paul Goldschmidt</span>, has been reignited.</p><p>\"That was a tough time,\" Lovullo said of the 1-8 trip, which came during an 8-19 month of May. \"This team showed a lot of toughness, and I was proud of them for that, because they never shut down, they never quit. We're on the other side of that now. You win three games here the way we did against this type of team, this atmosphere, you're doing a lot right and I'm proud of these guys. Considering what we've been doing, and where we came from about 10 days ago, it was a great moment for us to come in here and play the type of baseball we did.\"</p><p>Goldschmidt was 16-for-25 during the road trip with six doubles, a triple and four homers. In the series against the Rockies, he put 12 balls in play and nine had an exit velocity above 95 mph, which qualify as hard-hit balls.</p><p>\"It's nice to see him get really hot,\" Descalso said. \"It's fun to watch.\"</p><p><iframe scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up/episodes/8f41b0ee-050e-4aa7-bfa3-69b19ea3b0b5/embed\" style=\"width: 100%; height: 200px; border: 0 none;\"></iframe></p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EC6AA0C48EEA99823E1A2\"><a href=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up\">Listen and subscribe to the Morning Lineup Podcast</a></span></p><p>The D-backs scored 29 games in the series with the Rockies. On that 1-8 road trip, they scored a total of 18 runs, with seven coming in one game.</p><p>\"This is a good place to hit,\" Descalso said of Coors Field. \"But I thought we did a good job of taking good at-bats, taking the walks when they were there, getting it to the next guy. We hit some home runs, we hit a lot of extra-base hits, some big innings, answered some of their run-scoring innings after they scored. That's a good recipe for success obviously.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CD0D1A32B252CB1328B9A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141534283\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte doubles for his 3rd RBI of the game</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BA252399CE2C5F9194790\">Zack Godley</span> (6-5) bounced back from a rough start in San Francisco to get the win, allowing two runs on five hits over 5 2/3 innings.</p><p>\"He was attacking the zone from pitch one to the last one that he threw,\" Lovullo said. \"He was around the zone attacking with a three or four-pitch mix.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2884443F1CDB74F7E97A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141220883\">Video: ARI@COL: Godley strikes out the side in the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Bracho gets it done:</b> Godley ran into some trouble in the sixth when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D65725A7C3014B742D999\">Ian Desmond</span> drove home a pair of runs with a single to right. With two out and two on and the D-backs clinging to a 4-2 lead, Lovullo elected to bring in right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88AB56442BF560EA449A1\">Silvino Bracho</span>, who had thrown two innings Saturday night. Bracho struck out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E6C96FBA7639E73BCE9D\">Noel Cuevas</span> to end the threat and the D-backs tacked on three in the seventh to take command.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-213D74984AAA195477685\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141453783\">Video: ARI@COL: Bracho K's Cuevas to escape a tight spot</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 D-backs second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4201CDF79A2F9160671B3\">Ketel Marte</span>'s home run in the second was his 10th straight extra-base hit, which tied a club record. The streak came to an end in the sixth when Marte singled to left. The last player to have an extra-base hit streak longer than 10 games was the Yankees' <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-868303FF0484A110D1293\">Aaron Judge</span> in September of last season, according to the Elias Sports Bureau.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-594687C9B2CA65E5CB496\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140586483\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte belts a solo homer in the 2nd inning</a></span></p><p>\u2022 Per ESPN Stats & Info, Goldschmidt is the first player with multiple extra-base hits and multiple RBIs in four straight games since the leagues were split into divisions in 1969. The last player to accomplish the feat was Frank Howard, who did it with the Washington Senators in 1968.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It came at a very good time, day game after a night game, maybe they were a little flat and we scored some early runs and got ahead and played downhill baseball. So, it was a good effort by him to set the tone.\" <i>-- Lovullo, on Godley</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The D-backs return home Monday night to open a three-game series with the Pirates. The homestand will also feature a four-game series with the Mets. Left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-85AD0DE8698EA728E5D9C\">Patrick Corbin</span> (6-2, 2.87 ERA) will get the start for the D-backs against Pirates righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FCF78BB01006B90686088\">Joe Musgrove</span> in the opener. Corbin is coming off a start in which he allowed one run over 6 1/3 innings against the Giants at AT&T Park.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Paul Goldschmidt stayed hot during Arizona's 8-3 win over the Rockies at Coors Field on Sunday afternoon. He added a pair of extra-base hits and drove in two to back Zack Godley, who picked up his sixth win of the year while striking out eight in 5 2/3 innings.",
									"body" : "<p>DENVER -- This flight back to Phoenix will be far different than the last one for the D-backs.</p><p>When they returned from their last road trip, they did so carrying a 1-8 record and an offense that had lost its way.</p><p>After Sunday afternoon's 8-3 win over the Rockies at Coors Field, the D-backs head home having swept Colorado, and with a 4-2 mark on the road, which also included a stop in San Francisco, where they coughed up a ninth-inning lead in the final game of the series.</p><p>\"Much better feeling this time,\" veteran infielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-896463C5DE287BB120E80\">Daniel Descalso</span> said. \"Winning road trip, probably had a chance to go really 5-1 on the trip, but couldn't pull that one out in San Francisco. But, nice to come in and get a sweep after losing a tough one to the Giants.\"</p><p>Even more important, their offense, led by five-time All-Star first baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B7B473A156B5AFEF56FA3\">Paul Goldschmidt</span>, has been reignited.</p><p>\"That was a tough time,\" Lovullo said of the 1-8 trip, which came during an 8-19 month of May. \"This team showed a lot of toughness, and I was proud of them for that, because they never shut down, they never quit. We're on the other side of that now. You win three games here the way we did against this type of team, this atmosphere, you're doing a lot right and I'm proud of these guys. Considering what we've been doing, and where we came from about 10 days ago, it was a great moment for us to come in here and play the type of baseball we did.\"</p><p>Goldschmidt was 16-for-25 during the road trip with six doubles, a triple and four homers. In the series against the Rockies, he put 12 balls in play and nine had an exit velocity above 95 mph, which qualify as hard-hit balls.</p><p>\"It's nice to see him get really hot,\" Descalso said. \"It's fun to watch.\"</p><p><iframe scrolling=\"no\" src=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up/episodes/8f41b0ee-050e-4aa7-bfa3-69b19ea3b0b5/embed\" style=\"width: 100%; height: 200px; border: 0 none;\"></iframe></p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EC6AA0C48EEA99823E1A2\"><a href=\"https://art19.com/shows/morning-line-up\">Listen and subscribe to the Morning Lineup Podcast</a></span></p><p>The D-backs scored 29 games in the series with the Rockies. On that 1-8 road trip, they scored a total of 18 runs, with seven coming in one game.</p><p>\"This is a good place to hit,\" Descalso said of Coors Field. \"But I thought we did a good job of taking good at-bats, taking the walks when they were there, getting it to the next guy. We hit some home runs, we hit a lot of extra-base hits, some big innings, answered some of their run-scoring innings after they scored. That's a good recipe for success obviously.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CD0D1A32B252CB1328B9A\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141534283\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte doubles for his 3rd RBI of the game</a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BA252399CE2C5F9194790\">Zack Godley</span> (6-5) bounced back from a rough start in San Francisco to get the win, allowing two runs on five hits over 5 2/3 innings.</p><p>\"He was attacking the zone from pitch one to the last one that he threw,\" Lovullo said. \"He was around the zone attacking with a three or four-pitch mix.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-2884443F1CDB74F7E97A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141220883\">Video: ARI@COL: Godley strikes out the side in the 5th</a></span></p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br /><b>Bracho gets it done:</b> Godley ran into some trouble in the sixth when <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D65725A7C3014B742D999\">Ian Desmond</span> drove home a pair of runs with a single to right. With two out and two on and the D-backs clinging to a 4-2 lead, Lovullo elected to bring in right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-88AB56442BF560EA449A1\">Silvino Bracho</span>, who had thrown two innings Saturday night. Bracho struck out <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E6C96FBA7639E73BCE9D\">Noel Cuevas</span> to end the threat and the D-backs tacked on three in the seventh to take command.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-213D74984AAA195477685\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141453783\">Video: ARI@COL: Bracho K's Cuevas to escape a tight spot</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />\u2022 D-backs second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4201CDF79A2F9160671B3\">Ketel Marte</span>'s home run in the second was his 10th straight extra-base hit, which tied a club record. The streak came to an end in the sixth when Marte singled to left. The last player to have an extra-base hit streak longer than 10 games was the Yankees' <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-868303FF0484A110D1293\">Aaron Judge</span> in September of last season, according to the Elias Sports Bureau.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-594687C9B2CA65E5CB496\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2140586483\">Video: ARI@COL: Marte belts a solo homer in the 2nd inning</a></span></p><p>\u2022 Per ESPN Stats & Info, Goldschmidt is the first player with multiple extra-base hits and multiple RBIs in four straight games since the leagues were split into divisions in 1969. The last player to accomplish the feat was Frank Howard, who did it with the Washington Senators in 1968.</p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"It came at a very good time, day game after a night game, maybe they were a little flat and we scored some early runs and got ahead and played downhill baseball. So, it was a good effort by him to set the tone.\" <i>-- Lovullo, on Godley</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The D-backs return home Monday night to open a three-game series with the Pirates. The homestand will also feature a four-game series with the Mets. Left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-85AD0DE8698EA728E5D9C\">Patrick Corbin</span> (6-2, 2.87 ERA) will get the start for the D-backs against Pirates righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-FCF78BB01006B90686088\">Joe Musgrove</span> in the opener. Corbin is coming off a start in which he allowed one run over 6 1/3 innings against the Giants at AT&T Park.</p>",

									"body" : "<p>OAKLAND -- Heroism comes in many forms. In baseball, on both sides of the ball. Together, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A2BD2B5293660FB1173A6\">Marcus Semien</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-01D8ECCF9F69D3E9FC7B1\">Matt Chapman</span>'s work turned the A's into winners on Sunday afternoon.</p><p>Chapman may have propelled them to a 3-2 victory with a go-ahead home run in the eighth inning to help them take three of four from the Royals at the Coliseum, but it was only because Semien's defensive doings put him in position.</p><p>The solo homer off right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7976D7BDB91692136A1AB\">Jason Adam</span> was Chapman's 10th of the season and followed a spectacular game-changing play by Semien in the top half of the inning. The A's shortstop made a diving stop on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A86DB4585C3D45CB353AD\">Salvador Perez</span>'s sharp grounder and nailed potential go-ahead runner <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71EB4680E8A3A35BA0FB0\">Whit Merrifield</span> at the plate to preserve a 2-2 tie.</p><p>\"That's a really good runner at third going on contact,\" A's manager Bob Melvin said. \"That's about as good a play I've seen him make since he's been here. To dive like that, get up and have to throw it off balance on the money like that, no legs underneath him \u2026 game winner.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-696B050B75268E575EE84\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141867783\">Video: KC@OAK: Semien dives, tosses Merrifield out at home</a></span></p><p>Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEAF0DEE6AD40E74DA5BC\">Sean Manaea</span>, lifted with one out in the eighth, was denied a win but turned in an encouraging outing with two runs and six hits allowed after posting a 6.63 ERA in his previous seven starts. He didn't walk a batter and struck out six, pitching past the sixth inning for the first time since April 27.</p><p>Closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EA6E3BE35693BB6FB8BB7\">Blake Treinen</span> secured the final five outs, the first being the game's finest.</p><p>\"It was an incredible play,\" Treinen said. \"Chapman made a great swing, but that swing doesn't get us the win if Marcus doesn't make that play. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5B280CB8A69F3D0902EA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/player/518960/jonathan-lucroy\">[Jonathan] Lucroy</a></span> and I were on the same page and we were trying to call a sinker there because he swung through a good one down the pitch before.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-892A51A637EF5A550FDBA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142166883\">Video: KC@OAK: Manaea K's 6 over 7 1/3 vs. the Royals</a></span></p><p>\"You figure with the sinker from Blake that the ball can come your way pretty quick,\" Semien said. \"Just reaction.\"</p><p>Lucroy's RBI single highlighted a two-run second inning for the A's, but the Royals were quick to match them, with help from the sun. Merrifield, awarded a double that fell in front of a blinded <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA2074211CEEBD9B5DB3\">Mark Canha</span> in left field, scored on a wild pitch, and Perez launched a game-tying homer with two outs.</p><p>By the time Chapman stepped to the plate in the eighth, the A's had squandered multiple scoring opportunities. Twice, they left the bases loaded. Then in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1C733F07F13173D19B29F\">Dustin Fowler</span> used his speed to record an infield single and race all the way to third on an errant pickoff attempt, only to be left there after Semien popped out and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-20C940B34447AB12CCEA8\">Khris Davis</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-44ABE8B7288C4D59102B5\">Matt Olson</span> both whiffed.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0DE090A2C87A61162BBA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141539483\">Video: KC@OAK: Chapman nabs Orlando with deep throw at third</a></span></p><p>\"You ease up just for a second after Davis and Olson,\" Melvin said, \"and Chapman can bite you like he did.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />The A's improved to 29-0 when leading after the eighth inning, after Treinen stranded a runner at third to end the game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CDFF7828935B02B2CDF86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142030283\">Video: KC@OAK: Treinen earns win with 5-out appearance</a></span></p><p>\"It's a funny game,\" Melvin said. \"It feels good, then it feels bad and the next thing you know it's good again. That's why you play all 27 and that's why you keep grinding on it. Now they're in a position in the last inning to tie it off a guy who's basically been spotless.\"</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The same fan caught consecutive foul balls off the bat of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEC6944070EA265B950B0\">Chad Pinder</span> in the sixth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-AF8113E8B8049BAEB73B1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142164183\">Video: Must C Catches: A's fan makes back-to-back grabs</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I thought he threw great today. That's the best we've seen him throw in a while. It's not always about the velo, but it's about the location and the life that he has on all his pitches. You were seeing some 92, 93s today. You were seeing some sliders that had a little higher velocity, changeups a little higher velocity.\" -- <i>Melvin, on Manaea</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The A's will enjoy an off-day Monday before resuming play Tuesday for the start of a three-game series with the Astros. Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4AFD25AD6666299F2A88B\">Daniel Mengden</span> (6-5, 3.45 ERA) will be on the mound in the 7:05 p.m. PT opener at the Coliseum. Houston will counter with righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6669C3AABD6369A1AED82\">Lance McCullers Jr.</span> (7-3, 3.94 ERA).</p>",

									"body" : "<p>OAKLAND -- Heroism comes in many forms. In baseball, on both sides of the ball. Together, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A2BD2B5293660FB1173A6\">Marcus Semien</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-01D8ECCF9F69D3E9FC7B1\">Matt Chapman</span>'s work turned the A's into winners on Sunday afternoon.</p><p>Chapman may have propelled them to a 3-2 victory with a go-ahead home run in the eighth inning to help them take three of four from the Royals at the Coliseum, but it was only because Semien's defensive doings put him in position.</p><p>The solo homer off right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7976D7BDB91692136A1AB\">Jason Adam</span> was Chapman's 10th of the season and followed a spectacular game-changing play by Semien in the top half of the inning. The A's shortstop made a diving stop on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A86DB4585C3D45CB353AD\">Salvador Perez</span>'s sharp grounder and nailed potential go-ahead runner <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71EB4680E8A3A35BA0FB0\">Whit Merrifield</span> at the plate to preserve a 2-2 tie.</p><p>\"That's a really good runner at third going on contact,\" A's manager Bob Melvin said. \"That's about as good a play I've seen him make since he's been here. To dive like that, get up and have to throw it off balance on the money like that, no legs underneath him \u2026 game winner.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-696B050B75268E575EE84\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141867783\">Video: KC@OAK: Semien dives, tosses Merrifield out at home</a></span></p><p>Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEAF0DEE6AD40E74DA5BC\">Sean Manaea</span>, lifted with one out in the eighth, was denied a win but turned in an encouraging outing with two runs and six hits allowed after posting a 6.63 ERA in his previous seven starts. He didn't walk a batter and struck out six, pitching past the sixth inning for the first time since April 27.</p><p>Closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EA6E3BE35693BB6FB8BB7\">Blake Treinen</span> secured the final five outs, the first being the game's finest.</p><p>\"It was an incredible play,\" Treinen said. \"Chapman made a great swing, but that swing doesn't get us the win if Marcus doesn't make that play. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5B280CB8A69F3D0902EA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/player/518960/jonathan-lucroy\">[Jonathan] Lucroy</a></span> and I were on the same page and we were trying to call a sinker there because he swung through a good one down the pitch before.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-892A51A637EF5A550FDBA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142166883\">Video: KC@OAK: Manaea K's 6 over 7 1/3 vs. the Royals</a></span></p><p>\"You figure with the sinker from Blake that the ball can come your way pretty quick,\" Semien said. \"Just reaction.\"</p><p>Lucroy's RBI single highlighted a two-run second inning for the A's, but the Royals were quick to match them, with help from the sun. Merrifield, awarded a double that fell in front of a blinded <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA2074211CEEBD9B5DB3\">Mark Canha</span> in left field, scored on a wild pitch, and Perez launched a game-tying homer with two outs.</p><p>By the time Chapman stepped to the plate in the eighth, the A's had squandered multiple scoring opportunities. Twice, they left the bases loaded. Then in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1C733F07F13173D19B29F\">Dustin Fowler</span> used his speed to record an infield single and race all the way to third on an errant pickoff attempt, only to be left there after Semien popped out and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-20C940B34447AB12CCEA8\">Khris Davis</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-44ABE8B7288C4D59102B5\">Matt Olson</span> both whiffed.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0DE090A2C87A61162BBA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141539483\">Video: KC@OAK: Chapman nabs Orlando with deep throw at third</a></span></p><p>\"You ease up just for a second after Davis and Olson,\" Melvin said, \"and Chapman can bite you like he did.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />The A's improved to 29-0 when leading after the eighth inning, after Treinen stranded a runner at third to end the game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CDFF7828935B02B2CDF86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142030283\">Video: KC@OAK: Treinen earns win with 5-out appearance</a></span></p><p>\"It's a funny game,\" Melvin said. \"It feels good, then it feels bad and the next thing you know it's good again. That's why you play all 27 and that's why you keep grinding on it. Now they're in a position in the last inning to tie it off a guy who's basically been spotless.\"</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The same fan caught consecutive foul balls off the bat of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEC6944070EA265B950B0\">Chad Pinder</span> in the sixth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-AF8113E8B8049BAEB73B1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142164183\">Video: Must C Catches: A's fan makes back-to-back grabs</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I thought he threw great today. That's the best we've seen him throw in a while. It's not always about the velo, but it's about the location and the life that he has on all his pitches. You were seeing some 92, 93s today. You were seeing some sliders that had a little higher velocity, changeups a little higher velocity.\" -- <i>Melvin, on Manaea</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The A's will enjoy an off-day Monday before resuming play Tuesday for the start of a three-game series with the Astros.
