									"blurb" : "Matt Chapman propelled the A's to a 3-2 victory on Sunday afternoon with a go-ahead home run in the eighth inning, helping them take three of four from the Royals at the Coliseum. The solo homer off right-hander Jason Adam was Chapman's 10th of the season and followed a spectacular game-changing defensive play by Marcus Semien in the top half of the inning. The A's shortstop made a diving stop and nailed the potential go-ahead run at the plate to preserve a 2-2 tie.",
									"body" : "<p>OAKLAND -- Heroism comes in many forms. In baseball, on both sides of the ball. Together, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A2BD2B5293660FB1173A6\">Marcus Semien</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-01D8ECCF9F69D3E9FC7B1\">Matt Chapman</span>'s work turned the A's into winners on Sunday afternoon.</p><p>Chapman may have propelled them to a 3-2 victory with a go-ahead home run in the eighth inning to help them take three of four from the Royals at the Coliseum, but it was only because Semien's defensive doings put him in position.</p><p>The solo homer off right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7976D7BDB91692136A1AB\">Jason Adam</span> was Chapman's 10th of the season and followed a spectacular game-changing play by Semien in the top half of the inning. The A's shortstop made a diving stop on <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A86DB4585C3D45CB353AD\">Salvador Perez</span>'s sharp grounder and nailed potential go-ahead runner <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-71EB4680E8A3A35BA0FB0\">Whit Merrifield</span> at the plate to preserve a 2-2 tie.</p><p>\"That's a really good runner at third going on contact,\" A's manager Bob Melvin said. \"That's about as good a play I've seen him make since he's been here. To dive like that, get up and have to throw it off balance on the money like that, no legs underneath him \u2026 game winner.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-696B050B75268E575EE84\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141867783\">Video: KC@OAK: Semien dives, tosses Merrifield out at home</a></span></p><p>Lefty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEAF0DEE6AD40E74DA5BC\">Sean Manaea</span>, lifted with one out in the eighth, was denied a win but turned in an encouraging outing with two runs and six hits allowed after posting a 6.63 ERA in his previous seven starts. He didn't walk a batter and struck out six, pitching past the sixth inning for the first time since April 27.</p><p>Closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EA6E3BE35693BB6FB8BB7\">Blake Treinen</span> secured the final five outs, the first being the game's finest.</p><p>\"It was an incredible play,\" Treinen said. \"Chapman made a great swing, but that swing doesn't get us the win if Marcus doesn't make that play. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-5B280CB8A69F3D0902EA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/player/518960/jonathan-lucroy\">[Jonathan] Lucroy</a></span> and I were on the same page and we were trying to call a sinker there because he swung through a good one down the pitch before.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-892A51A637EF5A550FDBA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142166883\">Video: KC@OAK: Manaea K's 6 over 7 1/3 vs. the Royals</a></span></p><p>\"You figure with the sinker from Blake that the ball can come your way pretty quick,\" Semien said. \"Just reaction.\"</p><p>Lucroy's RBI single highlighted a two-run second inning for the A's, but the Royals were quick to match them, with help from the sun. Merrifield, awarded a double that fell in front of a blinded <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CEA2074211CEEBD9B5DB3\">Mark Canha</span> in left field, scored on a wild pitch, and Perez launched a game-tying homer with two outs.</p><p>By the time Chapman stepped to the plate in the eighth, the A's had squandered multiple scoring opportunities. Twice, they left the bases loaded. Then in the seventh, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1C733F07F13173D19B29F\">Dustin Fowler</span> used his speed to record an infield single and race all the way to third on an errant pickoff attempt, only to be left there after Semien popped out and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-20C940B34447AB12CCEA8\">Khris Davis</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-44ABE8B7288C4D59102B5\">Matt Olson</span> both whiffed.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0DE090A2C87A61162BBA4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141539483\">Video: KC@OAK: Chapman nabs Orlando with deep throw at third</a></span></p><p>\"You ease up just for a second after Davis and Olson,\" Melvin said, \"and Chapman can bite you like he did.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />The A's improved to 29-0 when leading after the eighth inning, after Treinen stranded a runner at third to end the game.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-CDFF7828935B02B2CDF86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142030283\">Video: KC@OAK: Treinen earns win with 5-out appearance</a></span></p><p>\"It's a funny game,\" Melvin said. \"It feels good, then it feels bad and the next thing you know it's good again. That's why you play all 27 and that's why you keep grinding on it. Now they're in a position in the last inning to tie it off a guy who's basically been spotless.\"</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />The same fan caught consecutive foul balls off the bat of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-EEC6944070EA265B950B0\">Chad Pinder</span> in the sixth inning.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-AF8113E8B8049BAEB73B1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142164183\">Video: Must C Catches: A's fan makes back-to-back grabs</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I thought he threw great today. That's the best we've seen him throw in a while. It's not always about the velo, but it's about the location and the life that he has on all his pitches. You were seeing some 92, 93s today. You were seeing some sliders that had a little higher velocity, changeups a little higher velocity.\" -- <i>Melvin, on Manaea</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The A's will enjoy an off-day Monday before resuming play Tuesday for the start of a three-game series with the Astros. Right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4AFD25AD6666299F2A88B\">Daniel Mengden</span> (6-5, 3.45 ERA) will be on the mound in the 7:05 p.m. PT opener at the Coliseum. Houston will counter with righty <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-6669C3AABD6369A1AED82\">Lance McCullers Jr.</span> (7-3, 3.94 ERA).</p>",

									"body" : "<p>WASHINGTON -- The Giants knew that they had to face <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B5D845A389A0EE19AABF\">Max Scherzer</span>. Ultimately, however, the Nationals confronted a more formidable opponent by having to oppose <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E6D5489CE13AD84D8E7B7\">Brandon Crawford</span>.</p><p>The Giants' shortstop, not the Nationals' pitching ace, loomed over the series finale at Nationals Park as if he were another D.C. monument. Crawford went 4-for-4, including a fourth-inning home run off Scherzer, to account for the scoring in San Francisco's 2-0 triumph.</p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EC7A4FC879CE357C2DF84\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/all-star/ballot\">VOTE: 2018 Camping World MLB All-Star Ballot</a></span></p><p>\"It was like he knew he had to be good. He stepped up,\" Giants manager Bruce Bochy said of Crawford, who was an All-Star in 2015 and is bidding to return to D.C. when the 2018 All-Star Game is played there next month.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5282457FF22ABFDE400B4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141982383\">Video: SF@WSH: Crawford charges, throws out Turner at first</a></span></p><p>The outcome gave San Francisco a 2-1 series victory over the National League East leaders and halted seven years of frustration here for the Giants, who entered this series having lost 17 of 22 games at Washington since the start of the 2011 season.</p><p>The Giants ended Scherzer's nine-decision winning streak. But they did nothing to overwhelm Scherzer (10-2) himself. He pitched almost flawlessly -- unless he was facing Crawford. The winner of the NL's past two Cy Young Awards yielded four hits in seven innings while walking three and striking out nine. But Crawford collected three of the hits off Scherzer, including a fourth-inning drive over the right-field barrier that followed <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FF026A883F738C0B0CB9\">Pablo Sandoval</span>'s leadoff walk.</p><p>Crawford said that Scherzer threw him the gamut of his deliveries, from fastballs to offspeed pitches, until he connected with a 2-2 slider. \"I just tried to shorten up and see the ball over the plate,\" said Crawford, who has eight home runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D8774B9492D7CBFC37CB8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141969283\">Video: SF@WSH: Posey nabs Taylor as he slides past second</a></span></p><p>Scherzer spoke with humility about facing Crawford. \"I threw good pitches to him,\" Scherzer said. \"He put great swings on them. He wins. I lose. It's as simple as that. He's hot. I have to be better than him. Today he was great. And tip your hat and move on.\"</p><p>Facing Nationals reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CA96E1DBD4F7E72EED48D\">Matt Grace</span> in the eighth inning, Crawford lashed his final hit, a double. The ball eluded Washington left fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0D2CB48596748A6B4BFBA\">Juan Soto</span> long enough to cause observers to wonder whether Crawford should have dashed toward third base in an attempt to record a cycle.</p><p>Said Crawford, \"Right when I hit it I was thinking about it, and I was running hard out of the box, and then I saw it curving pretty hard, so I thought it was going to go foul. I slowed up for a second -- which might have cost me a shot at the cycle. But I was a little disappointed in myself when I saw it bounce by him.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A4486D1E21D43E961BA6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953283\">Video: SF@WSH: Holland strikes out 4 over 5 scoreless frames</a></span></p><p>Crawford, who recorded his sixth career effort featuring four or more hits, also became the first Giant to amass at least three hits off Scherzer in a game. Moreover, Crawford joined Cincinnati's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-434F3160A979CA1009882\">Scooter Gennett</span> and Miami's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF772D023E3AFAE164899\">Martin Prado</span> as the only players to collect three or more hits off Scherzer in a game this season.</p><p>The Giants' pitching also contributed significantly. Starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9220F57D2902D463A1A8D\">Derek Holland</span> surrendered three hits in five innings before relievers <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-096809C9884ED117FB9B6\">Mark Melancon</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0189CF14C1ABB9E38D288\">Sam Dyson</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B044BAAF3986B432AE7BF\">Tony Watson</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B7FA499A68198D093D8A2\">Hunter Strickland</span> each worked an inning apiece.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0B1C3C68043A4F4B61F9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142210583\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland fans Adams, locks down 13th save</a></span></p><p>\"I knew coming into the game that I couldn't make any mistakes,\" said Holland (4-6).</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />This game's ninth inning marked the first time that Strickland and Washington megastar <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-438FF67AE1F17D825FAB5\">Bryce Harper</span> faced each other since their AT&T Park altercation on May 29, 2017. This time, Strickland never came close to throwing at Harper, who grounded out to Crawford.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-63CC3A387F5BAEF69D4A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142244783\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland retires Harper in the 9th inning</a></span></p><p>\"The past is the past,\" Strickland said. \"I think everybody's moved on from that. That's part of our job, to get whoever it is out. No matter if it's him or [Matt] Adams, they're all good hitters.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Sandoval, starting at first base, drew a pair of walks. That marked the first time he coaxed multiple walks in one game since Aug. 12, 2015, when he was in his first year with the Red Sox.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Like Washington, the previous stop on their three-city trip, the Giants haven't fared too well at Miami, posting a 3-6 record there in the previous three years. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-352D769B1B3BB61DBAFBB\">Madison Bumgarner</span> will get the first crack at reversing this trend, which should raise the Giants' hopes. However, Bumgarner has recorded only three quality starts in his seven previous outings against the Marlins. Miami will counter with left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B0F4CB473A8FDBB9CE692\">Wei-Yin Chen</span>, who's 1-3 with a 5.86 ERA.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Giants shortstop Brandon Crawford continued to make a strong case for his second All-Star Game appearance with a home run in a 2-0 victory over Max Scherzer and the Nationals.",
									"body" : "<p>WASHINGTON -- The Giants knew that they had to face <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B5D845A389A0EE19AABF\">Max Scherzer</span>. Ultimately, however, the Nationals confronted a more formidable opponent by having to oppose <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E6D5489CE13AD84D8E7B7\">Brandon Crawford</span>.</p><p>The Giants' shortstop, not the Nationals' pitching ace, loomed over the series finale at Nationals Park as if he were another D.C. monument. Crawford went 4-for-4, including a fourth-inning home run off Scherzer, to account for the scoring in San Francisco's 2-0 triumph.</p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EC7A4FC879CE357C2DF84\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/all-star/ballot\">VOTE: 2018 Camping World MLB All-Star Ballot</a></span></p><p>\"It was like he knew he had to be good. He stepped up,\" Giants manager Bruce Bochy said of Crawford, who was an All-Star in 2015 and is bidding to return to D.C. when the 2018 All-Star Game is played there next month.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5282457FF22ABFDE400B4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141982383\">Video: SF@WSH: Crawford charges, throws out Turner at first</a></span></p><p>The outcome gave San Francisco a 2-1 series victory over the National League East leaders and halted seven years of frustration here for the Giants, who entered this series having lost 17 of 22 games at Washington since the start of the 2011 season.</p><p>The Giants ended Scherzer's nine-decision winning streak. But they did nothing to overwhelm Scherzer (10-2) himself. He pitched almost flawlessly -- unless he was facing Crawford. The winner of the NL's past two Cy Young Awards yielded four hits in seven innings while walking three and striking out nine. But Crawford collected three of the hits off Scherzer, including a fourth-inning drive over the right-field barrier that followed <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FF026A883F738C0B0CB9\">Pablo Sandoval</span>'s leadoff walk.</p><p>Crawford said that Scherzer threw him the gamut of his deliveries, from fastballs to offspeed pitches, until he connected with a 2-2 slider. \"I just tried to shorten up and see the ball over the plate,\" said Crawford, who has eight home runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D8774B9492D7CBFC37CB8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141969283\">Video: SF@WSH: Posey nabs Taylor as he slides past second</a></span></p><p>Scherzer spoke with humility about facing Crawford. \"I threw good pitches to him,\" Scherzer said. \"He put great swings on them. He wins. I lose. It's as simple as that. He's hot. I have to be better than him. Today he was great. And tip your hat and move on.\"</p><p>Facing Nationals reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CA96E1DBD4F7E72EED48D\">Matt Grace</span> in the eighth inning, Crawford lashed his final hit, a double. The ball eluded Washington left fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0D2CB48596748A6B4BFBA\">Juan Soto</span> long enough to cause observers to wonder whether Crawford should have dashed toward third base in an attempt to record a cycle.</p><p>Said Crawford, \"Right when I hit it I was thinking about it, and I was running hard out of the box, and then I saw it curving pretty hard, so I thought it was going to go foul. I slowed up for a second -- which might have cost me a shot at the cycle. But I was a little disappointed in myself when I saw it bounce by him.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A4486D1E21D43E961BA6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953283\">Video: SF@WSH: Holland strikes out 4 over 5 scoreless frames</a></span></p><p>Crawford, who recorded his sixth career effort featuring four or more hits, also became the first Giant to amass at least three hits off Scherzer in a game. Moreover, Crawford joined Cincinnati's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-434F3160A979CA1009882\">Scooter Gennett</span> and Miami's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF772D023E3AFAE164899\">Martin Prado</span> as the only players to collect three or more hits off Scherzer in a game this season.</p><p>The Giants' pitching also contributed significantly. Starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9220F57D2902D463A1A8D\">Derek Holland</span> surrendered three hits in five innings before relievers <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-096809C9884ED117FB9B6\">Mark Melancon</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0189CF14C1ABB9E38D288\">Sam Dyson</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B044BAAF3986B432AE7BF\">Tony Watson</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B7FA499A68198D093D8A2\">Hunter Strickland</span> each worked an inning apiece.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0B1C3C68043A4F4B61F9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142210583\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland fans Adams, locks down 13th save</a></span></p><p>\"I knew coming into the game that I couldn't make any mistakes,\" said Holland (4-6).</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />This game's ninth inning marked the first time that Strickland and Washington megastar <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-438FF67AE1F17D825FAB5\">Bryce Harper</span> faced each other since their AT&T Park altercation on May 29, 2017. This time, Strickland never came close to throwing at Harper, who grounded out to Crawford.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-63CC3A387F5BAEF69D4A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142244783\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland retires Harper in the 9th inning</a></span></p><p>\"The past is the past,\" Strickland said. \"I think everybody's moved on from that. That's part of our job, to get whoever it is out. No matter if it's him or [Matt] Adams, they're all good hitters.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Sandoval, starting at first base, drew a pair of walks. That marked the first time he coaxed multiple walks in one game since Aug. 12, 2015, when he was in his first year with the Red Sox.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Like Washington, the previous stop on their three-city trip, the Giants haven't fared too well at Miami, posting a 3-6 record there in the previous three years. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-352D769B1B3BB61DBAFBB\">Madison Bumgarner</span> will get the first crack at reversing this trend, which should raise the Giants' hopes. However, Bumgarner has recorded only three quality starts in his seven previous outings against the Marlins. Miami will counter with left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B0F4CB473A8FDBB9CE692\">Wei-Yin Chen</span>, who's 1-3 with a 5.86 ERA.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Giants shortstop Brandon Crawford continued to make a strong case for his second All-Star Game appearance with a home run in a 2-0 victory over Max Scherzer and the Nationals.",
									"body" : "<p>WASHINGTON -- The Giants knew that they had to face <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4B5D845A389A0EE19AABF\">Max Scherzer</span>. Ultimately, however, the Nationals confronted a more formidable opponent by having to oppose <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E6D5489CE13AD84D8E7B7\">Brandon Crawford</span>.</p><p>The Giants' shortstop, not the Nationals' pitching ace, loomed over the series finale at Nationals Park as if he were another D.C. monument. Crawford went 4-for-4, including a fourth-inning home run off Scherzer, to account for the scoring in San Francisco's 2-0 triumph.</p><p>\u2022 <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-EC7A4FC879CE357C2DF84\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/all-star/ballot\">VOTE: 2018 Camping World MLB All-Star Ballot</a></span></p><p>\"It was like he knew he had to be good. He stepped up,\" Giants manager Bruce Bochy said of Crawford, who was an All-Star in 2015 and is bidding to return to D.C. when the 2018 All-Star Game is played there next month.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-5282457FF22ABFDE400B4\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141982383\">Video: SF@WSH: Crawford charges, throws out Turner at first</a></span></p><p>The outcome gave San Francisco a 2-1 series victory over the National League East leaders and halted seven years of frustration here for the Giants, who entered this series having lost 17 of 22 games at Washington since the start of the 2011 season.</p><p>The Giants ended Scherzer's nine-decision winning streak. But they did nothing to overwhelm Scherzer (10-2) himself. He pitched almost flawlessly -- unless he was facing Crawford. The winner of the NL's past two Cy Young Awards yielded four hits in seven innings while walking three and striking out nine. But Crawford collected three of the hits off Scherzer, including a fourth-inning drive over the right-field barrier that followed <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9FF026A883F738C0B0CB9\">Pablo Sandoval</span>'s leadoff walk.</p><p>Crawford said that Scherzer threw him the gamut of his deliveries, from fastballs to offspeed pitches, until he connected with a 2-2 slider. \"I just tried to shorten up and see the ball over the plate,\" said Crawford, who has eight home runs.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-D8774B9492D7CBFC37CB8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141969283\">Video: SF@WSH: Posey nabs Taylor as he slides past second</a></span></p><p>Scherzer spoke with humility about facing Crawford. \"I threw good pitches to him,\" Scherzer said. \"He put great swings on them. He wins. I lose. It's as simple as that. He's hot. I have to be better than him. Today he was great. And tip your hat and move on.\"</p><p>Facing Nationals reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CA96E1DBD4F7E72EED48D\">Matt Grace</span> in the eighth inning, Crawford lashed his final hit, a double. The ball eluded Washington left fielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0D2CB48596748A6B4BFBA\">Juan Soto</span> long enough to cause observers to wonder whether Crawford should have dashed toward third base in an attempt to record a cycle.</p><p>Said Crawford, \"Right when I hit it I was thinking about it, and I was running hard out of the box, and then I saw it curving pretty hard, so I thought it was going to go foul. I slowed up for a second -- which might have cost me a shot at the cycle. But I was a little disappointed in myself when I saw it bounce by him.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0A4486D1E21D43E961BA6\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141953283\">Video: SF@WSH: Holland strikes out 4 over 5 scoreless frames</a></span></p><p>Crawford, who recorded his sixth career effort featuring four or more hits, also became the first Giant to amass at least three hits off Scherzer in a game. Moreover, Crawford joined Cincinnati's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-434F3160A979CA1009882\">Scooter Gennett</span> and Miami's <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CF772D023E3AFAE164899\">Martin Prado</span> as the only players to collect three or more hits off Scherzer in a game this season.</p><p>The Giants' pitching also contributed significantly. Starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9220F57D2902D463A1A8D\">Derek Holland</span> surrendered three hits in five innings before relievers <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-096809C9884ED117FB9B6\">Mark Melancon</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0189CF14C1ABB9E38D288\">Sam Dyson</span>, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B044BAAF3986B432AE7BF\">Tony Watson</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B7FA499A68198D093D8A2\">Hunter Strickland</span> each worked an inning apiece.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-0B1C3C68043A4F4B61F9F\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142210583\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland fans Adams, locks down 13th save</a></span></p><p>\"I knew coming into the game that I couldn't make any mistakes,\" said Holland (4-6).</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />This game's ninth inning marked the first time that Strickland and Washington megastar <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-438FF67AE1F17D825FAB5\">Bryce Harper</span> faced each other since their AT&T Park altercation on May 29, 2017. This time, Strickland never came close to throwing at Harper, who grounded out to Crawford.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-63CC3A387F5BAEF69D4A7\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142244783\">Video: SF@WSH: Strickland retires Harper in the 9th inning</a></span></p><p>\"The past is the past,\" Strickland said. \"I think everybody's moved on from that. That's part of our job, to get whoever it is out. No matter if it's him or [Matt] Adams, they're all good hitters.\"</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Sandoval, starting at first base, drew a pair of walks. That marked the first time he coaxed multiple walks in one game since Aug. 12, 2015, when he was in his first year with the Red Sox.</p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />Like Washington, the previous stop on their three-city trip, the Giants haven't fared too well at Miami, posting a 3-6 record there in the previous three years. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-352D769B1B3BB61DBAFBB\">Madison Bumgarner</span> will get the first crack at reversing this trend, which should raise the Giants' hopes. However, Bumgarner has recorded only three quality starts in his seven previous outings against the Marlins. Miami will counter with left-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B0F4CB473A8FDBB9CE692\">Wei-Yin Chen</span>, who's 1-3 with a 5.86 ERA.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Behind the hot bat of infielder Max Muncy and a strong effort on the mound from Ross Stripling, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. Muncy homered in his third consecutive game, while Logan Forsythe and Enrique Hernandez also hit solo shots. 									"body" : "<p>LOS ANGELES -- In a season where several of the Dodgers' key players have been hampered by injuries, others continue to step up admirably in their stead.</p><p>Behind the hot bat of infielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-089FB68037C80FE98FCAA\">Max Muncy</span> and a strong effort on the mound from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-346CF28DB5A65D132898E\">Ross Stripling</span>, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. The Dodgers have now won seven of their last eight contests, placing them back in the thick of the race for the National League West, thanks to some unlikely names.</p><p>Stripling -- the 28-year-old right-hander elevated into the Dodgers' starting rotation in May after making a spot start in April -- was quality. He pitched 6 2/3 innings, relinquishing just two runs on two hits to the Braves' offense, which ranked tops in the National League in batting average entering the game.</p><p>Stripling (5-1, 1.65 ERA) completed his outing without dealing any walks, and struck out six batters. He took a perfect game into the fourth inning, before <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA48586079FD76F4A9FAD\">Ozzie Albies</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-947AF2755679C774793BA\">Freddie Freeman</span> each connected on solo home runs. Stripling bounced back, however, retiring each of the last nine batters he faced.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8C31165AE39E790CCD7B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142306983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Roberts discusses Stripling's big game</a></span></p><p>\"I was able to get off to a good start,\" Stripling said. \"I went through the lineup once I think [in] less than 30 pitches, so I was in a good spot, then had a 33-pitch fourth. Obviously, the two homers, then was able to limit it to that. After that, you know you're trying to get through that inning and settle down and [I] was able to do that. Went 6 2/3 and just give us a chance to win, which is what I was trying to do when I went out there.\"</p><p>The Dodgers have won in each of Stripling's last five starts. His performance Sunday was buoyed by Los Angeles' offense, which bounced back from a quiet night Saturday to post seven runs while collecting 10 hits.</p><p>Braves starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F07D4E665D02F4187439E\">Sean Newcomb</span> kept the Dodgers hitless through the game's first two innings, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E429B12B9261F6A8A489\">Logan Forsythe</span> led off the third with a solo blast to open the scoring. Los Angeles filled the bases to set up back-to-back RBI singles from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E87D96060B9E2D539DC9B\">Matt Kemp</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0FA39B41B19A62959098F\">Enrique Hernandez</span>, giving the Dodgers a three-run advantage. Newcomb managed to limit the outburst, however, ending the inning with back-to-back strikeouts of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1803E0AC70A0D57BBA981\">Yasiel Puig</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-48A9BB431CC7D43FD5BA8\">Cody Bellinger</span> to get out of the jam.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-23229682C74347EEB8886\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141257583\">Video: ATL@LAD: Forsythe lines a solo homer to left</a></span></p><p>\"We had a chance to put them away,\" Roberts said. \"Even Yasiel striking out I thought was a good at-bat. That whole inning I thought was the end of Newcomb. We stressed him the whole inning. He's a good young arm and it was good to see Logan put the good swing on him.\"</p><p>Newcomb's recovery allowed Albies and Freeman's homers to trim the Dodgers' lead to 3-2 in the top of the fourth, but the Dodgers responded in the bottom of the fifth. Muncy got hold of a first-pitch fastball from Newcomb, driving it out of the park -- 421 feet, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-CF3855D906085F5BBFB8B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> -- for a solo bomb, restoring the Dodgers' two-run advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FE355BF81FC13A6A0DDAE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141548483\">Video: ATL@LAD: Muncy launches a long solo home run</a></span></p><p>\"He had a good fastball going today,\" Muncy said of Newcomb. \"It was cutting a little bit. It looked like he had a good spin. I just got lucky to get one over the plate and got a hold of it.\"</p><p>Forsythe slotted an RBI ground-rule double into left field during the sixth to extend the Dodgers' lead to three, prompting Newcomb's exit from the contest. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D8AC4F4104AD455C85A84\">Chris Taylor</span> walked to load the bases, and Muncy walked to make the score, 6-2. Hernandez smashed a solo home run in the seventh to grow the lead to its fullest extent.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-60E6C57473CB0C88A3E86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141965183\">Video: ATL@LAD: Hernandez goes dead center for solo home run</a></span></p><p>With the victory, the Dodgers once again are one game above .500, improving to 33-32 overall and 6-2 this month. They've managed to do so without many of their injured starters returning, including third baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF1DEF94AAFC697A6F9BA\">Justin Turner</span>, who's been dealing with a wrist injury but was expected to start Sunday's contest. Instead, Roberts elected to rest Turner one more game, inserting Muncy, who rewarded him with 1-for-2 day at the plate, including a home run and two walks.</p><p>\"We feel good not to deploy J.T. when he's not 100 percent, to get other guys involved,\" Roberts said. \"It was a collective effort. Staying away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D08480AD0B453BE029A8\">Josh Fields</span> was a good thing. A lot of good things for us.\"</p><p>Following the weekend, the Dodgers are tied with the Giants for second place in the National League West, standing 2 1/2 games behind the first-place D-backs.</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Muncy swatted a home run for the third consecutive game with his solo blast in the fifth, marking the first time in his Major League career that he's strung together such a streak. It's the 12th time Muncy has gone yard this season -- a career high -- through 44 games; he hit 12 homers in 109 games at the Triple-A level last season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />As the Dodgers built a 3-0 lead in the third, Puig worked a full count against Newcomb, and after fouling a pitch off, licked his bat before stepping back into the batter's box. He then broke his bat in frustration heading back to the dugout following the next pitch after whiffing on a 93.4-mph fastball from Newcomb to end the at-bat with a strikeout.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-844BFDA4BE916BD54A3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141344983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Puig snaps bat over knee after strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I guess you could say that. It's just a good stretch for me. It's just one of those -- it's kind of how baseball goes. It's one of those stretches where it seems like there's a lot of pitches over the plate for me. I'm sure it won't be long before there's a stretch where it seems like everything is around the corner. That's just kind of how it goes. When you get in a stretch like this, you have to take advantage of it.\" <i>-- Muncy, on whether he's dialed in, having hit five home runs in nine games played in June</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F00C7C0F02FB6B6BDB80\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142510883\">Video: ATL@LAD: Stripling and Muncy discuss win over Braves</a></span></p><p>\"He's good. That's a legit curveball. It's got some bite and his fastball plays up. He seemed to have pretty good command of all his pitches. He made for some tough at-bats.\" <i>-- Braves catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4473A490C2ECEA90DAAB2\">Tyler Flowers</span>, on Stripling's performance</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Dodgers will receive a day off Monday before starting a two-game series against the Rangers on Tuesday. First pitch is scheduled for 7:10 p.m. PT. Los Angeles has yet to name a starter, while right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B17711FF64A6F6F06299D\">Bartolo Colon</span> is expected to start for Texas.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Behind the hot bat of infielder Max Muncy and a strong effort on the mound from Ross Stripling, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. Muncy homered in his third consecutive game, while Logan Forsythe and Enrique Hernandez also hit solo shots. The Dodgers have now won seven of their last eight contests, placing them back in the thick of the race for the National League West.",
									"body" : "<p>LOS ANGELES -- In a season where several of the Dodgers' key players have been hampered by injuries, others continue to step up admirably in their stead.</p><p>Behind the hot bat of infielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-089FB68037C80FE98FCAA\">Max Muncy</span> and a strong effort on the mound from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-346CF28DB5A65D132898E\">Ross Stripling</span>, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. The Dodgers have now won seven of their last eight contests, placing them back in the thick of the race for the National League West, thanks to some unlikely names.</p><p>Stripling -- the 28-year-old right-hander elevated into the Dodgers' starting rotation in May after making a spot start in April -- was quality. He pitched 6 2/3 innings, relinquishing just two runs on two hits to the Braves' offense, which ranked tops in the National League in batting average entering the game.</p><p>Stripling (5-1, 1.65 ERA) completed his outing without dealing any walks, and struck out six batters. He took a perfect game into the fourth inning, before <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA48586079FD76F4A9FAD\">Ozzie Albies</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-947AF2755679C774793BA\">Freddie Freeman</span> each connected on solo home runs. Stripling bounced back, however, retiring each of the last nine batters he faced.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8C31165AE39E790CCD7B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142306983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Roberts discusses Stripling's big game</a></span></p><p>\"I was able to get off to a good start,\" Stripling said. \"I went through the lineup once I think [in] less than 30 pitches, so I was in a good spot, then had a 33-pitch fourth. Obviously, the two homers, then was able to limit it to that. After that, you know you're trying to get through that inning and settle down and [I] was able to do that. Went 6 2/3 and just give us a chance to win, which is what I was trying to do when I went out there.\"</p><p>The Dodgers have won in each of Stripling's last five starts. His performance Sunday was buoyed by Los Angeles' offense, which bounced back from a quiet night Saturday to post seven runs while collecting 10 hits.</p><p>Braves starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F07D4E665D02F4187439E\">Sean Newcomb</span> kept the Dodgers hitless through the game's first two innings, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E429B12B9261F6A8A489\">Logan Forsythe</span> led off the third with a solo blast to open the scoring. Los Angeles filled the bases to set up back-to-back RBI singles from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E87D96060B9E2D539DC9B\">Matt Kemp</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0FA39B41B19A62959098F\">Enrique Hernandez</span>, giving the Dodgers a three-run advantage. Newcomb managed to limit the outburst, however, ending the inning with back-to-back strikeouts of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1803E0AC70A0D57BBA981\">Yasiel Puig</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-48A9BB431CC7D43FD5BA8\">Cody Bellinger</span> to get out of the jam.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-23229682C74347EEB8886\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141257583\">Video: ATL@LAD: Forsythe lines a solo homer to left</a></span></p><p>\"We had a chance to put them away,\" Roberts said. \"Even Yasiel striking out I thought was a good at-bat. That whole inning I thought was the end of Newcomb. We stressed him the whole inning. He's a good young arm and it was good to see Logan put the good swing on him.\"</p><p>Newcomb's recovery allowed Albies and Freeman's homers to trim the Dodgers' lead to 3-2 in the top of the fourth, but the Dodgers responded in the bottom of the fifth. Muncy got hold of a first-pitch fastball from Newcomb, driving it out of the park -- 421 feet, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-CF3855D906085F5BBFB8B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> -- for a solo bomb, restoring the Dodgers' two-run advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FE355BF81FC13A6A0DDAE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141548483\">Video: ATL@LAD: Muncy launches a long solo home run</a></span></p><p>\"He had a good fastball going today,\" Muncy said of Newcomb. \"It was cutting a little bit. It looked like he had a good spin. I just got lucky to get one over the plate and got a hold of it.\"</p><p>Forsythe slotted an RBI ground-rule double into left field during the sixth to extend the Dodgers' lead to three, prompting Newcomb's exit from the contest. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D8AC4F4104AD455C85A84\">Chris Taylor</span> walked to load the bases, and Muncy walked to make the score, 6-2. Hernandez smashed a solo home run in the seventh to grow the lead to its fullest extent.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-60E6C57473CB0C88A3E86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141965183\">Video: ATL@LAD: Hernandez goes dead center for solo home run</a></span></p><p>With the victory, the Dodgers once again are one game above .500, improving to 33-32 overall and 6-2 this month. They've managed to do so without many of their injured starters returning, including third baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF1DEF94AAFC697A6F9BA\">Justin Turner</span>, who's been dealing with a wrist injury but was expected to start Sunday's contest. Instead, Roberts elected to rest Turner one more game, inserting Muncy, who rewarded him with 1-for-2 day at the plate, including a home run and two walks.</p><p>\"We feel good not to deploy J.T. when he's not 100 percent, to get other guys involved,\" Roberts said. \"It was a collective effort. Staying away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D08480AD0B453BE029A8\">Josh Fields</span> was a good thing. A lot of good things for us.\"</p><p>Following the weekend, the Dodgers are tied with the Giants for second place in the National League West, standing 2 1/2 games behind the first-place D-backs.</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Muncy swatted a home run for the third consecutive game with his solo blast in the fifth, marking the first time in his Major League career that he's strung together such a streak. It's the 12th time Muncy has gone yard this season -- a career high -- through 44 games; he hit 12 homers in 109 games at the Triple-A level last season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />As the Dodgers built a 3-0 lead in the third, Puig worked a full count against Newcomb, and after fouling a pitch off, licked his bat before stepping back into the batter's box. He then broke his bat in frustration heading back to the dugout following the next pitch after whiffing on a 93.4-mph fastball from Newcomb to end the at-bat with a strikeout.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-844BFDA4BE916BD54A3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141344983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Puig snaps bat over knee after strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I guess you could say that. It's just a good stretch for me. It's just one of those -- it's kind of how baseball goes. It's one of those stretches where it seems like there's a lot of pitches over the plate for me. I'm sure it won't be long before there's a stretch where it seems like everything is around the corner. That's just kind of how it goes. When you get in a stretch like this, you have to take advantage of it.\" <i>-- Muncy, on whether he's dialed in, having hit five home runs in nine games played in June</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F00C7C0F02FB6B6BDB80\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142510883\">Video: ATL@LAD: Stripling and Muncy discuss win over Braves</a></span></p><p>\"He's good. That's a legit curveball. It's got some bite and his fastball plays up. He seemed to have pretty good command of all his pitches. He made for some tough at-bats.\" <i>-- Braves catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4473A490C2ECEA90DAAB2\">Tyler Flowers</span>, on Stripling's performance</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Dodgers will receive a day off Monday before starting a two-game series against the Rangers on Tuesday. First pitch is scheduled for 7:10 p.m. PT. Los Angeles has yet to name a starter, while right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B17711FF64A6F6F06299D\">Bartolo Colon</span> is expected to start for Texas.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Behind the hot bat of infielder Max Muncy and a strong effort on the mound from Ross Stripling, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. Muncy homered in his third consecutive game, while Logan Forsythe and Enrique Hernandez also hit solo shots. The Dodgers have now won seven of their last eight contests, placing them back in the thick of the race for the National League West.",
									"body" : "<p>LOS ANGELES -- In a season where several of the Dodgers' key players have been hampered by injuries, others continue to step up admirably in their stead.</p><p>Behind the hot bat of infielder <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-089FB68037C80FE98FCAA\">Max Muncy</span> and a strong effort on the mound from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-346CF28DB5A65D132898E\">Ross Stripling</span>, Los Angeles defeated the Braves, 7-2, at Dodger Stadium on Sunday, to claim its third straight series victory. The Dodgers have now won seven of their last eight contests, placing them back in the thick of the race for the National League West, thanks to some unlikely names.</p><p>Stripling -- the 28-year-old right-hander elevated into the Dodgers' starting rotation in May after making a spot start in April -- was quality. He pitched 6 2/3 innings, relinquishing just two runs on two hits to the Braves' offense, which ranked tops in the National League in batting average entering the game.</p><p>Stripling (5-1, 1.65 ERA) completed his outing without dealing any walks, and struck out six batters. He took a perfect game into the fourth inning, before <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DA48586079FD76F4A9FAD\">Ozzie Albies</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-947AF2755679C774793BA\">Freddie Freeman</span> each connected on solo home runs. Stripling bounced back, however, retiring each of the last nine batters he faced.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-8C31165AE39E790CCD7B8\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142306983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Roberts discusses Stripling's big game</a></span></p><p>\"I was able to get off to a good start,\" Stripling said. \"I went through the lineup once I think [in] less than 30 pitches, so I was in a good spot, then had a 33-pitch fourth. Obviously, the two homers, then was able to limit it to that. After that, you know you're trying to get through that inning and settle down and [I] was able to do that. Went 6 2/3 and just give us a chance to win, which is what I was trying to do when I went out there.\"</p><p>The Dodgers have won in each of Stripling's last five starts. His performance Sunday was buoyed by Los Angeles' offense, which bounced back from a quiet night Saturday to post seven runs while collecting 10 hits.</p><p>Braves starter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-F07D4E665D02F4187439E\">Sean Newcomb</span> kept the Dodgers hitless through the game's first two innings, but <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9E429B12B9261F6A8A489\">Logan Forsythe</span> led off the third with a solo blast to open the scoring. Los Angeles filled the bases to set up back-to-back RBI singles from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-E87D96060B9E2D539DC9B\">Matt Kemp</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0FA39B41B19A62959098F\">Enrique Hernandez</span>, giving the Dodgers a three-run advantage. Newcomb managed to limit the outburst, however, ending the inning with back-to-back strikeouts of <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-1803E0AC70A0D57BBA981\">Yasiel Puig</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-48A9BB431CC7D43FD5BA8\">Cody Bellinger</span> to get out of the jam.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-23229682C74347EEB8886\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141257583\">Video: ATL@LAD: Forsythe lines a solo homer to left</a></span></p><p>\"We had a chance to put them away,\" Roberts said. \"Even Yasiel striking out I thought was a good at-bat. That whole inning I thought was the end of Newcomb. We stressed him the whole inning. He's a good young arm and it was good to see Logan put the good swing on him.\"</p><p>Newcomb's recovery allowed Albies and Freeman's homers to trim the Dodgers' lead to 3-2 in the top of the fourth, but the Dodgers responded in the bottom of the fifth. Muncy got hold of a first-pitch fastball from Newcomb, driving it out of the park -- 421 feet, according to <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-CF3855D906085F5BBFB8B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/topic/73955164\">Statcast\u2122</a></span> -- for a solo bomb, restoring the Dodgers' two-run advantage.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FE355BF81FC13A6A0DDAE\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141548483\">Video: ATL@LAD: Muncy launches a long solo home run</a></span></p><p>\"He had a good fastball going today,\" Muncy said of Newcomb. \"It was cutting a little bit. It looked like he had a good spin. I just got lucky to get one over the plate and got a hold of it.\"</p><p>Forsythe slotted an RBI ground-rule double into left field during the sixth to extend the Dodgers' lead to three, prompting Newcomb's exit from the contest. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D8AC4F4104AD455C85A84\">Chris Taylor</span> walked to load the bases, and Muncy walked to make the score, 6-2. Hernandez smashed a solo home run in the seventh to grow the lead to its fullest extent.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-60E6C57473CB0C88A3E86\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141965183\">Video: ATL@LAD: Hernandez goes dead center for solo home run</a></span></p><p>With the victory, the Dodgers once again are one game above .500, improving to 33-32 overall and 6-2 this month. They've managed to do so without many of their injured starters returning, including third baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-BF1DEF94AAFC697A6F9BA\">Justin Turner</span>, who's been dealing with a wrist injury but was expected to start Sunday's contest. Instead, Roberts elected to rest Turner one more game, inserting Muncy, who rewarded him with 1-for-2 day at the plate, including a home run and two walks.</p><p>\"We feel good not to deploy J.T. when he's not 100 percent, to get other guys involved,\" Roberts said. \"It was a collective effort. Staying away from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D08480AD0B453BE029A8\">Josh Fields</span> was a good thing. A lot of good things for us.\"</p><p>Following the weekend, the Dodgers are tied with the Giants for second place in the National League West, standing 2 1/2 games behind the first-place D-backs.</p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Muncy swatted a home run for the third consecutive game with his solo blast in the fifth, marking the first time in his Major League career that he's strung together such a streak. It's the 12th time Muncy has gone yard this season -- a career high -- through 44 games; he hit 12 homers in 109 games at the Triple-A level last season.</p><p><b>YOU GOTTA SEE THIS</b><br />As the Dodgers built a 3-0 lead in the third, Puig worked a full count against Newcomb, and after fouling a pitch off, licked his bat before stepping back into the batter's box. He then broke his bat in frustration heading back to the dugout following the next pitch after whiffing on a 93.4-mph fastball from Newcomb to end the at-bat with a strikeout.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-844BFDA4BE916BD54A3AA\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2141344983\">Video: ATL@LAD: Puig snaps bat over knee after strikeout</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"I guess you could say that. It's just a good stretch for me. It's just one of those -- it's kind of how baseball goes. It's one of those stretches where it seems like there's a lot of pitches over the plate for me. I'm sure it won't be long before there's a stretch where it seems like everything is around the corner. That's just kind of how it goes. When you get in a stretch like this, you have to take advantage of it.\" <i>-- Muncy, on whether he's dialed in, having hit five home runs in nine games played in June</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-9F00C7C0F02FB6B6BDB80\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142510883\">Video: ATL@LAD: Stripling and Muncy discuss win over Braves</a></span></p><p>\"He's good. That's a legit curveball. It's got some bite and his fastball plays up. He seemed to have pretty good command of all his pitches. He made for some tough at-bats.\" <i>-- Braves catcher <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-4473A490C2ECEA90DAAB2\">Tyler Flowers</span>, on Stripling's performance</i></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Dodgers will receive a day off Monday before starting a two-game series against the Rangers on Tuesday. First pitch is scheduled for 7:10 p.m. PT. Los Angeles has yet to name a starter, while right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-B17711FF64A6F6F06299D\">Bartolo Colon</span> is expected to start for Texas.</p>",

									"blurb" : "Todd Frazier's two-run homer and a combined shutout led by Seth Lugo sent the Mets to a 2-0 win over the Yankees on Sunday at Citi Field, putting an end to the Mets' eight-game losing streak, their longest skid in 14 years. Luis Severino struck out seven in five innings, but the Yanks' ace took his first loss in two months.",
									"body" : "<p>NEW YORK -- The Mets arrived at Citi Field on Sunday facing an unenviable ultimatum: defeat <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91EE07D52D132C0291AA9\">Luis Severino</span>, an early American League Cy Young Award candidate, or cap a winless homestand with their ninth straight loss. Increasing the degree of difficulty was the fact that their own starter, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-463C9F3509B4B3CE21890\">Seth Lugo</span>, was stretched out only enough to give them approximately 80 pitches.</p><p>On paper, it was a mismatch. But baseball is not played on paper, as Lugo, a former 34th-round Draft pick who has made a career of beating odds, rightly knows. Giving the Mets more than they could have hoped considering his pitch restrictions, Lugo blanked Major League Baseball's top-ranked offense for six innings, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8AE1C4637E3977ED139C\">Todd Frazier</span> provided all the offense in a 2-0 win over the Yankees. That snapped the Mets' longest losing streak in 14 years.</p><p>In 14 starts, Severino has allowed just five homers. The fifth of them came after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DCEC566E79614AE22F599\">Jose Reyes</span> singled in the fifth inning, as Frazier gave the Mets the lead against his former club.</p><p>\"One of those sliders that he threw just hung up a little bit longer,\" Frazier said. \"With him, he's dominant, so when you get a pitch like that you have to drive it.\"</p><p>Arguably Frazier's most famous home run during his time with the Yankees came at Citi Field last September during a series against the Rays that was moved to Queens because of Hurricane Irma. A Mets fan responded with a <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-FBD4128927E1E68A54A81\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/cut4/mets-fan-gary-dunaier-gave-yankees-thumbs-down-at-citi-field/c-254604636\">thumbs-down gesture</a></span> that became a trademark for the Yankees during their unexpected postseason run.</p><p>Frazier's home run Sunday elicited a different reaction from Mets fans, and was more than enough with Lugo dealing.</p><p>\"Lugo set the tone today,\" Mets reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-072340E8F68E6230FB595\">Robert Gsellman</span> said.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C081C1B31AD23306729BC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143177983\">Video: NYY@NYM: Lugo strikes out 8 over 6 strong frames</a></span></p><p>After allowing two-out singles in the first and second innings, Lugo retired the final 13 batters he faced. With a pair of relievers warm in the sixth inning, Lugo induced a popup from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AFEABC74E014E1FDCA189\">Gleyber Torres</span> and a flyout from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8C03099B0BF7559E4CC8B\">Brett Gardner</span>, then froze reigning National League MVP <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CAD830A007BF99AE22588\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> with a 95 mph sinker on his 84th and final pitch.</p><p>\"He wanted to go back out and we needed him to back out,\" Mets manager Mickey Callaway said of the sixth. \"That's how you do something special.\"</p><p>In so doing, Lugo lowered his ERA to 1.77 -- fourth among big leaguers with at least 40 innings pitched. The reigning AL and NL Cy Young Award winners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-803EDA85AD6E2152498B9\">Corey Kluber</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-261F79B544B15F18D90BC\">Max Scherzer</span>, are fifth and sixth.</p><p>After Lugo departed, the team leaned on two shutout relief innings from Gsellman and one from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-910E582093166C1D0DF80\">Anthony Swarzak</span> to complete their first win since May 30.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-682906AC7B7E242CFC883\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143381183\">Video: NYY@NYM: Gsellman gets six big outs in relief</a></span></p><p>Stopping short of calling it \"a now-or-never situation,\" Callaway nonetheless harped on the importance of the win for a Mets team that had lost 10 consecutive games at Citi Field. Lugo's role in the slump-busting victory was not lost on the manager, who hinted that he may have earned a more permanent stay in the rotation, even after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-57FF4186B72441359A28C\">Noah Syndergaard</span> returns from the disabled list.</p><p>The Mets will make those decisions in the weeks to come. For now, with a 10-game road trip looming, the Mets were happy to take a rare happy flight to Atlanta.</p><p>\"We've got to get the ball rolling,\" Lugo said. \"Against a team like that, one of the best teams in the league, hopefully that's the momentum we need.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />With regular closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9636866E27CE8589EBCAF\">Jeurys Familia</span> and setup man <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0651D7AAA332194B08DBE\">AJ Ramos</span> both on the disabled list, the Mets had to find a way to piece together the game's final nine outs. Gsellman pitched the seventh and, after a brief conversation with Callaway, returned for the eighth. That left Swarzak as the obvious candidate to face the heart of the Yankees' batting order in the ninth.</p><p>Recently returned from the DL himself, Swarzak struck out Stanton, walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A158381332191727F40AB\">Greg Bird</span> then induced a line-drive double play that <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D115BFFC746C4DE901B1\">Gary Sanchez</span> hit right into Frazier's glove.</p><p>\"With [Familia] being out, it just creates opportunity for everybody else,\" Swarzak said. \"I got the ball tonight in the ninth. I don't know if that's going to be the case on Tuesday. But if it is, I'll be ready to go.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-672CC221DCD193EEA0093\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143278283\">Video: NYY@NYM: Swarzak gets game-ending DP for 1st save</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Mets starting pitchers posted a 2.16 ERA over the team's eight-game losing streak, something that hadn't happened in 99 years. The last MLB team with an ERA that low over an eight-game stretch of losses was the 1919 Senators, who posted a 1.73 mark.</p><p><b>FROM THE TRAINER'S ROOM</b><br />Mets second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D7ECF91124B8871B9D484\">Asdrubal Cabrera</span> departed after three innings due to a sore left hamstring, but the team was relatively unconcerned about it after the game. Cabrera didn't travel with the Mets to Atlanta, staying back in New York to undergo tests. Still, the team does not consider it a potential DL situation.</p><p>\"He felt like he could have kept on going but he didn't want it to get worse,\" Callaway said. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-6A8D9E562B7D9BCC22487\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/mets/news/asdrubal-cabrera-leaves-with-apparent-injury/c-280706746\">More ></a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-3D725B01FB7B9FA90E387\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142937783\">Video: NYY@NYM: Cabrera injures leg swinging, later exits</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Tonight was just a good night for the team here. We needed that win. Every game's important. Fans needed that win. The stadium was definitely rocking tonight. It's been rocking all weekend, and I think the fans deserved that one.\" <i>--Swarzak</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-44257D2BB1EB83445748B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143535483\">Video: NYY@NYM: Mets on shutout victory over the Yankees</a></span></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />Reyes' season-long issues continued in the eighth inning. With a runner on first base and one out, pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-97EFEDD8F2A074CEAAE88\">Aaron Judge</span> hit a routine grounder to shortstop. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3E9C3D0C2A9A1151B7B88\">Amed Rosario</span> fielded and fired to second base, where Reyes straddled the bag without actually touching it as he threw well wide of first base, allowing Judge to reach safely.</p><p>Although umpires initially ruled <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-39AC0A81B17950CF2D2B5\">Miguel Andujar</span> out at second, a replay review overturned that call, sticking Reyes with a fielding error and a throwing error on the same play. Reyes' only solace was that Gsellman retired the next two batters without issue, preserving a two-run lead in spite of the gaffe.</p><p>\"I just missed the base,\" Reyes said. \"In that situation, I have to touch the base and make the double play. But Gsellman picked me up. That's what teammates do. We pick each other up.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FCFD60AF5972635E239A1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143202083\">Video: NYY@NYM: Judge safe on Reyes' errors after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Mets will put their Citi Field struggles behind them when they embark on a 10-game, three-city road trip beginning Tuesday in Atlanta. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AEC432518E3CF5FDE4FB5\">Zack Wheeler</span> will start the 7:35 p.m. ET opener of that two-game set at SunTrust Park, opposite right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5A9C312E1F012AE978784\">Mike Foltynewicz</span>.</p>",

									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Todd Frazier's two-run homer and a combined shutout led by Seth Lugo sent the Mets to a 2-0 win over the Yankees on Sunday at Citi Field, putting an end to the Mets' eight-game losing streak, their longest skid in 14 years. Luis Severino struck out seven in five innings, but the Yanks' ace took his first loss in two months.",
									"body" : "<p>NEW YORK -- The Mets arrived at Citi Field on Sunday facing an unenviable ultimatum: defeat <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91EE07D52D132C0291AA9\">Luis Severino</span>, an early American League Cy Young Award candidate, or cap a winless homestand with their ninth straight loss. Increasing the degree of difficulty was the fact that their own starter, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-463C9F3509B4B3CE21890\">Seth Lugo</span>, was stretched out only enough to give them approximately 80 pitches.</p><p>On paper, it was a mismatch. But baseball is not played on paper, as Lugo, a former 34th-round Draft pick who has made a career of beating odds, rightly knows. Giving the Mets more than they could have hoped considering his pitch restrictions, Lugo blanked Major League Baseball's top-ranked offense for six innings, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8AE1C4637E3977ED139C\">Todd Frazier</span> provided all the offense in a 2-0 win over the Yankees. That snapped the Mets' longest losing streak in 14 years.</p><p>In 14 starts, Severino has allowed just five homers. The fifth of them came after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DCEC566E79614AE22F599\">Jose Reyes</span> singled in the fifth inning, as Frazier gave the Mets the lead against his former club.</p><p>\"One of those sliders that he threw just hung up a little bit longer,\" Frazier said. \"With him, he's dominant, so when you get a pitch like that you have to drive it.\"</p><p>Arguably Frazier's most famous home run during his time with the Yankees came at Citi Field last September during a series against the Rays that was moved to Queens because of Hurricane Irma. A Mets fan responded with a <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-FBD4128927E1E68A54A81\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/cut4/mets-fan-gary-dunaier-gave-yankees-thumbs-down-at-citi-field/c-254604636\">thumbs-down gesture</a></span> that became a trademark for the Yankees during their unexpected postseason run.</p><p>Frazier's home run Sunday elicited a different reaction from Mets fans, and was more than enough with Lugo dealing.</p><p>\"Lugo set the tone today,\" Mets reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-072340E8F68E6230FB595\">Robert Gsellman</span> said.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C081C1B31AD23306729BC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143177983\">Video: NYY@NYM: Lugo strikes out 8 over 6 strong frames</a></span></p><p>After allowing two-out singles in the first and second innings, Lugo retired the final 13 batters he faced. With a pair of relievers warm in the sixth inning, Lugo induced a popup from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AFEABC74E014E1FDCA189\">Gleyber Torres</span> and a flyout from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8C03099B0BF7559E4CC8B\">Brett Gardner</span>, then froze reigning National League MVP <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CAD830A007BF99AE22588\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> with a 95 mph sinker on his 84th and final pitch.</p><p>\"He wanted to go back out and we needed him to back out,\" Mets manager Mickey Callaway said of the sixth. \"That's how you do something special.\"</p><p>In so doing, Lugo lowered his ERA to 1.77 -- fourth among big leaguers with at least 40 innings pitched. The reigning AL and NL Cy Young Award winners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-803EDA85AD6E2152498B9\">Corey Kluber</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-261F79B544B15F18D90BC\">Max Scherzer</span>, are fifth and sixth.</p><p>After Lugo departed, the team leaned on two shutout relief innings from Gsellman and one from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-910E582093166C1D0DF80\">Anthony Swarzak</span> to complete their first win since May 30.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-682906AC7B7E242CFC883\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143381183\">Video: NYY@NYM: Gsellman gets six big outs in relief</a></span></p><p>Stopping short of calling it \"a now-or-never situation,\" Callaway nonetheless harped on the importance of the win for a Mets team that had lost 10 consecutive games at Citi Field. Lugo's role in the slump-busting victory was not lost on the manager, who hinted that he may have earned a more permanent stay in the rotation, even after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-57FF4186B72441359A28C\">Noah Syndergaard</span> returns from the disabled list.</p><p>The Mets will make those decisions in the weeks to come. For now, with a 10-game road trip looming, the Mets were happy to take a rare happy flight to Atlanta.</p><p>\"We've got to get the ball rolling,\" Lugo said. \"Against a team like that, one of the best teams in the league, hopefully that's the momentum we need.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />With regular closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9636866E27CE8589EBCAF\">Jeurys Familia</span> and setup man <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0651D7AAA332194B08DBE\">AJ Ramos</span> both on the disabled list, the Mets had to find a way to piece together the game's final nine outs. Gsellman pitched the seventh and, after a brief conversation with Callaway, returned for the eighth. That left Swarzak as the obvious candidate to face the heart of the Yankees' batting order in the ninth.</p><p>Recently returned from the DL himself, Swarzak struck out Stanton, walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A158381332191727F40AB\">Greg Bird</span> then induced a line-drive double play that <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D115BFFC746C4DE901B1\">Gary Sanchez</span> hit right into Frazier's glove.</p><p>\"With [Familia] being out, it just creates opportunity for everybody else,\" Swarzak said. \"I got the ball tonight in the ninth. I don't know if that's going to be the case on Tuesday. But if it is, I'll be ready to go.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-672CC221DCD193EEA0093\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143278283\">Video: NYY@NYM: Swarzak gets game-ending DP for 1st save</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Mets starting pitchers posted a 2.16 ERA over the team's eight-game losing streak, something that hadn't happened in 99 years. The last MLB team with an ERA that low over an eight-game stretch of losses was the 1919 Senators, who posted a 1.73 mark.</p><p><b>FROM THE TRAINER'S ROOM</b><br />Mets second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D7ECF91124B8871B9D484\">Asdrubal Cabrera</span> departed after three innings due to a sore left hamstring, but the team was relatively unconcerned about it after the game. Cabrera didn't travel with the Mets to Atlanta, staying back in New York to undergo tests. Still, the team does not consider it a potential DL situation.</p><p>\"He felt like he could have kept on going but he didn't want it to get worse,\" Callaway said. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-6A8D9E562B7D9BCC22487\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/mets/news/asdrubal-cabrera-leaves-with-apparent-injury/c-280706746\">More ></a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-3D725B01FB7B9FA90E387\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142937783\">Video: NYY@NYM: Cabrera injures leg swinging, later exits</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Tonight was just a good night for the team here. We needed that win. Every game's important. Fans needed that win. The stadium was definitely rocking tonight. It's been rocking all weekend, and I think the fans deserved that one.\" <i>--Swarzak</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-44257D2BB1EB83445748B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143535483\">Video: NYY@NYM: Mets on shutout victory over the Yankees</a></span></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />Reyes' season-long issues continued in the eighth inning. With a runner on first base and one out, pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-97EFEDD8F2A074CEAAE88\">Aaron Judge</span> hit a routine grounder to shortstop. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3E9C3D0C2A9A1151B7B88\">Amed Rosario</span> fielded and fired to second base, where Reyes straddled the bag without actually touching it as he threw well wide of first base, allowing Judge to reach safely.</p><p>Although umpires initially ruled <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-39AC0A81B17950CF2D2B5\">Miguel Andujar</span> out at second, a replay review overturned that call, sticking Reyes with a fielding error and a throwing error on the same play. Reyes' only solace was that Gsellman retired the next two batters without issue, preserving a two-run lead in spite of the gaffe.</p><p>\"I just missed the base,\" Reyes said. \"In that situation, I have to touch the base and make the double play. But Gsellman picked me up. That's what teammates do. We pick each other up.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FCFD60AF5972635E239A1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143202083\">Video: NYY@NYM: Judge safe on Reyes' errors after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Mets will put their Citi Field struggles behind them when they embark on a 10-game, three-city road trip beginning Tuesday in Atlanta. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AEC432518E3CF5FDE4FB5\">Zack Wheeler</span> will start the 7:35 p.m. ET opener of that two-game set at SunTrust Park, opposite right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5A9C312E1F012AE978784\">Mike Foltynewicz</span>.</p>",
