									"approval" : "This story was not subject to the approval of Major League Baseball or its clubs.",
									"blurb" : "Todd Frazier's two-run homer and a combined shutout led by Seth Lugo sent the Mets to a 2-0 win over the Yankees on Sunday at Citi Field, putting an end to the Mets' eight-game losing streak, their longest skid in 14 years. Luis Severino struck out seven in five innings, but the Yanks' ace took his first loss in two months.",
									"body" : "<p>NEW YORK -- The Mets arrived at Citi Field on Sunday facing an unenviable ultimatum: defeat <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-91EE07D52D132C0291AA9\">Luis Severino</span>, an early American League Cy Young Award candidate, or cap a winless homestand with their ninth straight loss. Increasing the degree of difficulty was the fact that their own starter, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-463C9F3509B4B3CE21890\">Seth Lugo</span>, was stretched out only enough to give them approximately 80 pitches.</p><p>On paper, it was a mismatch. But baseball is not played on paper, as Lugo, a former 34th-round Draft pick who has made a career of beating odds, rightly knows. Giving the Mets more than they could have hoped considering his pitch restrictions, Lugo blanked Major League Baseball's top-ranked offense for six innings, and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A8AE1C4637E3977ED139C\">Todd Frazier</span> provided all the offense in a 2-0 win over the Yankees. That snapped the Mets' longest losing streak in 14 years.</p><p>In 14 starts, Severino has allowed just five homers. The fifth of them came after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-DCEC566E79614AE22F599\">Jose Reyes</span> singled in the fifth inning, as Frazier gave the Mets the lead against his former club.</p><p>\"One of those sliders that he threw just hung up a little bit longer,\" Frazier said. \"With him, he's dominant, so when you get a pitch like that you have to drive it.\"</p><p>Arguably Frazier's most famous home run during his time with the Yankees came at Citi Field last September during a series against the Rays that was moved to Queens because of Hurricane Irma. A Mets fan responded with a <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-FBD4128927E1E68A54A81\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/cut4/mets-fan-gary-dunaier-gave-yankees-thumbs-down-at-citi-field/c-254604636\">thumbs-down gesture</a></span> that became a trademark for the Yankees during their unexpected postseason run.</p><p>Frazier's home run Sunday elicited a different reaction from Mets fans, and was more than enough with Lugo dealing.</p><p>\"Lugo set the tone today,\" Mets reliever <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-072340E8F68E6230FB595\">Robert Gsellman</span> said.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-C081C1B31AD23306729BC\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143177983\">Video: NYY@NYM: Lugo strikes out 8 over 6 strong frames</a></span></p><p>After allowing two-out singles in the first and second innings, Lugo retired the final 13 batters he faced. With a pair of relievers warm in the sixth inning, Lugo induced a popup from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AFEABC74E014E1FDCA189\">Gleyber Torres</span> and a flyout from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-8C03099B0BF7559E4CC8B\">Brett Gardner</span>, then froze reigning National League MVP <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-CAD830A007BF99AE22588\">Giancarlo Stanton</span> with a 95 mph sinker on his 84th and final pitch.</p><p>\"He wanted to go back out and we needed him to back out,\" Mets manager Mickey Callaway said of the sixth. \"That's how you do something special.\"</p><p>In so doing, Lugo lowered his ERA to 1.77 -- fourth among big leaguers with at least 40 innings pitched. The reigning AL and NL Cy Young Award winners, <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-803EDA85AD6E2152498B9\">Corey Kluber</span> and <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-261F79B544B15F18D90BC\">Max Scherzer</span>, are fifth and sixth.</p><p>After Lugo departed, the team leaned on two shutout relief innings from Gsellman and one from <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-910E582093166C1D0DF80\">Anthony Swarzak</span> to complete their first win since May 30.</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-682906AC7B7E242CFC883\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143381183\">Video: NYY@NYM: Gsellman gets six big outs in relief</a></span></p><p>Stopping short of calling it \"a now-or-never situation,\" Callaway nonetheless harped on the importance of the win for a Mets team that had lost 10 consecutive games at Citi Field. Lugo's role in the slump-busting victory was not lost on the manager, who hinted that he may have earned a more permanent stay in the rotation, even after <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-57FF4186B72441359A28C\">Noah Syndergaard</span> returns from the disabled list.</p><p>The Mets will make those decisions in the weeks to come. For now, with a 10-game road trip looming, the Mets were happy to take a rare happy flight to Atlanta.</p><p>\"We've got to get the ball rolling,\" Lugo said. \"Against a team like that, one of the best teams in the league, hopefully that's the momentum we need.\"</p><p><b>MOMENTS THAT MATTERED</b><br />With regular closer <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-9636866E27CE8589EBCAF\">Jeurys Familia</span> and setup man <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-0651D7AAA332194B08DBE\">AJ Ramos</span> both on the disabled list, the Mets had to find a way to piece together the game's final nine outs. Gsellman pitched the seventh and, after a brief conversation with Callaway, returned for the eighth. That left Swarzak as the obvious candidate to face the heart of the Yankees' batting order in the ninth.</p><p>Recently returned from the DL himself, Swarzak struck out Stanton, walked <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-A158381332191727F40AB\">Greg Bird</span> then induced a line-drive double play that <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-7D115BFFC746C4DE901B1\">Gary Sanchez</span> hit right into Frazier's glove.</p><p>\"With [Familia] being out, it just creates opportunity for everybody else,\" Swarzak said. \"I got the ball tonight in the ninth. I don't know if that's going to be the case on Tuesday. But if it is, I'll be ready to go.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-672CC221DCD193EEA0093\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143278283\">Video: NYY@NYM: Swarzak gets game-ending DP for 1st save</a></span></p><p><b>SOUND SMART</b><br />Mets starting pitchers posted a 2.16 ERA over the team's eight-game losing streak, something that hadn't happened in 99 years. The last MLB team with an ERA that low over an eight-game stretch of losses was the 1919 Senators, who posted a 1.73 mark.</p><p><b>FROM THE TRAINER'S ROOM</b><br />Mets second baseman <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-D7ECF91124B8871B9D484\">Asdrubal Cabrera</span> departed after three innings due to a sore left hamstring, but the team was relatively unconcerned about it after the game. Cabrera didn't travel with the Mets to Atlanta, staying back in New York to undergo tests. Still, the team does not consider it a potential DL situation.</p><p>\"He felt like he could have kept on going but he didn't want it to get worse,\" Callaway said. <span class=\"token token-hyperLink\" id=\"token-6A8D9E562B7D9BCC22487\"><a href=\"https://www.mlb.com/mets/news/asdrubal-cabrera-leaves-with-apparent-injury/c-280706746\">More ></a></span></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-3D725B01FB7B9FA90E387\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2142937783\">Video: NYY@NYM: Cabrera injures leg swinging, later exits</a></span></p><p><b>HE SAID IT</b><br />\"Tonight was just a good night for the team here. We needed that win. Every game's important. Fans needed that win. The stadium was definitely rocking tonight. It's been rocking all weekend, and I think the fans deserved that one.\" <i>--Swarzak</i></p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-44257D2BB1EB83445748B\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143535483\">Video: NYY@NYM: Mets on shutout victory over the Yankees</a></span></p><p><b>MITEL REPLAY OF THE DAY</b><br />Reyes' season-long issues continued in the eighth inning. With a runner on first base and one out, pinch-hitter <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-97EFEDD8F2A074CEAAE88\">Aaron Judge</span> hit a routine grounder to shortstop. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-3E9C3D0C2A9A1151B7B88\">Amed Rosario</span> fielded and fired to second base, where Reyes straddled the bag without actually touching it as he threw well wide of first base, allowing Judge to reach safely.</p><p>Although umpires initially ruled <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-39AC0A81B17950CF2D2B5\">Miguel Andujar</span> out at second, a replay review overturned that call, sticking Reyes with a fielding error and a throwing error on the same play. Reyes' only solace was that Gsellman retired the next two batters without issue, preserving a two-run lead in spite of the gaffe.</p><p>\"I just missed the base,\" Reyes said. \"In that situation, I have to touch the base and make the double play. But Gsellman picked me up. That's what teammates do. We pick each other up.\"</p><p><span class=\"token token-video\" id=\"token-FCFD60AF5972635E239A1\"><a href=\"http://m.mlb.com/video/v2143202083\">Video: NYY@NYM: Judge safe on Reyes' errors after review</a></span></p><p><b>UP NEXT</b><br />The Mets will put their Citi Field struggles behind them when they embark on a 10-game, three-city road trip beginning Tuesday in Atlanta. <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-AEC432518E3CF5FDE4FB5\">Zack Wheeler</span> will start the 7:35 p.m. ET opener of that two-game set at SunTrust Park, opposite right-hander <span class=\"token token-playerCard\" id=\"token-5A9C312E1F012AE978784\">Mike Foltynewicz</span>.</p>",
